Excessively noisy and overly reliant on genre clichÃ©s, The Art of War wastes its star's charisma on a ridiculous, convoluted plot and poorly edited action sequences.
Though the four actors are good together, the jokes are stale and not funny.
Julia Stiles and Heath Ledger add strong performances to an unexpectedly clever script, elevating 10 Things (slightly) above typical teen fare.
A sweet ensemble comedy about a high school reunion, 10 Years is well cast but unfortunately predictable and short on three dimensional characters.
A scattered mob movie that employs every mafia cliche and fails to establish an identity of its own.
Even though Jamie Foxx shines in Bait, the movie suffers from music video roots and a formulaic script that strains credibility.
Duets suffers from sloppy direction and stretches credibility. Also, the characters are uninteresting and it's hard to care about what happens to them.
Sally Field's directing debut suffers from an inconsistent tone, implausible script, and a protagonist that critics say is one of the most loathsome to come around in a long time.
Though Hackman and Freeman turn in solid performances, Under Suspicion moves at a plodding rate and has a disappointing ending.
Michael Caine shows up to collect a paycheck, and so does everyone else in this rote, middling remake.
The Contender wears its political heart on its sleeve, but strong performances and a solid screenplay help the end result add up to a gripping drama from either side of the aisle.
The Ladies Man joins the growing list of mediocre movies based on SNL skits. It just doesn't have enough material to last the length of the movie.
Though Kaminski's film is visually stylish, Lost Souls is just another derivative entry in the Apocalypse genre, with lackluster direction, unengaging characters, and no scares.
Though it has its funny moments, this remake is essentially a one-joke movie with too many flat spots.
Heartwarming, but over-the-top and too formulaic.
Malena ends up objectifying the character of the movie's title. Also, the young boy's emotional investment with Malena is never convincing, as she doesn't feel like a three-dimensional person.

With a reported budget of around 10 million, The Gift is obviously a labor of love for those involved. Unfortunately, the A-list cast can't prevent the movie from becoming a by-the-numbers whodunit with an ending that's all but unsatisfactory.

Soderbergh successfully pulls off the highly ambitious Traffic, a movie with three different stories and a very large cast. The issues of ethics are gray rather than black-and-white, with no clear-cut good guys. Terrific acting all around.
Despite a good performance by Orlando Jones, the movie is ruined by a ridiculous, messy plot and fails to generate laughs.
Though its subject matter is grim and may make viewers queasy, The Pledge features an excellent, subtle performance by Jack Nicholson.
This quirky little film about a gangster in therapy feels fresh and well-crafted.
While superbly acted and stylishly filmed, Hannibal lacks the character interaction between the two leads which made the first movie so engrossing.
A toned down Chris Rock fails to bring a limp script to life as the movie moves from one gag to the next.
Schmaltzy and manipulative, Sweet November suffers from an implausible plot and non-existent chemistry between its leads.
Often seen as a Waiting to Exhale with men, The Brothers is amiable. However, it feels superficial and somewhat of a retread.
Though the actors pour a lot of energy into their roles, Heartbreakers is too drawn out, and the romantic subplot doesn't blend well. Also, the con women aren't particularly sympathetic.
A light and predictable, if somewhat shallow, romantic comedy that's easy to sit through because of the charming leads.
L.I.E. is a well-acted and unsettling look at a boy's relationship with a pedophile.
Underdeveloped characters, silly plot dynamics, and obvious CG effects.

movie_title: Ace in the Hole (The Big Carnival)
critics_consensus: Spearheaded by an excellent Kirk Douglas, Ace in the Hole is an incisive and sardonic satire that, much like its opportunistic hero, never lets moral compunction get in the way of a good story.
There is too much hollow bloodshed in Brother, and the characters are stereotypically flat.
Though the earlier part of the movie suggested something more, the movie turns out to be nothing more than a schmaltzy romance.
While less offensive and more charming than recent gross-humored comedies, The Animal is still rather mediocre.
Director Reitman tries to remake Ghostbusters, but his efforts are largely unsuccessful because the movie has too many comedic misfires.
Sleek and shiny on the surface, The Fast and the Furious recalls those cheesy teenage exploitation flicks of the 1950s.
Pearl Harbor tries to be the Titanic of war movies, but it's just a tedious romance filled with laughably bad dialogue. The 40 minute action sequence is spectacular though.

movie_title: Time and Tide (Shun liu Ni liu)
The Road Home (Wo de fu qin mu qin)
critics_consensus: Beautifully filmed, The Road Home is a simple touching and tender love story.
This remake of Planet of the Apes can't compare to the original in some critics' mind, but the striking visuals and B-movie charms may win you over.
Though the movie treads familiar ground in the heist/caper genre, Robert DeNiro, Edward Norton, and Marlon Brando make the movie worth watching.
Heist didn't cover any new ground, but the cast and Mamet's expertise with witty banter make it worthwhile.
The Others is a spooky thriller that reminds us that a movie doesn't need expensive special effects to be creepy.
It may lack some of the depth and complexity of the play, but Mel Gibson and Franco Zeffirelli make a surprisingly successful team.
With its large cast and frantic comic pacing, Big Trouble labors for slapstick-style hilarity, but it never really gains steam.
Though well-acted, Sidewalks of New York generally comes off as a second-rate Woody Allen film. The characters seem self-absorbed, the problems trite.
Sloppily-made, amateurish, and scarce on laughs, The Wash can't compare to Richard Pryor's 1976 Car Wash.
Despite its timely subject matter, Collateral Damage is an unexceptional and formulaic action thriller.
Though it may not reach for any new artistic heights, The Count of Monte Cristo is an old-fashioned yet enjoyable swashbuckler.
Sluggish and flawed, this is a minor work in Herzog's career.
As far as westerns go, Texas Rangers is strictly mediocre stuff.
A solidly constructed drama, Iris is greatly elevated by the strength of its four lead performances.
The plot for Behind Enemy Lines is more jingoistic than credible, and the overload of flashy visual tricks makes the action sequences resemble a video game.
Though Lillard is uncannily spot-on as Shaggy, Scooby Doo is a tired live-action update, filled with lame jokes.
A cliched and silly pop star vanity project, Crossroads is strictly for Britney fans only.
Incoherent, silly, and unoriginal, The New Guy offers up the same old teen gross-out comedy cliches.
This Machine has all the razzle-dazzles of modern special effects, but the movie takes a turn for the worst when it switches from a story about lost love to a confusing action-thriller.
A heart-warming sports flick, The Rookie greatly benefits from understated direction and the emotional honesty Dennis Quaid brings to the role of Jim Morris.
Showtime starts out as a promising satire of the buddy cop genre. Unfortunately, it ends up becoming the type of movies it is satirizing.
As quirky as Being John Malkovich but not as funny, Human Nature feels too forced and unengaging.
A predictable police procedural that works better as a character study rather than a thriller.
The well-crafted, twist-filled Enigma is a thinking person's spy thriller.
Joshua is well-intentioned, but too heavy-handed.
Enough exploits the serious issue of spousal abuse to make an illogical, unintelligent thriller.
Driven by Pacino's performance, Insomnia is a smart and riveting psychological drama.
They fails to sustain the level of creepiness necessary to rise above other movies in the horror genre.
With its plot about child kidnapping and endangerment, Trapped is an exploitative thriller, more queasy than suspenseful.
Muddled and lacking the political context of the original, Swept Away offers further proof that Madonna can't act.
All or Nothing's depiction of the working-class can be depressingly bleak, but the performances are wonderfully true to life.
The thriller Femme Fatale is overheated, nonsensical, and silly.
Thoughtful and wonderfully acted, The Quiet American manages to capture the spirit of Green's novel.
In terms of the gangster genre, Empire's story is yet another tired retread.
Dizzyingly original, the loopy, multi-layered Adaptation is both funny and thought-provoking.
Roberto Benigni misfires wildly with this adaptation of Pinocchio, and the result is an unfunny, poorly-made, creepy vanity project.
Thanks to a strong cast of experienced actors and director Douglas McGrath's steady hand, Nicholas Nickleby is a worthy and respectful adaptation of the Dickens novel.
An all too familiar chase movie that's not worth the talents involved.
Thought not without its funny moments, Anger Management is ultimately stale and disappointingly one-note, especially considering its capable cast.
A suspenseful, gripping documentary that features an engaging cross section of American children.
A mixed bag of uneven tones that feels flat.
Mediocre skateboard stunts are padded by a half-baked plot and one-dimensional characters.
More gory than scary, Cabin Fever is satisfied with paying homage to genre conventions rather than reinventing them.
This cinematic treatment of Martin Luther's life is more dull than inspiring.
Dummy is a sweet family comedy that succeeds due to charming performances, even if the final product feels slightly undercooked.
Good Boy! should appeal to kids. Adults, however, might consider it a dog.
A grungy, disjointed, mostly brainless mess of a film, House of the Dead is nonetheless loaded with unintentional laughs.
A fascinating, poignant look at the cult of celebrity.
An expertly acted and directed Western. But like other Ron Howard features, the movie is hardly subtle.
A charming father-and-son tale filled with typical Tim Burton flourishes.
Its deliberately unfocused narrative may frustrate some viewers, but The Company finds Altman gracefully applying his distinctive eye to the world of dance.
Solid if far from definitive, this version of Peter Pan is visually impressive, psychologically complex and faithful to its original source.
Silly and noisy, Torque is stylish fun for the MTV crowd.
A talky, ponderous movie.
The movie borrows heavily from Risky Business, though Hirsch and Cuthbert are appealing leads.
More depth about the legendary outlaw would be welcome, but as it is, Ned Kelly is a reasonably entertaining Western.
Jack Black and Ben Stiller fail to wring laughs from a script that's essentially one extended poop joke.
A good cast fails to elevate this overly violent and by-the-numbers revenge flick.
A coming-of-age tale that's more cloying than affecting.
The Terminal transcends its flaws through the sheer virtue of its crowd-pleasing message and a typically solid star turn from Tom Hanks.
The magic is gone, leaving a dreary, generic action movie.
A political doc that methodically and effectively argues its case.
Lightning in a Bottle pays dazzling tribute to the blues by capturing its power and excitement through backstage interviews and performance footage.
Despite a strong performance by Queen Latifah, Beauty Shop is in need of some style pointers.
Grisly and cliched, audiences may feel they're being held Hostage.
This supposed family comedy staring the usually blameless Ice Cube and Nia Long has provoked most critics to write, "Is it over yet?"
Robert De Niro and especially Dakota Fanning have earned some praise for their work in Hide and Seek, but critics have called the rest of the film derivative, illogical and somewhat silly.

movie_title: The Private Lives of Elizabeth and Essex

critics_consensus: A predictable plot and cheesy special effects make Cursed a less-than-scary experience.
This highly derivative superhero coming-of-age flick is moderately entertaining, family-friendly fluff.
While visually arresting, Appleseed's narrative and dialogue pondering existentialism is ponderous, awkward, and clumsy.
A mindless adventure flick with a preposterous plot.
A raw and unsettling morality piece on modern angst and urban disconnect, Crash examines the dangers of bigotry and xenophobia in the lives of interconnected Angelenos.
This pointless remake of the classic TV series only offers generic characters and gags.
Loud, preposterous, and predictable, Stealth borrows heavily and unsucessfully from Top Gun and 2001.
Thanks to its creaky and formulaic script, The Skeleton Key is more mumbo-jumbo than hoodoo and more dull than scary.
With solid performances and tight direction from Wes Craven, Red Eye is a brisk, economic thriller.
Given the movie's premise, one would assume it's gritty and street-smart, but in reality it's a slave to stale cliches and formula.
Hellbent is proof that gay slasher films can be just as tedious and mediocre as straight ones.

A voodoo horror flick without the mojo, Venom is chock full of gory impalings of interchangeable teenage girls and hunky guys by an unstoppable zombie whose unimaginative rampage quickly lulls us to sleep.
Philip Seymour Hoffman's riveting central performance guides a well-constructed retelling of the most sensational and significant period in author Truman Capote's life.
Nine Lives is bolstered by a strong cast and features many insightful glimpses into the lives of women.
A passionate and concise cinematic civics lesson, Good Night, And Good Luck has plenty to say about today's political and cultural climate, and its ensemble cast is stellar.
An awkward blend of teen comedy and social commentary, Kids in America largely fails to provoke thought or laughter.
Fans of the stage musical may forgive Rent its flaws, but weak direction, inescapable staginess and an irritating faux-boho pretension prevent the film from connecting on screen.
This first person account of the first Gulf War scores with its performances and cinematography but lacks an emotional thrust.
Despite arresting visuals and strong lead performances, The New World suffers from an unfocused narrative that will challenge viewers' attention spans over its 2 1/2 hours.
Sure, it's another adaptation of cinema's fave Jane Austen novel, but key performances and a modern filmmaking sensibility make this familiar period piece fresh and enjoyable.
Despite a few laughs and good intentions, The Ringer is too predictable to really score the points it aims for.
Well-acted if monotonous drama about a transvestite prostitute in London during the 1970s.
Curious George is a bright, sweet, faithful adaptation of the beloved children's books.
Unfunny and unoriginal. In other words, a perfect piece of evidence for opponents of pointless movie sequels.

movie_title: The Promise (Master of Crimson Armor) (Wu ji)
critics_consensus: An incoherent plot and ridiculously obvious CGI effects doom this effort from the usually outstanding Chinese director Chen Kaige.
This fractured fairytale doesn't have the wit or animation quality to compete with the likes of the Shrek franchise.
As formulaic as sports movies get, this underdog story still triumphs on the strength of its inspiring story.
In an attempt to parody rom-com cliches, Date Movie ultimately makes a mockery of itself, with juvenile toilet humor and empty pop culture references.
A provocative and timely film that explores the military/industrial complex and the motivating forces that lead us to war.
This frothy, oddly bloodless film does a disservice to the colorful life of the real Casanova.
Overloaded with pop culture references, but lacking in compelling characters and plot, Doogal is too simpleminded even for the kiddies.
Strong performances and an inclusive approach to sexual awakening aren't enough to make Summer Storm a truly memorable coming-of-age story.
Gross-out comedy and true love make for an awkward mix in this clunky romance.
Another blue-collar inspirational feel-good British dramedy, On A Clear Day succeeds on the strength of lead actor Peter Mullan's performance and Gaby Dellal's competent direction.
In one of her best roles, Cheung gives a believable and arresting performance as a recovering addict.
Hampered by pretension and undermined by unlikable characters, London proves that the novelty of seeing actors play against type isn't enough to rescue a deeply flawed film.
Fueled by powerful work from a strong cast led by Cate Blanchett, Little Fish is a hard-hitting story worth watching -- and a major step forward for director Rowan Woods.
Evil's attempts to unpack the causes and effects of violence aren't always successful, but the well-acted end result still has an unsettling impact.
Whether you think this mentally ill cult musician is worthy of being called a "genius," this document of his life is crafted with sincere respect and is fascinating to watch.
See No Evil is packed with cliches from countless other teen slasher films, making for a predictable, scare-free waste of time.

Lavish imagery and a daring soundtrack set this film apart from most period dramas; in fact, style completely takes precedence over plot and character development in Coppola's vision of the doomed queen.

movie_title: Goal! The Dream Begins (Goal!: The Impossible Dream)
critics_consensus: Impressive sports action sequences are the highlight, as the run-of the-mill story invokes every known sports movie cliche.
Though Sleeping Dogs Lie treats its subject and characters humanely, it's unable to overcome the low-budget production and Bobcat Goldthwait's pedestrian directing.
A muddled sex-comedy that feels oddly sexless, The Oh in Ohio packs in too many ideas without establishing a clear identity or objective.
An agreeably familiar story with some welcome quirky twists, Christmas in the Clouds offers all the comforting entertainment its title suggests.
The Hoax is an enormously appealing film, thanks to the uniformly excellent performances and Lasse HallstrÃ¶m's zippy direction.
As the object of satire gets bigger the jokes become thinner, and Christopher Guest isn't as droll or insightful here than when he was lampooning smaller subjects.
The symbolism in this cinematic metaphor on conflicts in the Middle East becomes so overbearing that it's hard to care about the characters or their plight.
This coming-of-age film's young, attractive cast helps to mitigate the stultifying dialogue and uninspired direction.
Superhero Movie is not the worst of the spoof genre, but relies on tired gags and lame pop culture references all the same.
With animated sequences adding imaginative quirkiness to the mix, this movie about death and disaster is insightful, empathic, and more uplifting than one would think.

Despite best intentions from director Emilio Estevez and his ensemble cast, they succumb to a script filled with pointless subplots and awkward moments working too hard to parallel contemporary times.
A gritty, low-budget thriller, Cavite takes us on a heart-pounding ride through the seedy Filipino underworld.
Coastlines features solid lead performances, but is hindered by an unconvincing love triangle and scattered direction. Not up to the standard of Victor Nunez's previous directorial efforts.
A comedy that tackles outrageous subjects (pornography, transvestism, bisexuality and drug abuse) with both grace and mischievous glee.
With an exploitative style that seems more suited for TV shows like CSI, Trade's message about the reality of child exploitation is easily lost.
Flawed yet filled with finely detailed characters, Red Doors is a glimpse of the Asian-American experience that suggests great promise for writer-director Georgia Lee.
Though it has charm, Driving Lessons is a middling offering in the genre where the youngster coming of age meets a quirky senior who teaches valuable lessons about life.
Even if you know little about ballet, there is much to love about this documentary's captivating archival footage and its interviews with elderly former dancers who have much to share.
Dull and confusing execution makes this ghost story utterly forgettable and unintentionally funny.

Tactlessly morbid or remarkably sensitive? Deeply disturbing or viscerally fascinating? Critics are divided on Eric Steele's unique documentary on the Golden Gate Bridge, wonder of the modern world and notorious suicide destination.
At some point in the conversation, God must have asked for a subtler, deeper film.

Despite the presence of Halle Berry and Bruce Willis, Perfect Stranger is too convoluted to work, and features a twist ending that's irritating and superfluous. It's a techno-thriller without thrills.
Though not highly original, Vitus is slightly redeemed by its charm and compelling performances.
With a clever script and charismatic leads, Definitely, Maybe is a refreshing entry into the romantic comedy genre.

Wanted is stylish, energetic popcorn fare with witty performances from Angelina Jolie (playing an expert assassin), James McAvoy, and Morgan Freeman that help to distract from its absurdly over-the-top plot.
Silk contains a simple love triangle story but director Francois Gerard goes to painstaking lengths to turn it into a protracted and wearisome art film.
Featuring one of Robin Williams' most shtick-heavy performances, the broad and formulaic License to Wed wrings little out of its slightly creepy, unappealing premise.
A slew of talent is wasted in this contrived and overly sentimental Christmas film, which can't quite get the balance between slapstick humor and schmaltzy uplift.
It's derivative and its more ambitious aspirations don't amount to much, but Antibodies remains a reasonably diverting and well-made thriller.
Though made with great skill, Funny Games is nevertheless a sadistic exercise in chastising the audience.

Though at times formulaic and sentimental, Jane Austen Book Club succeeds on the strength of its likable ensemble cast. Even those not familiar with Jane Austen's work may find much to enjoy this lighthearted romance.
Lars and the Real Girl could've so easily been a one-joke movie. But the talented cast, a great script, and direction never condescends to its character or the audience.
Descent has the potential to make a statement about sexual violence, but falls flat by focusing on revenge rather than Rosario Dawson's emotional state.

movie_title: Kannathil Muthamittal (A Peck on the Cheek)

critics_consensus: Yet another film about a small town girl trying to make it in the City of Angels,  Hollywood Dreams' improvisation and absurdity tests viewers' patience.
The Final Season recycles clichÃ©s we've seen in countless other sports movies, making for an unoriginal and uninspiring addition to the genre.
A story of redemption held together with flashbacks, Take has moments of emotional intensity, but is ultimately undone by preachiness.
Featuring wonderful performances from Ben Kingsley and Tea Leoni, You Kill Me is a charming, funny take on the familiar inner-lives-of-hit-men premise.
Amu uses one woman's experiences to train a lens on a painful period in Indian history with heartbreaking clarity.
The Hunting Party is tonally awkward: its shifts from dark satire to serious political thriller create an uneven film, despite best efforts from its game leads.
Though cutely rendered, Alvin and the Chipmunks suffers from bland potty humor and a rehashed kids' movie formula.
The Express crosses the goal line as an inspirational sports drama, although fans of the genre will recognize many -- if not most -- of its clichÃ©s.
The Rape of Europa grapples with a subject that's vast and powerful enough to fill several films -- and emerges with a story as fascinating as it is infuriating.
This allegorical disaster film about society's reaction to mass blindness is mottled and self-satisfied; provocative but not as interesting as its premise implies.
A laborious, unfunny and implausible heist film.
Though it features a few scares and some creepy atmosphere, The Haunting in Connecticut ultimately relies too much on familiar horror cliches to achieve its goals.
Jennifer Venditti's doc Billy the Kid turns "special" into a double edged sword, forging a sharply honest film around a strangely enigmatic -- if awkward -- kid named Billy.

Angels and Demons is a fast-paced thrill ride, and an improvement on the last Dan Brown adaptation, but the storyline too often wavers between implausible and ridiculous, and does not translate effectively to the big screen.
It's stuffed full of Peter Jackson's typically dazzling imagery, but The Lovely Bones suffers from abrupt shifts between horrific violence and cloying sentimentality.
By turns fluffy and biting, this show biz comedy is given girth by comic heavyweight John Malkovich and made all the more charming by Emily Blunt.
Well cast and crisply directed, The Bank Job is a thoroughly entertaining British heist thriller.

movie_title: Zack and Miri Make a Porno
critics_consensus: Zack and Miri Make a Porno is a modest success for Kevin Smith, due in large part to the charm of Seth Rogen and Elizabeth Banks.
With few laughs and little romantic chemistry, Over Her Dead Body lacks the ingredients of a successful romantic comedy.
Despite a promising turn by newcomer Yara Shahidi, Imagine That is another pedestrian family comedy that squanders Eddie Murphy's comedic talents.
Ricky Gervais' consistently sharp performance and beautifully dry execution transform this otherwise mainstream comedy into an endearing, funny, and altogether snappy romantic comedy. With ghosts.
A pale imitation of the raunchy frat comedies of old, College aims low and misses.
Beautifully shot and well-acted, Changeling is a compelling story that unfortunately gives in to convention too often.

movie_title: Life is a Bed of Roses

critics_consensus: Less biting or offensive than Korine's earlier works, this frustratingly dull film still maintains the director's trademark odd beauty.
Hell Ride misses out on the rusting zeitgeist of the biker genre, sucking the glee from a saucy premise.
A disappointing melodrama focussing on the partition of India and Pakistan. Strange cross-culture casting doesn't help the pedestrian script and direction.
Despite its sharp cast and a few laughs, Smart People is too thinly plotted to fully resonate.
A taut, well-acted political thriller, State of Play overcomes some unsubtle plot twists with an intelligent script and swift direction.
Trumbo celebrates the life and work of blacklisted screenwriter Dalton Trumbo with measures of humor and sadness.
Employing multiple cinematic clichÃ©s and milking stale performances, Deal proves inadequate for even the lowly regarded poker movie genre.
Despite Jared Leto's committed performance, Chapter 27 fails to penetrate to mind of Mark David Chapman, John Lennon's killer.
Step Brothers indulges in a cheerfully relentless immaturity that will quickly turn off viewers unamused by Ferrell and Reilly -- and delight those who find their antics hilarious.
Noise starts with an interesting premise, but fails to build it into a cohesive whole.
An intelligent, adult, and provocative Philip Roth adaptation that features classy performances, Elegy is never quite the sum of its parts.

movie_title: Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs (Ice Age 3)
critics_consensus: Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs boasts some excellent animation -- in particular, the dinosaurs are wonderfully realized -- but its story is tired and monotonous.
It won't win many converts, but High School Musical 3 is bright, energetic, and well-crafted.

movie_title: Encounters at the End of the World
critics_consensus: Encounters at the End of the World offers a poignant study of the human psyche amid haunting landscapes.
Blessed with a good cast, Phoebe's heart is in the right place, but its execution is dicey.
Suitably grand and special effects-laden, The Wolfman suffers from a suspense-deficient script and a surprising lack of genuine chills.
Mike Leigh's latest partially-improvised film is a light-hearted comedy with moments that bite, and features a brilliant star turn by Sally Hawkins.
Though it's lengthy and doesn't always walk the line between schlock and kitschy homage successfully, Viva's lovely visuals and knowing humor are undeniable.
My Winnipeg is a charmingly irreverent 'docu-fantasy' from the unpredictable mind of Guy Maddin.
Space Chimps' cheap animation and overabundance of monkey puns feels especially dated in a post-Wall-E world.
Despite a noble effort from Dakota Fanning, Hounddog is overwrought, cliche-ridden and downright exploitative.
Smartly constructed by writer-director Gina Kim and brought to life by a strong cast led by Vera Farmiga, Never Forever is an unexpectedly engaging melodrama.
The warmth of traditional Disney animation makes this occasionally lightweight fairy-tale update a lively and captivating confection for the holidays.

movie_title: Cloudy With a Chance of Meatballs
critics_consensus: Quirky humor, plucky characters and solid slapstick make this family comedy a frenetically tasty time at the movies.
Julian Schnabel expertly captures the dark melancholy of Lou Reed's misunderstood concept album in this moving concert documentary.
Elegiac and personal, Patti Smith: Dream of Life paints an enduring and sometimes rough portrait of the titular chanteuse, complete with footage onstage and at home.
This thriller about a menacing cop wreaking havoc on his neighbors is tense enough but threatens absurdity when it enters into excessive potboiler territory.
Quarantine uses effective atmosphere and consistent scares to stand above the crop of recent horror films.
With Reprise, first-time director Joachim Trier effectively captures the spirit of young adulthood, and announces his arrival as a filmmaker to be watched.
While lushly photographed and politically suggestive, this soapy melodrama lacks emotional resonance.
My Name Is Bruce succeeds or fails based entirely upon the viewer's opinion of Bruce Campbell, an unreasonable burden for even the most accomplished actor.
Inconsistency and listless plot make this K-horror remake a less-than-frightening time at the movies.

movie_title: OSS 117: Le Caire Nid d'Espions (OSS 117: Cairo, Nest of Spies)
critics_consensus: This clever spy spoof plays politics and movie conventions for laughs and features a great turn by Jen Dujardin as a smarmy-suave nouveau-Bond.
This beautiful Israeli film is both a moving family drama and a potent examination of the trials of faith.
A searing debut by director Lance Hammer, this subtle and contemplative Mississippi set drama lingers long after its conclusion.
Alternately a sharp ensemble dramedy and a love letter to the titular city, Paris is uneven but often striking.
Fantastic Mr. Fox is a delightfully funny feast for the eyes with multi-generational appeal -- and it shows Wes Anderson has a knack for animation.
It's bogged down with an unfocused script and countless sports movie cliches, but The Perfect Game still manages to charm with its unabashed sweetness and a stirring final act.
It may not rank with Scorsese's best work, but Shutter Island's gleefully unapologetic genre thrills represent the director at his most unrestrained.
Overly serious and incomprehensibly edited, Ninja Assassin fails to live up to the promise of its title.
Recount deftly brings a controversial chapter of electoral history to dramatic life with a compelling cast, although some viewers may take issue with its conclusions.
Heavily reliant on stereotypes and shallow teen comedy clichÃ©s, I Love You Beth Cooper is a humorless affair that fails to capture the charm of its source novel.
Well-researched and swimming in scientific data, this global warming documentary offers some practical and wide-ranging solutions to our climate crisis.
A charismatic turn by star Matt Damon and a consistently ironic tone boost this quietly funny satire about a corporate whistle-blower.
While it's far better than it could have been, JosÃ© Padilha's RoboCop remake fails to offer a significant improvement over the original.
Despite a lavish and polished production, Dorian Gray is tame and uninspired with a lifeless performance by Ben Barnes in the title role.
Despite the best efforts of a strong cast, Nobel Son is over-plotted and self-consciously odd.
Though it uses a well-worn formula, 17 Again has just enough Zac Efron charm to result in a harmless, pleasurable teen comedy.
Dwayne Johnson brings the full force of his charm (and his appropriately pale chompers) to the title role, but flat direction and a committee-written script render The Tooth Fairy unacceptably dull.
It's burdened by a predictable, overly melodramatic story, but The Greatest benefits from strong performances by its talented cast.
Dark Streets is a film noir musical that's too gimmicky for its own good.

Matt Damon and Paul Greengrass return to the propulsive action and visceral editing of the Bourne films -- but a cliched script and stock characters keep those methods from being as effective this time around.
A lightweight and pithy Noel Coward adaptation with plenty of sparkle and fizz.

movie_title: Dear Zachary: A Letter to a Son About His Father
critics_consensus: Dear Zachary is a both a touching tribute to a fallen friend and a heart-wrenching account of justice gone astray, skillfully put to film with no emotion spared.
Technically and visually dazzling...
Me and Orson Welles boasts a breakout performance by Christian McKay and an infectious love of the backstage drama that overcomes its sometimes fluffy tone.
Unsettling and spine-chilling low-budget British horror, with effective and disturbing scares.

movie_title: The Last House on the Left
critics_consensus: Excessive and gory, this remake lacks the intellectual punch of the 1972 original.
Tense, nicely shot, and uncommonly intelligent, The Crazies is a horror remake that, unusually, works.

Although its story is perhaps too familiar and less complex than some might wish, 9 is visually spectacular, and director Shane Acker's attention to detail succeeds in drawing viewers into the film's universe.
While nowhere near as painful as it could have been, The Three Stooges fails to add fresh laughs to the Stooges' inestimable cinematic legacy.
An accomplished cast can't save a derivative suspense flick that manages to confuse and bore rather than thrill.
This Charles Darwin biopic is curiously dispassionate, but Creation contains some of director Jon Amiel's best work, and Paul Bettany's performance is not to be missed.

movie_title: Crips and Bloods: Made in America

critics_consensus: Despite some beautiful scenery, Tennessee can't extend its simple premise beyond typical independent road trip movie tropes.

movie_title: Four Flies on Grey Velvet (4 mosche di velluto grigio)

critics_consensus: Despite a strong cast, The Taking of Pelham 1 2 3 suffers under the excesses of Tony Scott's frantic direction, and fails to measure up to the 1974 original.
The inevitable Fatal Attraction comparisons aside, Obsessed is a generic, toothless thriller both instantly predictable and instantly forgettable.
Masterfully crafted by an experienced directorial hand, Katyn is a powerful, personal depiction of wartime tragedy.
Hugh Dancy's elegant performance as a man with Asperger's Syndrome elevates Adam, an offbeat but touching romantic comedy.
A fascinating, emotional, and frank confessional from Iron Mike that sheds a sympathetic light on one of boxing's most controversial icons.
Great performances by Clive Owen and The Boys save this melodrama from entering into the sappy territory it might have in less competent hands.
It doesn't take its terrific premise quite as far as it should, but Splice is a smart, well-acted treat for horror fans.
Despite fine work by an appealing cast, It's Complicated is predictable romantic comedy fare, going for broad laughs instead of subtlety and nuance.
Though decidedly one-sided, The Cove is an impeccably crafted, suspenseful expose of the covert slaughter of dolphins in Japan.

movie_title: 12:08 East of Bucharest (A fost sau n-a fost?)
critics_consensus: With a witty script full of satirical overtones and dry humor, 12:08 East of Bucharest is a thoroughly enjoyable Romanian comedy.
Mary and Max is a lovingly crafted, startlingly inventive piece of animation whose technical craft is equaled by its emotional resonance.
It isn't deep or groundbreaking, but what it lacks in profundity, Puss in Boots more than makes up for with an abundance of wit, visual sparkle, and effervescent charm.

movie_title: El BaÃ±o del Papa (The Pope's Toilet)
critics_consensus: An offbeat charmer, The Pope's Toilet is a humorous, well-crafted tale with plenty of heart and a poignant social message.
Stuffed with characters and overly reliant on uninspired dialogue, Eclipse won't win The Twilight Saga many new converts, despite an improved blend of romance and action fantasy.
Gruesome, explicit and highly controversial; Lars Von Triers arthouse-horror, though beautifully shot, is no easy ride.
Extract has some very funny moments and several fine performances, but the film feels slighter and more uneven than Mike Judge's previous work.
Its time-shifting narrative creates distracting casting problems, but ultimately, The Debt is a smart, well-acted entry in a genre that could use more like it.
A calm, charismatic performance from Robert De Niro nearly saves the movie, but ultimately, Everybody's Fine has the look and feel of a stereotypical Christmas dramedy.
Last Night doesn't opt for easy answers, but the framework and characters overall are too slight and plain to be compelling.
James Franco gives it his all as beat poet Allen Ginsberg, but Howl never develops enough of a focus to do his performance justice.
With Life During Wartime, Todd Solondz delivers an unexpected semi-sequel to Happiness in typically uncompromising fashion.
The Friends of Eddie Coyle sees Robert Mitchum in transformative late-career mode in a gritty and credible character study.
Its leads are likeable, but Remember Me suffers from an overly maudlin script and a borderline offensive final twist.
Critics say that despite a warm, well-meaning message about the importance of family ties, Uncle Nino is utterly corny and predictable.
What Goes Up squanders the charisma of Steve Coogan with a lazy screenplay, contrived plotting, and overall poor production.

movie_title: C'est Pas Moi, Je le Jure! (It's Not Me, I Swear!)

critics_consensus: Disconcerting and sometimes eerie, this enigmatic French film is an assured directorial debut.
Triangle sails into some strange waters, but this intelligent, well-acted horror outing anchors its idiosyncrasies in a satisfyingly scary story.
Thanks to a suitably raunchy script and a pair of winning performances from Jonah Hill and Russell Brand, Get Him to the Greek is one of the year's funniest comedies.
A thought-provoking and insightful documentary about the dangers of commercial fishing.
An intriguingly unusual ghost story, Conor McPherson's Eclipse blends supernatural suspense with romance to create a satisfying, character-driven whole.
It might strike some viewers as a little too pat, but The Blind Side has the benefit of strong source material and a strong performance from Sandra Bullock.
A thin premise stretched far beyond serviceable length, Furry Vengeance subjects Brendan Fraser -- and the audience -- to 92 minutes of abuse.
Warrior relies on many of the clichÃ©s that critics of the genre love to mock -- and it transcends them with gripping action, powerful acting, and heart.
Hackneyed and over dramatic, this undercooked courtroom drama suffers from bad dialogue and a twist ending you'll see from a distance.
Featuring an impressive star turn by newcomer Tahar Rahim, A Prophet is a French gangster film filled with arresting, immediate details.
Featuring Patton Oswalt's sympathetic portrayal, Big Fan humorously and effectively captures the dark and lonely world of a sports fanatic.
Angelina Jolie gives it her all in the title role, and her seasoned performance is almost enough to save Salt from its predictable and ludicrous plot.

movie_title: Did You Hear About the Morgans?
critics_consensus: It gets a certain amount of mileage out of the inherent likability of its stars, but with an unfunny script and a lack of onscreen chemistry, Did You Hear About the Morgans? falls flat.
World's Greatest Dad is a risky, deadpan, dark comedy that effectively explores the nature of posthumous cults of celebrity.
Half enviro-saving doc, half publicity stunt, No Impact Man is inspiring and fun to both casual activists and hardcore recyclers.
Though fans of the event will likely enjoy X-Games 3D: The Movie, most will find it a poorly put together, skin deep, extended advertisement for the extreme sports competition.
The Way We Get By is a thoughtful, poignant look at some unsung American heroes.
Oliver Hirschbiegel's dramatic take on "The Troubles" is an actor's showcase -- and Liam Neeson and James Nesbitt are more than up to the challenge.
It plays more like a traditional melodrama than the Susanne Bier film that inspired it, but Jim Sheridan's Brothers benefits from rock-solid performances by its three leads.
Increasingly tedious displays of gore makes this torture porn home-invasion-horror more programmatic than provocative.
Borrowing heavily (and intelligently) from Pixar and Looney Tunes, Despicable Me is a surprisingly thoughtful, family-friendly treat with a few surprises of its own.
A cheerful and cute - though never overly mawkish - nature-doc about... you guessed it... Meerkats.

movie_title: Anita O'Day: The Life of a Jazz Singer
critics_consensus: This rich documentary chronicles the highs and lows of one of the medium's finest singers, utilizing remarkable archive footage and insightful interviews with O'Day herself.
This engaging and well-organized eco-doc maps the successes and failures of the American environmental movement, thanks to sharp interviews and remarkable archive footage.
A dramedy that's got a taste for the tragic as well as the poignantly comic, Amreeka adds a new sweetness to the hope and distress of the immigrant experience.
A horror comedy that's almost as chilling as it is funny, I Sell the Dead relies on its dark humor and offbeat charm to overcome its low budget shortcomings.
A breezy road movie with characters both glamorous and familiar, My One and Only is a colorful period look at the early life of actor George Hamilton.
It traces a familiar, albeit inspirational arc, but The Horse Boy tells a moving tale of parental devotion with grace and sensitivity.
Though somewhat uneven in places, Fifty Dead Men Walking is a gripping portrayal of Ireland's violent history, carried by the strong performances of its lead actors.
Art & Copy doesn't probe deeply enough, or think critically enough about its subject.
Semi-comic-action thriller Triangle teams three leading Hong Kong directors together with confusing results. For asian cinema aficionados only.
Gerald McMorrow's bold debut is a complex and ambitious film that highlights the director's potential, but its multi-layered story takes time to develop and might be frustrating for some.
Spike Lee's document of the Tony Award-winning musical Passing Strange is every bit as compelling onscreen as it was on stage.

This documentary about Josh Harris' surveillance-as-art project exposes the problems of privacy in the internet age and asks provocative questions about the power of ego in a place where everything is on display.
Not for the faint of heart, Kick-Ass takes the comic adaptation genre to new levels of visual style, bloody violence, and gleeful profanity.
Despite the chemistry of stars Patricia Clarkson and Stanely Tucci, Blind Date's stagey direction and underdeveloped story make it feel more like a rehearsal than a performance.
Though the costumes are beautiful and the art direction impeccable, what stands out most from this debut by fashion designer Tom Ford is the leading performance by Colin Firth.
Gerard Butler and Jennifer Aniston remain as attractive as ever, but The Bounty Hunter's formula script doesn't know what to do with them -- or the audience's attention.
Though lengthy and at times plodding, Soderbergh's vision and Benicio Del Toro's understated performance ensure that Che always fascinates.
Tim Burton's Alice sacrifices the book's minimal narrative coherence -- and much of its heart -- but it's an undeniable visual treat.
The Losers is loud, fast, and unrelentingly violent -- but it's also funny and well-acted, which will make all the difference for some action fans.
As gut-wrenching as it is inspirational, 127 Hours unites one of Danny Boyle's most beautifully exuberant directorial efforts with a terrific performance from James Franco.
The plot's a bit of a jumble, but excellent performances and mind-blowing plot twists make 12 Monkeys a kooky, effective experience.
Visually striking and grippingly fast-paced, 12 O'Clock Boys asks thought-provoking questions with admirable subtlety and restraint.
Energetic but empty, 12 Rounds' preposterous plot hurtles along at a rapid pace, but can't disguise the derivative script.
It's far from comfortable viewing, but 12 Years a Slave's unflinchingly brutal look at American slavery is also brilliant -- and quite possibly essential -- cinema.
Takashi Miike's electric remake of Eiichi Kudo's 1963 period action film is a wild spectacle executed with killer, dizzying panache.
The plot's nothing new, but Garner shows a lovable flair for romantic comedies.
13 Sins may be derivative of other horror films that made their moral points with more finesse, but it atones with a grim sense of humor and sleek style.
This starkly minimalist nail-biter of a thriller relentlessly builds up the tension and keeps the audience guessing.
Atmospheric, great sets and costumes, but thin plot.
Relying on psychological tension rather than overt violence and gore, 1408 is a genuinely creepy thriller with a strong lead performance by John Cusack.
Historically inaccurate and dramatically inert, Ridley Scott's retelling of Christopher Columbus' exploits is an epic without grandeur or insight.
As critical as it is about sensationalism in the media, 15 Minutes itself indulges in lurid violence, and its satire is too heavy-handed to be effective.
Despite strong performances from Bruce Willis and Mos Def, 16 Blocks is a shopworn entry in the buddy-action genre.
Steven Spielberg's attempt at screwball comedy collapses under a glut of ideas, confusing an unwieldy scope for a commensurate amount of guffaws.
1984 doesn't fully emerge from the shadow of its source material, but still proves a solid, suitably discomfiting adaptation of a classic dystopian tale.
Revealing yet respectful, 20,000 Days on Earth is essential viewing for any Nick Cave fan.
One of the most influential of all sci-fi films -- and one of the most controversial -- Stanley Kubrick's 2001 is a delicate, poetic meditation on the ingenuity -- and folly -- of mankind.
2010 struggles to escape from the shadow of its monolithic predecessor, but offers brainy adventure in a more straightforward voyage through the cosmos.
Roland Emmerich's 2012 provides plenty of visual thrills, but lacks a strong enough script to support its massive scope and inflated length.
Rich, insightful, and occasionally heartbreaking, 20 Feet From Stardom is an energetic tribute to the passion, talent, and hard work of backup singers.
Though it strives to mimic The Hangover, 21 and Over is too predictable, too unabashedly profane, and too inconsistently funny to carry the torch.
Alejandro GonzÃ¡lez IÃ±Ã¡rritu deftly weaves an uncommonly structured narrative with panache in 21 Grams, a stylish, haunting drama full of fine performances.
A smart, affectionate satire of '80s nostalgia and teen movie tropes, 21 Jump Street offers rowdy mainstream comedy with a surprisingly satisfying bite.

Boasting even more of the bromantic chemistry between its stars -- and even more of the goofy, good-natured humor that made its predecessor so much fun -- 22 Jump Street is the rare sequel that improves upon the original.
One of China's most talented directors blurs the lines between non-fiction, drama, and musical theater in this vivid portrait of a country in cultural flux.
The colorful, chaotic 24 Hour Party People nimbly captures the spirit of the Manchester music scene.
Dull, joyless, and formulaic, My Soul to Take suggests writer/director Wes Craven ended his five-year filmmaking hiatus too soon.
An intelligent and well-acted film despite the usual Spike Lee excesses.
The filmmakers perfectly follow the well-worn romantic comedy formula, rendering 27 Dresses clichÃ©d and mostly forgettable.
Even though 28 Days is tackling a difficult subject, it comes off light and superficial, and maybe even a little preachy.
Kinetically directed by Danny Boyle, 28 Days Later is both a terrifying zombie movie and a sharp political allegory.
While 28 Weeks Later lacks the humanism that made 28 Days Later a classic, it's made up with fantastic atmosphere and punchy direction.
2 Days in New York breezes past its shortcomings thanks to an enjoyably madcap plot and the sweet chemistry between its well-matched stars.
Delpy proves not only to be an adept actress, but makes her mark as a writer and director in this thought-provoking comedy that breaks the romantic comedy mold.
A labyrinthine thriller with a host of memorable characters, 2 Days in the Valley is an uneven but intriguing thriller/black comedy.
Beautiful people and beautiful cars in a movie that won't tax the brain cells.
Formulaic and often jarringly violent, 2 Guns rests its old-school appeal on the interplay between its charismatic, well-matched stars.
A simple-minded but visually exciting experience, full of blood, violence, and ready-made movie quotes.
While the premise sounds promising, the movie turns out to be a tedious and unnecessarily violent heist movie that's low on laughs and leaves no cliche unturned.
It's bound to hit some viewers as an empty exercise in stylish gore, and despite a gonzo starring performance from Eva Green, 300: Rise of an Empire is a step down from its predecessor.
While 30 Days of Night offers a few thrills, it ultimately succumbs to erratic execution.
It's sporadically funny and it benefits from a talented cast, but 30 Minutes or Less suffers from a disjointed narrative, and too often mistakes crude gags for true lowbrow humor.

movie_title: 31 North 62 East (Too Close to the Truth)

critics_consensus: This remake of a classic Western improves on the original, thanks to fiery performances from Russell Crowe and Christian Bale as well as sharp direction from James Mangold.
Spreading itself thin across a sprawling narrative without a unifying focus, 360 just keeps running in circles.
3 Days to Kill uneasily mixes technically accomplished action sequences with an underdeveloped family conflict.
A tender and moving romance from Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... And Spring's director Kim Ki-Duk.
3 Ninjas might be exciting enough for younger action enthusiasts, but they deserve better -- and there's no shortage of superior options to choose from.

movie_title: 3 Ninjas: High Noon at Mega Mountain

critics_consensus: 3 Women is a strange, eerie portrait of late-'70s womanhood that upends and then defies all expectations.
A seminal French New Wave film that offers an honest, sympathetic, and wholly heartbreaking observation of adolescence without trite nostalgia.
As romantic comedies go, 40 Days and 40 Nights is smutty, sexist, and puerile.
Steve Carell's first star turn scores big with a tender treatment of its titular underdog, using raunchy but realistically funny comedy to connect with adult audiences.
42 is an earnest, inspirational, and respectfully told biography of an influential American sports icon, though it might be a little too safe and old-fashioned for some.
An actor's movie with a strong cast, 44 Inch Chest can't quite redeem its static plotting and tonal shifts.
47 Ronin is a surprisingly dull fantasy adventure, one that leaves its talented international cast stranded within one dimensional roles.
Marking an auspicious feature film debut for Eddie Murphy, 48 Hrs. is a briskly paced action comedy that succeeds largely due to the outstanding chemistry between its two leads.
Boldly ambitious and bracingly passionate, 4 opens an inscrutable window onto modern-day Russia -- and announces director Ilya Khrzhanovsky as a major talent.
4 Little Girls finds Spike Lee moving into documentary filmmaking with his signature style intact -- and all the palpable fury the subject requires.
Featuring gut-wrenching performances from Anamaria Marinca and Laura Vasiliu, 4 Months is a gripping portrayal of life in Communist Romania.
A clever, offbeat romantic comedy, 500 Days of Summer is refreshingly honest and utterly charming.
A good-hearted film about a difficult topic, 50/50 maneuvers between jokes and drama with surprising finesse.

Gross-out humor overwhelms the easy chemistry between Adam Sandler and Drew Barrymore, who bring some energy and yucks to this tale of a girl with short-term memory loss and the guy who tries to get her to love him.
A filmmaker's investigation of his parents' marriage renders an ordinary subject surprisingly powerful.
Robbed of its integral LGBTQ themes, 54 is a compromised and disjointed glance at the glory days of disco.
Director Michael Apted continues to utilize cinema as a window into the lives of everyday people, and in the reflection of this documentary we can glimpse our own aging humanity.

movie_title: 71 Fragmente einer Chronologie des Zufalls (71 Fragments of a Chronology of Chance)

critics_consensus: Inventive, thought-provoking, and funny, 8 1/2 represents the arguable peak of Federico Fellini's many towering feats of cinema.
It's unabashedly biased, but this look at the fight over gay marriage in California is impassioned and provocative.
88 Minutes is a shockingly inept psychological thriller that expertly squanders the talent at hand.
Even though the story is overly familiar, there's enough here for an engaging ride.
Its sadistic violence is unappealing and is lacking in suspense and mystery.
Its storyline isn't as wondrous as its visuals, but $9.99 has a sophistication and handmade charm that sets it apart from the animated pack.

movie_title: A Crude Awakening: The Oil Crash
A Film with Me in It
Jackie Chan's Project A2 ('A' gai wak juk jap) (Project A, Part II)
A Mother's Courage: Talking Back To Autism (SÃ³lskinsdrengurinn)

critics_consensus: A Band Called Death is not only a fascinating portrait of a pioneering rock group, but also a tribute to family ties and perseverance in the face of hardship.
Powered by a terrific performance from DemiÃ¡n Bichir, A Better Life is an immigrant story told with simplicity and an ample amount of heart.

movie_title: A Bottle in the Gaza Sea

critics_consensus: A Cat in Paris depicts a stylish, imaginative world with a wonderful soundtrack and Hitchcockian overtones.
Amiably slight, A Coffee in Berlin compensates for its lack of narrative drive with a sure-handed screenplay and echoes of early Woody Allen.
A provocative historical fiction about the early days of psychoanalysis, A Dangerous Method is buoyed by terrific performances by Michael Fassbender, Keira Knightley, and Viggo Mortensen.
Aside from a few chuckles and Simon Pegg's reliably affable screen presence, A Fantastic Fear of Everything has embarrassingly little to offer.
Recklessly assembled and occasionally compelling in spite of itself, A Field in England showcases a singularly brilliant voice in British cinema.
Modest to a fault, A Five Star Life is worth seeing chiefly for Margherita Buy's marvelous work in the central role.

movie_title: A Girl Walks Home Alone at Night
critics_consensus: A Girl Walks Home Alone at Night blends conventional elements into something brilliantly original -- and serves as a striking calling card for writer-director Ana Lily Amirpour.

movie_title: A Glimpse Inside the Mind of Charles Swan III
critics_consensus: Tiresomely self-indulgent and lacking any storytelling cohesion, this Glimpse Inside the Mind finds little food for thought.

movie_title: A Good Day To Die Hard
critics_consensus: A Good Day to Die Hard is the weakest entry in a storied franchise, and not even Bruce Willis' smirking demeanor can enliven a cliched, uninspired script.

movie_title: A Guide to Recognizing Your Saints
critics_consensus: A Guide to Recognizing Your Saints is a lively, powerful coming-of-age tale with winning performances and sharp direction from first-timer Dito Montiel.
Wasting the talent of its leads, this predictable romantic comedy relies on cheap laughs.
A Haunted House seeks to offend every sensibility, but it's greatest sin: not being funny!
Sloppy, vulgar, and manic, A Haunted House 2 might be worth a chuckle or two, but mostly it's a string of pop culture references and crude gags that fail to hit their intended targets.
A tense, gripping thriller, A Hijacking avoids action movie cliches and instead creates a palpable sense of dread by mixing gritty realism with atmospheric beauty.
This powerful documentary explores an important subject -- homosexuality in the Muslim world -- with humanity and courage.
An outstanding ensemble cast lends weight and depth to A Late Quartet's melodramatic script, and the result is insightful and emotionally satisfying.
Even if bowling isn't your sport, this colorful documentary is still an entertaining watch.
Sweet, sad, and visually striking, A Letter to Momo is a hand-drawn experience for animation fans to savor.

movie_title: A Liar's Autobiography - The Untrue Story of Monty Python's Graham Chapman

critics_consensus: A Little Bit of Heaven subjects viewers to a whole bunch of schmaltz - and strands Kate Hudson and Gael GarcÃ­a Bernal in a fatally misguided film.
Tonally jumbled and conceptually ill-advised, A Long Way Down bungles its source material and wastes a talented cast.
Though it lacks moviemaking polish, A Man Named Pearl is redeemed by the interest -- and uplift -- generated by its subject.

movie_title: A Million Ways to Die in the West
critics_consensus: While it offers a few laughs and boasts a talented cast, Seth MacFarlane's overlong, aimless A Million Ways to Die in the West is a disappointingly scattershot affair.
Smart, subtle, and steadily absorbing, A Most Wanted Man proves once again that John le Carre books make for sharp, thoughtful thrillers.
A Night in Old Mexico gives Robert Duvall a too-rare starring showcase -- then frustratingly wastes it on a contrived story that's often unworthy of his talents.

movie_title: A Nightmare on Elm Street 2: Freddy's Revenge
critics_consensus: An intriguing subtext of repressed sexuality gives Freddy's Revenge some texture, but the Nightmare loses its edge in a sequel that lacks convincing performances or memorable scares.

movie_title: A Nightmare on Elm Street 3: Dream Warriors
critics_consensus: A Nightmare on Elm Street 3: Dream Warriors offers an imaginative and surprisingly satisfying rebound for a franchise already starting to succumb to sequelitis.

movie_title: A Nightmare on Elm Street 4: The Dream Master
critics_consensus: A Nightmare on Elm Street 4: The Dream Master marks a relative high point in this franchise's bumpy creative journey, although the original remains far superior.

movie_title: A Nightmare on Elm Street 5: The Dream Child
critics_consensus: A Nightmare on Elm Street feels exhausted by this cheesy fifth entry, bogged down by a convoluted mythology while showing none of the chilling technique that kicked off the franchise.
While smarter than the average slasher film, A Perfect Getaway eventually devolves into a standard, predictable, excessively violent thriller.
A Place at the Table is a well-reported documentary that raises important questions about the state of hunger in America culture.
The hard edges of E.M. Foster novel maybe sanded off, but what we get with A Room with a View is an eminently entertaining comedy with an intellectual approach to love.
A Screaming Man deftly uses its personal look at a family dynamic to offer pointed political observations, confirming writer-director Mahamat-Saleh Haroun as a major talent.
Morally complex, suspenseful, and consistently involving, A Separation captures the messiness of a dissolving relationship with keen insight and searing intensity.
Blending dark humor with profoundly personal themes, the Coen brothers deliver what might be their most mature -- if not their best -- film to date.
It has a bleak sense of atmosphere and a terrific performance by Sam Rockwell, but A Single Shot is undercut by its predictable story and slow pace.
Lili Talyor is the best thing in this uninvolving and unconvincing drama.
Flat and unfocused, A Smile Like Yours aims for romantic comedy but settles for tired sitcom formula.
Grueling but honest depiction about the ravages of Alzheimer's. Yep, it's a downer.
Michael Winterbottom's tale of grief and mourning, though frustrating in places, is intelligent filmmaking with superb central performances.
Restrained but disturbing, A Tale of Two Sisters is a creepily effective, if at times confusing, horror movie.
The A-Team assembles a top-rate cast only to ditch the show's appealingly silly premise for explosive yet muddled blockbuster filmmaking.
Dated jokes (A Thousand Words was shot in 2008) and removing Eddie Murphy's voice -- his greatest comedic asset -- dooms this painful mess from the start.

movie_title: A Thousand Years of Good Prayers
critics_consensus: Though it may not be as profound as its pacing would suggest, A Thousand Years of Good Prayers delicately examines familial issues in an earnest fashion.
Its screenplay isn't as graceful as the choreography of its action sequences, but A Touch of Sin offers enough stylishly satisfying violence to muscle past its rough spots.

movie_title: A Town Called Panic (Panique au village)
critics_consensus: A Town Called Panic is a raucous, endlessly creative animated romp with a quirky, adult sense of humor.
With a fascinating character as its subject, A Very British Gangster makes for entertaining, frightening, and informative viewing.
A well-crafted and visually arresting drama with a touch of whimsy.
A Walk Among the Tombstones doesn't entirely transcend its genre clichÃ©s, but it does offer Liam Neeson one of his more compelling roles in recent memory, and that's often enough.

movie_title: A Walk Into the Sea: Danny Williams and the Warhol Factory
critics_consensus: A portrait piece of Danny Williams, set amongst New Yorks Factory, home of Andy Warhol, provides insight and flavour of the time and the setting, with an unresolved mystery at its heart.

movie_title: A Woman, A Gun and a Noodle Shop (San qiang pai an jing qi) (A Simple Noodle Story) (The First Gun)
critics_consensus: Zhang Yimou's broad reinterpretation of the Coen Brothers' Blood Simple struggles to bring anything new to the twisty murder mystery and instead ladles on an excess of stilted comedy.

movie_title: A Woman Is a Woman (Une femme est une femme)
critics_consensus: One of the last times Godard could make film paradoxes with glee, A Woman Is a Woman is a mocking, genuine tribute to musicals.

movie_title: A Woman of Paris: A Drama of Fate

critics_consensus: The plotline for Abandon is too disjointed and muddled to offer much in the way of thrills.
The Abandoned spends so much time setting up the creepy atmosphere, that it forgets to inhabit it with genuine spooks or scares.
A zany horror spoof that plays up and then plays into the best of Universal horror cliches.

movie_title: Abbott and Costello Meet Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde
Abbott and Costello Meet the Mummy

critics_consensus: ABCs of Death 2 delivers some inventively gory thrills, offering a surprising (albeit still somewhat uneven) upgrade over its predecessor.
A soulless and incompetent action/thriller not even a veteran lead actor could save, let alone Taylor Lautner.
Though the characters are difficult to watch at times, Aberdeen burns with ferocious honesty and strong performances.
About a Boy benefits tremendously from Hugh Grant's layered performance, as well as a funny, moving story that tugs at the heartstrings without tilting into treacle.
Although some of the characters' motivation may not be that clear, the movie is still a funny and sexy charmer.
About Alex pointedly provokes comparisons to The Big Chill, but the script doesn't have enough substance to support them -- or give its talented cast enough to work with.
About Last Night wanders even further from the David Mamet play that inspired the original, but it benefits from an engaging cast and a screenplay that smartly balances romance and comedy.
In this funny, touching character study, Nicholson gives one of the best performances of his career.
Beautifully filmed and unabashedly sincere, About Time finds director Richard Curtis at his most sentimental.

Abraham Lincoln: Vampire Hunter has visual style to spare, but its overly serious tone doesn't jibe with its decidedly silly central premise, leaving filmgoers with an unfulfilling blend of clashing ingredients.
Absolute Wilson is an excellent introduction to the artist Robert Wilson, even if it can't quite capture the spirit of his work.
Abuse of Weakness' fact-based plot proves that truth can be stranger than fiction -- and provide grist for compelling character studies.
Like its characters who aren't able to meet their potential, Accepted's inconsistent and ridiculous plot gets annoying, despite a few laughs.

movie_title: The Accidental Spy (Te wu mi cheng)

critics_consensus: Jim Carrey's twitchy antics and gross-out humor are on full, bombastic display in Ace Ventura: Pet Detective, which is great news for fans of his particular brand of comedy but likely unsatisfying for anyone else.
Nature Calls in this Ace Ventura sequel, and it's answered by the law of diminishing returns.
Despite its impressive cast and some sharp observations, A.C.O.D. is neither funny enough nor poignant enough to work as a potent comedy or incisive satire.
Psychedelic musical numbers can't mask Across the Universe's clichÃ©d love story and thinly written characters.
It's undeniably reverent of the real-life heroes in its cast, but Act of Valor lets them down with a clichÃ©d script, stilted acting, and a jingoistic attitude that ignores the complexities of war.
Such an unusual tale might have made for a compelling drama, but Adam Resurrected suffers from narrative confusion and an emotional detachment at its core.
Sandler returns to his roots in this nauseating concoction filled with potty humor and product placements.
Good and evil collide with interesting results in Adam's Apples, a dark Biblical allegory that's alternatively funny and shocking.
The movie is peppered with amusing sight gags and one-liners, but the disjointed script doesn't cohere into a successful whole.
New, well-developed characters add dimension to this batty satire, creating a comedy much more substantial than the original.
As visually thrilling as it is inscrutable, Goodbye to Language 3D offers a late-period masterpiece from a legendary director still very much in control of his craft.
First-time writer/director George Nolfi struggles to maintain a consistent tone, but The Adjustment Bureau rises on the strong, believable chemistry of its stars.
Admission has a pair of immensely likable leads in Tina Fey and Paul Rudd, but it wastes them on a contrived (and clumsily directed) screenplay.
A complex and thought-provoking work, Atom Egoyan's Adoration works well as both mystery and engaging drama.
Naomi Watts and Robin Wright give it their all, but they can't quite make Adore's trashy, absurd plot believable.
Colorful, witty, and uplifting, Advanced Style celebrates life and pays tribute to those who flout convention.
Full of humor and nostalgia, Adventureland is a sweet, insightful coming-of-age comedy that will resonate with teens and adults alike.
Sweet and spry, Adventures in Babysitting gets by on its amiable tone.

movie_title: The Adventures of Elmo in Grouchland
critics_consensus: This fun and moral tale entertains both first-time Seasame Street watchers and seasoned veterans.

movie_title: The Adventures of Ichabod and Mr. Toad
critics_consensus: This Disney two-fer may not be the most reverent literary adaptation, but it's remarkably crafted and emotionally resonant.
The Adventures of Pluto Nash is neither adventurous nor funny, and Eddie Murphy is on autopilot in this notorious box office bomb.

movie_title: The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert
critics_consensus: While its premise is ripe for comedy -- and it certainly delivers its fair share of laughs -- Priscilla is also a surprisingly tender and thoughtful road movie with some outstanding performances.
Though the film stays true to the nature of the original cartoon, the script is disappointing and not funny.
Aeon Flux lacks the gravity-defying pace of its animated predecessor, and, despite some flash, is largely a dull affair.
A film about court intrigue, The Affair of the Necklace turns out to be more dull than juicy. Swank seems flat and miscast in the central role of Jeanne.
There's not too much to it besides Cary Grant and Deborah Kerr, but that's still enough to make this An Affair to Remember.
It isn't without its share of clichÃ©s, but Afflicted proves there's still life in the found-footage horror genre.
Dark and bleak, the "kick-ass" performances, especially Nolte's "effective" portrayal of an abused soul, is the reason to see this film.
An enlightening and sobering documentary on Afghanistan's very own X-Factor.
It isn't quite as majestic as its subjects, but African Cats boasts enough astounding footage -- and a big enough heart -- to keep things entertaining.
After Earth is a dull, ploddingly paced exercise in sentimental sci-fi -- and the latest setback for director M. Night Shyamalan's once-promising career.
This understated yet emotionally devastating documentary lets the stories of its subjects speak for themselves.
It has an interesting premise and admirable ambitions, but After.Life fails to deliver enough twists or thrills to sustain its creepy atmosphere.
A slick but bland thriller.
The cast brings After the Wedding's melodramatic script to life, creating a movie that is emotionally raw and satisfying.
After Tiller applies empathy, honesty, and graceful understatement to a discussion that all too often lacks them all.
It represents an occasionally uneven collision of genres, but all in all, Wladyslaw Pasikowski's Aftermath delves into Holocaust guilt with power and efficiency.
Afternoon Delight's uncertain tone is entertainingly offset by smart dialogue and standout starring work from Kathryn Hahn.

movie_title: Afternoon of a Faun: Tanaquil Le Clercq

critics_consensus: Antonio Campos'Afterschool is an intelligent, ambitious debut that boasts strong performances and plenty of ideas.

Aftershock hints at an inventive twist on horror tropes, but ultimately settles for another round of mind-numbing depravity that may alternately bore and revolt all but the most ardent gore enthusiasts.
A bland, dumbed-down package of sports cliches.
Equal measures romantic and wistful, Martin Scorsese's elegant adaptation of The Age of Innocence is a triumphant exercise in both stylistic and thematic restraint.
Should satisfy young teens, but offers nothing new for those who are familiar with the formula.
Young kids may find this London adventure fun, but older kids may find it too simplistic.
Noble goals and a gripping performance from Rachel Weisz can't save Agora from its muddled script, uneven acting, and choppy editing.

movie_title: Aguirre, the Wrath of God (Aguirre, der Zorn Gottes)
critics_consensus: A haunting journey of natural wonder and tangible danger, Aguirre transcends epic genre trappings and becomes mythological by its own right.
A curious, not always seamless, amalgamation of Kubrick's chilly bleakness and Spielberg's warm-hearted optimism, A.I. is, in a word, fascinating.

movie_title: Aileen: Life and Death of a Serial Killer
critics_consensus: This chilling, unsettling documentary provides an eye-opening look at both Wuornos and the American justice system.

movie_title: Aileen Wuornos - The Selling of a Serial Killer
Ain't In It For My Health: A Film About Levon Helm

critics_consensus: While conventional in plot, Ain't Them Bodies Saints is a visually poetic film that pays homage to the New Hollywood directors of the 1970s and promises big things from director David Lowery.
This late-period Harrison Ford actioner is full of palpable, if not entirely seamless, thrills.
It's up for debate how serious or ironic its subjects are, but Air Guitar Nation is nonetheless a funny and exciting documentary with a killer soundtrack.
Though unabashedly juvenile and silly, Airplane! is nevertheless an uproarious spoof comedy full of quotable lines and slapstick gags that endure to this day.
This multi-character drama balances intimate portrayals and broad political implications to paint a bracing and moving portrait of the Middle East conflict.
A warm, family-friendly underdog story, featuring terrific supporting performances from Keke Palmer, Laurence Fishburne, and Angela Bassett.
Akira is strikingly bloody and violent, but its phenomenal animation and sheer kinetic energy helped set the standard for modern anime.
Never flinching during its descent into depravity, I Saw the Devil is a pulverizing thriller that will give bloody satisfaction to audiences who like their revenge served with fiery rage.

movie_title: Aladdin and the King of Thieves

critics_consensus: Too conventional and uninvolving to be memorable.
The Alan Partridge movie ditches the TV series' nuanced humor for something broader, and succeeds in presenting the character on a global scale.
Albert Nobbs tells a worthy story with an outstanding performance at its core, even if the end result is often somewhat less than the sum of its admirable parts.
A dull and unfunny comedy where the leads fail to generate any sparks.
Tyler Perry and Matthew Fox do their best, but they're trampled by Rob Cohen's frustrating direction and a tasteless, lazily written screenplay.
Alex Rider: Operation Stormbreaker is strictly children's fare, as it lacks originality, excitement, and believabiltity.
Even at nearly three hours long, this ponderous, talky, and emotionally distant biopic fails to illuminate Alexander's life.

movie_title: Alexander and the Terrible, Horrible, No Good, Very Bad Day
critics_consensus: Affably pleasant without ever trying to be anything more, Alexander and the Terrible, Horrible, No Good, Very Bad Day is a fine -- albeit forgettable -- family diversion.

This unnecessary remake wants Alfie to have his cake and eat it, too, but a lack of sexual fizz and a sour performance by Jude Law conspire to deliver audiences a romantic comedy that isn't romantic or funny.
Though perhaps no film could fully do justice to the fascinating life and personality of Muhammad Ali, Mann's direction and Smith's performance combine to pack a solid punch.
A modern classic, Alien blends science fiction, horror and bleak poetry into a seamless whole.
Alien3 takes admirable risks with franchise mythology, but far too few pay off in a thinly scripted sequel whose stylish visuals aren't enough to enliven a lack of genuine thrills.
Alien Nation takes the interesting premise of extraterrestrials living among us and doesn't do enough with it, emphasizing a police procedural plotline over the more intriguing sci-fi elements.
Alien Resurrection marks a slight improvement over its predecessor, but still lacks the emotional stakes that helped make the franchise's first two entries sci-fi/horror classics.
An earnest attempt to parody campy 1950s sci-fi films, Alien Trespass eventually loses its charm among tedious dialogue and cheesy special effects.
Gore without scares and cardboard cut-out characters make this clash of the monsters a dull sit.
Inoffensive and kid-friendly this mundane family comedy is light on imagination.
An amazing array of images from beneath the sea.
It's somewhat clumsily expressed, but Alive Inside offers such an uplifting message that it's ultimately hard to resist.

movie_title: All About My Mother (Todo sobre mi madre)
critics_consensus: Almodovar weaves together a magnificent tapestry of femininity with an affectionate wink to classics of theater and cinema in this poignant story of love, loss and compassion.
All About Steve is an oddly creepy, sour film, featuring a heroine so desperate and peculiar that audiences may be more likely to pity than root for her.
A sloppy, poorly directed action-comedy, All About the Benjamins is too derivative and gratuitously violent.
All Cheerleaders Die sets out to subvert horror tropes, but ends up falling victim to many of the same trashy cliches it's trying to mock.
It's well-acted, and the true story that inspired it offers plenty of drama -- which is why it's so frustrating that All Good Things is so clichÃ©d and frustratingly ambiguous.
Well-acted but uneven, All Is Bright strands a pair of strong performances from Paul Giamatti and Paul Rudd in a meandering script.
Anchored by another tremendous performance in a career full of them, All Is Lost offers a moving, eminently worthwhile testament to Robert Redford's ability to hold the screen.
Big heart, big drama, and even bigger colors, All That Heaven Allows is tip top Douglas Sirk.
With a scenery-chewing performance from Sean Penn, an absence of political insight, and an overall lack of narrative cohesiveness, these Men give Oscar bait a bad name.
A taut, solidly acted paean to the benefits of a free press and the dangers of unchecked power, made all the more effective by its origins in real-life events.
This adaptation of Cormac McCarthy's novel comes off as rather flat and uninvolving. Scenes feel rushed and done in shorthand, and the romance between Damon and Cruz has no sparks.
Has enough honest moments to warrant a look.
Alle Anderen (Everyone Else) taps into the unpredictable energy between two couples to throw finely detailed - and richly rewarding - sparks of emotional truth.
Almost Famous, with its great ensemble performances and story, is a well-crafted, warm-hearted movie that successfully draws you into its era.
A sorry swan song for the talented Chris Farley, Almost Heroes is a directionless comedy that doesn't even come close to triumph.
Almost Human lands with an impressively grisly B-movie splatter, but a fatally flawed screenplay undermines much of its impact.
Inept on almost every level, Alone in the Dark may not work as a thriller, but it's good for some head-slapping, incredulous laughter.
Alone With Her is a tense psychological thriller that overcomes its contrivances with fine performances and a perpetually unsettling mood.
Derivative and contains too many implausible situations.
Though the supporting actors are funny, Stiller and Aniston don't make a believable couple, and the gross-out humor is gratuitous.
With bland visuals and a dull, predictable plot, Alpha and Omega is a runt in 2010's animated litter.
