Buffy the Vampire Slayer's supernatural coming of age tale is let down by poor directing and even poorer plotting -- though Kristy Swanson and Paul Reubens' game performances still manage to slay.
Disappointing resolution aside, Bug uses its claustrophobic setting and cinÃ©ma vÃ©ritÃ© camerawork to tense, impressive effect.
A Bug's Life is a rousing adventure that blends animated thrills with witty dialogue and memorable characters - and another smashing early success for Pixar.
Stylishly scattered, Bugsy offers cinematic homage to the infamous underworld legend, chiefly through a magnetic performance from Warren Beatty in the title role.
A thoroughly engrossing documentary examining the life of talented but troubled writer Charles Bukowski.
Kevin Costner at his funniest and most charismatic in Bull Durham, a film that's as wise about relationships as it is about minor league baseball.
Bullet to the Head's unapologetically trashy thrills evoke memories of its star and director's proud cinematic pasts -- but sadly, those memories are just about all it has to offer.
Venerable action star Chow Yun-Fat is the only saving grace in this silly action flick that more often than not resembles a commercial in style.
Steve McQueen is cool as ice in this thrilling police procedural that also happens to contain arguably the greatest movie car chase ever.
With its lingering shots of naked teenage bodies, Bully feels more sordidly exploitative than realistic.
Hard-hitting and gracefully filmed, Bully powerfully delivers an essential message to an audience that may not be able to see it.
Star and director Beatty's ambitious take on race and politics in 20th-century America isn't perfect, but manages to provide more than its share of thought-provoking laughs.
Bunraku admirably strives for visual panache, but the staging, acting, and effects are dismal with a complete lack of excitement.
Wringing a seemingly impossible amount of gripping drama out of its claustrophobic premise, Buried is a nerve-wracking showcase for Ryan Reynolds' talent.
Campy and clichÃ©d, Burlesque wastes its talented cast (including a better-than-expected Christina Aguilera) on a movie that wavers uncertainly between "bad" and "so bad it's good."

movie_title: Burma VJ: Reporter i et Lukket Land (Burma VJ: Reporting from a Closed Country)
critics_consensus: A powerfully visceral docu-drama highlighting the evils of censorship and the essential need for freedom of speech.
With Burn After Reading, the Coen Brothers have crafted another clever comedy/thriller with an outlandish plot and memorable characters.

movie_title: Night of the Eagle (Burn, Witch, Burn! )

critics_consensus: This heavily symbolic, melodramatic multi-narrative drama lacks emotional resonance.
Epstein's argument in favor of home birthing is certainly biased -- but its biases are so transparent, and so impassioned, that they work in the film's favor.
The Business of Strangers showcases a complex, compelling performance by Channing. Her interactions and clashes with Stiles make for riveting viewing.

Too broad to make any real statements, But I'm a Cheerleader isn't as sharp as it should be, but a charming cast and surprisingly emotional center may bring enough pep for viewers looking for a light social satire.
Equal parts comical and harrowing, The Butcher Boy is a sobering tale of abuse told with an imaginative lyricism that is by turns inspired and distracting.
Despite its talented cast and a few funny moments, Butter's satirical aims are largely undone by a lack of subtlety and air of smugness.
The premise is intriguing, but it's placed in the service of an overwrought and tasteless thriller.
Director Neil Jordan remains as expert as ever when it comes to setting a chilling mood, but Byzantium struggles to match its creepily alluring atmosphere with a suitably compelling story.
Great performances and evocative musical numbers help Cabaret secure its status as a stylish, socially conscious classic.
Cabin in the Sky overcomes some questionable storytelling choices thanks to irresistible musical numbers and a brilliantly talented cast.
The Cable Guy's dark flashes of thought-provoking, subversive wit are often -- but not always -- enough to counter its frustratingly uneven storytelling approach.
A creepy French psychological thriller that commands the audience's attention throughout.
Though unabashedly crude and juvenile, Caddyshack nevertheless scores with its classic slapstick, unforgettable characters, and endlessly quotable dialogue.
Handicapped by a family friendly PG rating, even the talents of Caddyshack II's all-star comic cast can't save it from its lazy, laughless script and uninspired direction.
What Cadillac Records may lack in originality, it more than makes up for in strong performances and soul-stirring music.
Though potentially too slowly paced for some, Cairo Time lingers long after the closing credits, largely due to a wonderful performance by Patricia Clarkson.
A charming, but cliched comedy reminiscent of The Full Monty.
Alternately horrific and uplifting, Call Me Kuchu exposes heinous systematic brutality with a clear eye and admirable precision.
An uneven biopic that struggles to convey what made its subject special, Callas Forever is far from a definitive look at the life of this brilliant opera diva.
A loving tribute to Latin Jazz artists where music does the talking.
Led by a brilliant performance from Brendan Gleeson, Calvary tackles weighty issues with humor, intelligence, and sensitivity.

movie_title: Cameraman: The Life And Work Of Jack Cardiff

critics_consensus: Camille Claudel, 1915 isn't an easy watch, but Juliette Binoche's excellent performance makes it worth the effort.
Campy comedy that squeaks by on its charms.
Camp Rock wants to be the next High School Musical, but its forgettable songs and dull premise hold it back.
Camp X-Ray's treatment of its subject verges on the shallow, but benefits greatly from a pair of impressive performances from Kristen Stewart and Peyman Moaadi.
The Candidate may not get all the details right when it comes to modern campaigning, but it captures political absurdity perfectly -- and boasts typically stellar work from Robert Redford to boot.
Stars Heath Ledger and Abbie Cornish look better than they should as heroin addicts, and their characters are too absorbed and self-pitying to be totally compelling.
Though it ultimately sacrifices some mystery in the name of gory thrills, Candyman is a nuanced, effectively chilling tale that benefits from an interesting premise and some fine performances.

movie_title: Cannibal! The Musical (Alferd Packer: The Musical)
critics_consensus: If you're only going to watch one black comedy about a real-life explorer whose fellow travelers ended up eaten, make it Cannibal! The Musical.
While Can't Buy Me Love gets some value out of its plucky leads, this romantic comedy struggles to find grace in a cynical conceit that belongs in the bargain bin.
Occasionally clever and moderately intelligent, Can't Hardly Wait also contains too many cheap laughs, recycled plotting, and flat characters.
Love him or hate him, Capitalism captures Michael Moore in his muckraking element -- with all the Moore-centric showmanship that entails.
A poetic and deeply felt debut by director Amin Matalqa, Captain Abu Raed is simultaneously mythic and melodramatic.
Lacking a script, budget, direction, or star capable of doing justice to its source material, this Captain America should have been left under the ice.
With plenty of pulpy action, a pleasantly retro vibe, and a handful of fine performances, Captain America is solidly old-fashioned blockbuster entertainment.
Suspenseful and politically astute, Captain America: The Winter Soldier is a superior entry in the Avengers canon and is sure to thrill Marvel diehards.

The cinematography is gorgeous, but the movie plays it fast and loose with history and the novel it was adapted from. Mostly, the movie fails because the romance between the leads strains credulity and the story is largely uninvolving.
Smart, powerfully acted, and incredibly intense, Captain Phillips offers filmgoers a Hollywood biopic done right -- and offers Tom Hanks a showcase for yet another brilliant performance.
Lacking scares or psychological insight, Captivity is a distasteful entry in the 'torture porn' subgenre.
A haunting depiction of a disintegrating family, and a powerful argument on the elusiveness of truth.
Caramel is both an astute cultural study, and a charming comedic drama from a talented newcomer.
Despite its hefty running time, Carlos moves along briskly, thanks to an engaging story, exotic locales, and a breakout performance by Edgar Ramirez.
It isn't as compelling on the screen as it was on the stage, but Carnage makes up for its flaws with Polanski's smooth direction and assured performances from Winslet and Foster.
Not even an HOV lane amid a traffic jam is worth boarding this aggravating and unfunny Carpool.
It boasts a talented cast, but Kimberly Peirce's "reimagining" of Brian De Palma's horror classic finds little new in the Stephen King novel -- and feels woefully unnecessary.
Cars offers visual treats that more than compensate for its somewhat thinly written story, adding up to a satisfying diversion for younger viewers.
Cars 2 is as visually appealing as any other Pixar production, but all that dazzle can't disguise the rusty storytelling under the hood.
Well-acted and thought provoking, if not completely satisfying.
Thinly written and not as funny as it needs to be, Casa de mi Padre would have worked better as a fake trailer or short film; stretched to feature length, it wears out its welcome far too quickly.
Director Christian Alvert has a certain stylish flair, but it's wasted on Case 39's frightless, unoriginal plot.
An unlikable protagonist, messy editing, and gratuitous nudity might make audiences ask for their cash back.
Kevin Spacey turns in one of his stronger performances, but Casino Jack is a disappointingly uneven fictionalized account of a fascinating true story.

movie_title: Casino Jack And The United States Of Money
critics_consensus: Casino Jack's subject matter is enraging, but in the hands of director Alex Gibney, it's also well-presented and briskly entertaining.

Casino Royale disposes of the silliness and gadgetry that plagued recent James Bond outings, and Daniel Craig delivers what fans and critics have been waiting for: a caustic, haunted, intense reinvention of 007.
A meandering, mindless family movie that frequently resorts to special effects and transparent sappiness.
Colin Farrell and Tom Wilkinson act up a storm in Cassandra's Dream, but Woody Allen's heavy-handed symbolism and foreshadowing drains the plot of all tension.
Flawed but fascinating, Cast Away offers an intelligent script, some of Robert Zemeckis' most mature directing, and a showcase performance from Tom Hanks.
Casualties of War takes a harrowing plunge into the Vietnam War with a well-acted ensemble piece that ranks among director Brian De Palma's more mature efforts.

movie_title: Dr. Seuss' The Cat in the Hat
critics_consensus: Filled with double entendres and potty humor, this Cat falls flat.
Catch-22 takes entertainingly chaotic aim at the insanity of armed conflict, supported by a terrific cast and smart, funny work from Buck Henry and Mike Nichols.
No stranger to the political thriller, director Phillip Noyce tackles apartheid and terrorism with experienced gusto, while Derek Luke and Tim Robbins hand in nuanced performances.
A romantic dramedy with boring, stock characters and contrived situations.

With help from a strong performance by Leonardo DiCaprio as real-life wunderkind con artist Frank Abagnale, Steven Spielberg crafts a film that's stylish, breezily entertaining, and surprisingly sweet.
An unimaginative heist movie aimed strictly at the preteen set.
This witty movie succeeds as both a modest teen coming-of-age story and a satirical microcosm of Italy's political climate.

Catfish may tread the line between real-life drama and crass exploitation a little too unsteadily for some viewers' tastes, but its timely premise and tightly wound mystery make for a gripping documentary.
A great concept, but the movie fails to develop the characters and some of the jokes are hit-or-miss.

movie_title: Cats & Dogs: The Revenge of Kitty Galore
critics_consensus: Dull and unfunny, this inexplicable sequel offers little more than the spectacle of digitally rendered talking animals with celebrity voices.
Cats Don't Dance, but they should easily entertain all-ages audiences thanks to some colorful animation, sharp humor, and a catchy soundtrack.
An effective if knowingly silly Stephen King anthology that combines comedy and terror.
The Cat's Meow is a deliciously evoked period piece and whodunit.
Halle Berry is the lone bright spot, but even she can't save this laughable action thriller.
Though solidly acted and pleasant to look at, Cavalcade lacks cohesion, and sacrifices true emotion for mawkishness.
Despite its stylized and impressive sets, this horror-monster movie mish-mash suffers from endless cliches and wildly implausible plotlines.
Hauntingly filmed and brimming with Herzog's infectious enthusiasm, Cave of Forgotten Dreams is a fascinating triumph.

movie_title: The Cave of the Yellow Dog (Die Hohle des gelben Hundes)
critics_consensus: A sparse, hauntingly beautiful journey across continents and cultures.
Hey! Ho! No no!
The idea behind John Waters' latest has much potential, but the movie ends up being too sloppy and underdeveloped in terms of script and direction. Also, by today's standards, it fails to shock.
It's as conventional as its Midwestern setting, but Cedar Rapids boasts a terrific cast and a script that deftly blends R-rated raunch and endearing sweetness.

While it doesn't subvert the genre as incisively as it thinks it does, Celeste and Jesse Forever is a shrewd rom-com that benefits from its likable cast and trumpets the arrival of Rashida Jones as a bona fide big screen talent.

movie_title: Celine: Through The Eyes Of The World

critics_consensus: Though it's gimmicky and occasionally feels like a high-end cell phone ad, Cellular is also an energetic and twisty thriller.
The Celluloid Closet takes a thought-provoking look at the decades of omission and misrepresentation endured by the gay community in mainstream cinema.
It fails to challenge the well-established conventions of its storyline, but Cemetery Junction benefits from the genuine warmth of its script, as well as its refusal to give in to cheap nostalgia.
For all its tease, the movie doesn't have more to say than money can't buy you love.
Viewers willing to sit through soapy plot contrivances to see some excellent dancing might enjoy Center Stage; for everyone else, there's still always Fame.
Director Salles transcends road-movie clichÃ©s and crafts a film that is as moving as it is universal.
It's a bloody geyser of Neil Marshall's typically stylish B-movie action, but Centurion is too focused on hacking and slashing to deliver original dialogue or interesting characters.
The main stars are absolutely perfect in this absorbing, existential drama that dissects human relationships.
Too in awe of its subject's great works to present him as a human being, Cesar ChÃ¡vez settles for trite hagiography.
Chalet Girl is light comedic fun geared for teenage girls, featuring a charming performance from Felicity Jones.
Chalk approaches its potentially rich subject matter with a light touch, but still emerges with a humorous, heartfelt tribute to a noble profession.
A thin plot is disguised by high octane dancing and action in this Bollywood crossover comedy.
Though some may find its conclusion unsatisfying, Changing Lanes is a tense, well-crafted exploration of meaty ethical dilemmas.
Ryan Reynolds and Emily Mortimer do what they can, but ultimately Chaos Theory is an overly conventional dramedy.
Chaplin boasts a terrific performance from Robert Downey, Jr. in the title role, but it isn't enough to overcome a formulaic biopic that pales in comparison to its subject's classic films.
Decidedly slower and less limber than the Olympic runners at the center of its story, the film nevertheless manages to make effectively stirring use of its spiritual and patriotic themes.
Closer to the source material than 1971's Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory, Charlie and the Chocolate Factory is for people who like their Chocolate visually appealing and dark.
With engaging performances marked by an inconsistent tone, Charlie Bartlett is a mixed bag of clever teen angst comedy and muddled storytelling.

movie_title: Charlie Chan and the Curse of the Dragon Queen

critics_consensus: Shia LaBeouf clearly relishes his role in Charlie Countryman, but his efforts can't salvage the movie's shallow script and overstuffed direction.
Zac Efron gives it his all, but Charlie St. Cloud is too shallow and cloying to offer much more than eye candy for his fans.
Charlie Wilson's War manages to entertain and inform audiences, thanks to its witty script and talented cast of power players.
Mixing tongue-in-cheek cheesecake with glossy action set pieces, Charlie's Angels is slick and resonably fun despite its lack of originality.
Eye candy for those who don't require a movie to have a plot or for it to make sense.
A dull adaptation of Sebastian Faulk's novel despite gorgeous cinematography and Cate Blanchett's best efforts.
Kids will be entertained by the straightforward plot and cute animals, and adults will be charmed by how quiet and humble the production is, a fine translation of E.B. White's genteel prose.
Chasing Amy explores gender roles, sexual mores, and the limits of friendship with a mixture of sensitivity, raw honesty, and director/screenwriter Kevin Smith's signature raunchy humor.
Formulaic comfort food for the teen crowd.
It's sweet, gentle, and affably modest, but Chasing Mavericks is ultimately pulled under by an unconvincing script and a puzzling lack of energy.
Obnoxious in tone and unable to provide its trio of stars a decent quip, Chasing Papi will have audiences running in the other direction.
The second part of Soderbergh's biopic is a dark, hypnotic and sometimes frustrating portrait of a warrior in decline, with a terrific central performance from Del Toro.
Gleefully nasty and darkly hilarious, Cheap Thrills lives down to its title in the best possible way.
In this family of twelve children, much chaos ensues, but little hilarity.
A sequel to a remake, Cheaper 2 wastes its solid cast in scenes of over-the-top, predictable humor.
Chef's charming cast and sharp, funny script add enough spice to make this feel-good comedy a flavorful -- if familiar -- treat.

Abel Ferrara's loving portrait of New York's Chelsea Hotel is less interested in telling the story of its famous residents than in exploring the magic of the place that housed so many moments in rock history.
The meandering Chelsea Walls is more pretentious than poetic.
A too-short script and a romance lacking in heat detracts from an otherwise haughty charmer.
The different genres in Cherish don't mesh well, and the quirkiness sometimes feels too forced.
Despite an interesting premise and spooky atmospherics, Chernobyl Diaries is mostly short on suspense and originality.
While Cherry 2000 has a certain low-budget appeal, all but the most ardent genre enthusiasts are likely to find its silly story and uneven performances unintentionally amusing.
A rousing and energetic adaptation of the Broadway musical, Chicago succeeds on the level pure spectacle, but provides a surprising level of depth and humor as well.
Disney expends more effort in the technical presentation than in crafting an original storyline.
Chicken Run has all the charm of Nick Park's Wallace & Gromit, and something for everybody. The voice acting is fabulous, the slapstick is brilliant, and the action sequences are spectacular.
Whimsical and melancholy, Chicken with Plums is visually striking and dreamily compelling despite its occasional narrative missteps.
An obviously reverent adaptation that fails to make a case for the source material being turned into a movie, Child of God finds director James Franco outmatched by Cormac McCarthy's novel.
Children of a Lesser God transcends its transparently noble goals thanks to a pair of absorbing performances from William Hurt and Marlee Matlin.
This beautifully photographed but dramatically flat war drama recounts an important chapter in history with little cinematic freshness.
Children of Men works on every level: as a violent chase thriller, a fantastical cautionary tale, and a sophisticated human drama about societies struggling to live.

movie_title: Children of Paradise (Les Enfants du Paradis)
critics_consensus: Strong performances abound, and Carne's wit and grace are evident in this masterful (if long) French epic.

movie_title: Children of the Corn 666: Isaac's Return
Children of the Corn II: The Final Sacrifice
Children of the Corn V: Fields of Terror
Children Shouldn't Play with Dead Things

critics_consensus: Child's Play occasionally stumbles across its tonal tightrope of comedy and horror, but its genuinely creepy monster and some deft direction by Tom Holland makes this chiller stand out on the shelf.
It isn't necessarily an easy watch, but thanks to Netzer's interesting direction and a riveting performance from Gheorghiu, Child's Pose is rewarding.
Claiming it fails on every level, critics had almost nothing good to say about this movie.
A classic story adapted by a filmmaker near his creative peak, Chimes at Midnight unites Welles and Shakespeare - and powerfully distills the best of both.
With gripping themes and a stellar cast, The China Syndrome is the rare thriller that's as thought-provoking as it is tense.

As bruised and cynical as the decade that produced it, this noir classic benefits from Robert Towne's brilliant screenplay, director Roman Polanski's steady hand, and wonderful performances from Jack Nicholson and Faye Dunaway.
Pleasantly easygoing and consistently funny, Chinese Puzzle offers a suitably endearing conclusion to CÃ©dric Klapisch's Trilogy of Xavier.
Eric Rohmer's Chloe in the Afternoon doesn't need sparkly cinematic dross to discover unspoken, universal truths about relationships and love through filmmaking.
Chocolat is a charmingly light-hearted fable with a lovely performance by Binoche.
While bolstered by strong performances from Sam Rockwell and Anjelica Huston, Choke struggles to capture the tone of Chuck Palahniuk's novel.
Quirky animated interludes fail to lift this dull US immigrant indie out of its introverted torpid state.
Eric Bana's performance as the charming but twisted Chopper is the highlight of this disturbing portrait about Australia's notorious author/criminal.
While predictable, this low-key heartwarmer manages to be uplifting without overdoing the sentiment.
On stage, A Chorus Line pulled back the curtain to reveal the hopes and fears of showbiz strivers, but that energy and urgency is lost in the transition to the big screen.
Chris and Don paints an affecting, enlightening portrait of a one-of-a-kind love affair.
The cracks are starting to show in John Carpenter's directorial instincts, but Christine is nonetheless silly, zippy fun.
A mirthless movie as fresh as last year's fruit cake, Christmas with the Kranks is a coarse, garish comedy that promotes conformity.
Chronicle transcends its found-footage gimmick with a smart script, fast-paced direction, and engaging performances from the young cast.

movie_title: The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, The Witch and The Wardrobe
critics_consensus: With first-rate special effects and compelling storytelling, this adaptation stays faithful to its source material and will please moviegoers of all ages.

movie_title: The Chronicles of Narnia: Prince Caspian
critics_consensus: The Chronicles of Narnia: Prince Caspian is an entertaining family adventure worthy of the standard set by its predecessor.

movie_title: The Chronicles of Narnia: The Voyage of the Dawn Treader
critics_consensus: Its leisurely, businesslike pace won't win the franchise many new fans, but Voyage of the Dawn Treader restores some of the Narnia franchise's lost luster with strong performances and impressive special effects.
As an action movie, Riddick offers some thrills, but as a sequel to Pitch Black, it's a disappointment.

movie_title: Chroniques sexuelles d'une famille d'aujourd'hui (Sexual Chronicles of a French Family)

critics_consensus: Where Chrystal's going isn't always clear, but this slow-burning story proves effective -- and marks writer-director-star McKinnon as a multi-hyphenated talent to watch.
As poignant as it is unsettling, Chuck & Buck uses the complex dynamic between two men as fuel for untangling a rich assortment of thought-provoking themes.

movie_title: Chuck Berry: Hail! Hail! Rock 'n' Roll
Chuck Close: A Portrait in Progress

critics_consensus: This derivative poke at suburbia falls short of delivering a scathing indictment of upper middle-class disconnect.
Brutal and unflinching, City of Men is both a harrowing look at Brazil's favela life, and a touching tale of youths rushed into adulthood.
The Cider House Rules has wonderful performances, lovely visuals, and an old-fashioned feel.
The rich colors, sweet songs, adorable mice and endearing (if suffering) heroine make Cinderella a nostalgically lovely charmer.

movie_title: Cinderella III: A Twist in Time

critics_consensus: With grittiness and an evocative sense of time and place, Cinderella Man is a powerful underdog story. And Ron Howard and Russell Crowe prove to be a solid combination.
An uninspired, generic updating of the classic fairy tale.
Cinema Paradiso is a life-affirming ode to the power of youth, nostalgia, and the the movies themselves.
A thought-provoking, insightful look into Iranian youth culture.
Orson Welles's epic tale of a publishing tycoon's rise and fall is entertaining, poignant, and inventive in its storytelling, earning its reputation as a landmark achievement in film.
Smart and sharply funny, Citizen Ruth is an entertaining look at a tough subject -- and an impressive calling card for debuting director/co-writer Alexander Payne.
Part real-life thriller, part sobering examination of 21st century civil liberties, Citizenfour transcends ideology to offer riveting, must-see cinema.
Even though the movie is well acted, it sinks under an abundance of melodrama and cliches.
Raymond De Felitta combines warmth, humanity, and a natural sense of humor, and is abetted by Andy Garcia and an excellent ensemble cast.
One of the best underdog romance movies ever, with an ending that will light up any heart.
City of Angels may not tug the heartstrings as effortlessly as it aims to, but the end results will still leave more than a few viewers in tears.
City of Ember is visually arresting, and boasts a superb cast, but is sadly lacking in both action and adventure.
Atmospheric, but that's about it.
A shocking and disturbing, but always compelling look at life in the slums of Rio de Janiero.

movie_title: The City of Lost Children (La CitÃ© des Enfants Perdus)
critics_consensus: Not all of its many intriguing ideas are developed, but The City of Lost Children is an engrossing, disturbing, profoundly memorable experience.

movie_title: Paura nella cittÃ  dei morti viventi (City Of The Living Dead) (The Gates of Hell)
City of Women (La cittÃ  delle donne)
The City of Your Final Destination
critics_consensus: A stellar cast can't elevate this leaden adaptation that, while just as beautiful as anything director James Ivory's made before, comes off as dusty and dry.
With a supremely talented cast and just enough midlife drama to add weight to its wildly silly overtones, City Slickers uses universal themes to earn big laughs.

movie_title: City Slickers 2 - The Legend of Curly's Gold
critics_consensus: Lacking any of the charm of its predecessor, City Slickers 2 meanders around the map without ever finding comedy gold.
At times a tense and provocative thriller, Civic Duty struggles to move beyond its one-note premise.
Intelligent and unconventional.
Eccentric and sweet, Stephen Chow's latest is charming, but too strangely and slackly plotted to work as a whole.
Though it sometimes feels cold and detached, The Claim is evocative, beautifully shot, and full of understated performances.

movie_title: The Clan of the Cave Bear

critics_consensus: A goofy, old-school sword-and-sandal epic, Clash of the Titans mines Greek mythology for its story and fleshes it out with Ray Harryhausen's charmingly archaic stop-motion animation techniques.

Its 3D effects are an improvement over its predecessor's, but in nearly every other respect, Wrath of the Titans fails to improve upon the stilted acting, wooden dialogue, and chaos-driven plot of the franchise's first installment.
An obviously affectionate remake of the 1981 original, Louis Leterrier's Clash of the Titans doesn't offer enough visual thrills to offset the deficiencies of its script.
Perfecting the formula established in earlier installments, Clear and Present Danger reunites its predecessor's creative core to solidly entertaining effect.
Though it has an excellent cast, this emotionally detached movie is the kind that one admires more than enjoys.
Critics say Cleopatra's Second Husband is unappetizing to watch and moves too slowly. Also, you don't care what happens to the characters.
With its quirky characters and clever, quotable dialogue, Clerks is the ultimate clarion call for slackers everywhere to unite and, uh, do something we guess?
Clerks II dishes up much of the graphic humor and some of the insight that made the 1994 original a cult hit.
This latest Adam Sandler vehicle borrows shamelessly from It's A Wonderful Life and Back To The Future, and fails to produce the necessary laughs that would forgive such imitation.
Ill-conceived and desperately unfunny, Clifford stars Martin Short as a 10-year-old boy. You read that correctly. That's the joke.
While a dull affair for parents, Clifford's Really Big Movie should charm its intended preschool audience.
A work of mournful maturity that sacrifices little of its director's signature energy, Clockers is an admittedly flawed drama with a powerfully urgent message.
A pleasant diversion for the young teens, but a waste of time for anyone older.
Disturbing and thought-provoking, A Clockwork Orange is a cold, dystopian nightmare with a very dark sense of humor.
Mechanical animation and a less-than stellar script make The Clone Wars a pale shadow of George Lucas' once great franchise.

movie_title: Close Encounters of the Third Kind
critics_consensus: Close Encounters of the Third Kind is deeply humane sci-fi exploring male obsession, cosmic mysticism, and music.
Slick and well acted, Closed Circuit unfortunately never quite works up a full head of steam, with a plot that's alternately predictable and full of holes.
Closer's talented cast and Mike Nichols' typically assured direction help smooth a bumpy journey from stage to screen.
A pleasant comedy with a great cast.
Its sprawling, ambitious blend of thought-provoking narrative and eye-catching visuals will prove too unwieldy for some, but the sheer size and scope of Cloud Atlas are all but impossible to ignore.

movie_title: Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs 2
critics_consensus: While not as clever or inventive as its predecessor, Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs 2 compensates with enough dazzling visuals to keep younger viewers entertained.
A sort of Blair Witch Project crossed with Godzilla, Cloverfield is economically paced, stylistically clever, and filled with scares.
Comedy is too hit-or-miss is this slasher spoof.
A robust ensemble of game actors elevate Clue above its schematic source material, but this farce's reliance on novelty over organic wit makes its entertainment value a roll of the dice.
A funny and clever reshaping of Emma, Clueless offers a soft satire that pokes as much fun at teen films as it does at the Beverly Hills glitterati.
Even though it's based on a true story, Coach Carter is pretty formulaic stuff, but it's effective and energetic, thanks to a strong central performance from Samuel L. Jackson.
Tommy Lee Jones's searing performance helps to elevate Cobb above your typical sports biopic; he's so effective, in fact, that some may find the film unpleasant.
The Cockettes provides a colorful, eye-opening view of the counterculture 1960s.
If you're interested in watching a battle between cockneys and zombies, this is the movie for you.
There are no surprises in Cocktail, a shallow, dramatically inert romance that squanders Tom Cruise's talents in what amounts to a naive barkeep's banal fantasy.
Though it doesn't quite capture the complexity of its subject's life, Coco Avant Chanel remains a fascinating, appropriately lovely tribute.
It's well-acted and beautifully filmed, but Jan Kounen's dramatization of the affair between his famous subjects is curiously short on passion.
Code 46 crafts an intriguing hypothetical future and populates it with characters who never engage, producing a slick sci-fi package without any humanity to power it.
Impassioned and infuriating, Code Black awakens viewers to an endemic problem with no clear solution.
Code Name: The Cleaner is a limp action/comedy flick that alternates between lame, worn-out jokes and cheesy martial arts.

movie_title: Code Unknown (Code inconnu: RÃ©cit incomplet de divers voyages)
critics_consensus: Though challengingly cryptic at times, Code Unknown still manages to resonate.
Episodes vary in quality, but overall this talky film is quirkily engaging.
C.O.G.'s plot is a bit meandering, but the characters are always compelling and the ending is richly rewarding.
A case study in less-is-more filmmaking, Coherence serves as a compelling low-budget calling card for debuting writer-director James Ward Byrkit.
Despite strong performances from Bryan Cranston and Alice Eve, Cold Comes the Night is undone by a series of illogical plot twists.
The plot of Cold Creek Manor is too predictable and contrived to generate suspense.
Boasting plenty of twists, a suitably seedy tone, and a memorable supporting turn from Don Johnson, Cold in July proves an uncommonly rewarding thriller.
The well-crafted Cold Mountain has an epic sweep and captures the horror and brutal hardship of war.
Straddling existential drama and surrealist comedy, Sophie Barthes debut feature is beautifully shot and full of inventive quandaries.
For viewers who manage to stay invested in its occasionally aimless story, Cold Weather proves a surprisingly sophisticated blend of mumblecore and indie noir.
Driven by director Michael Mann's trademark visuals and a lean, villainous performance from Tom Cruise, Collateral is a stylish and compelling noir thriller.
Filled with shrill gags and middling slapstick, College Road Trip is woefully short on comic imagination.
Three teens contemplate life after high school while singing their hearts out in this fresh musical.
Zoe Saldana has the chops but she's taken out by erratic and sloppy filmmaking.

movie_title: The Color of Lies (Au coeur du mensonge)

critics_consensus: That it's inferior to the original goes without saying, but Paul Newman and Tom Cruise are a joy to watch, and Martin Scorsese's direction is typically superb.
Bruce willie shot aside, the only other things popping out in Color of Night are some ridiculous plot contortions and majorly camp moments.
A sentimental tale that reveals great emotional truths in American history.
Colour Me Kubrick has a fascinating premise, but provides little insight into Kubrick and the man who impersonated him.
Full of groin-centric humor and tired sports clichÃ©s, The Comebacks is poor even by parody movie standards.
Comedian is an insightful look at the hard work of creating comedy.

movie_title: Comic-Con: Episode IV - A Fan's Hope

critics_consensus: Eddie Murphy was in full control at this point, starkly evident in Coming to America's John Landis' coasting direction.
A flat and misconceived movie with big stars.
Anchored by smart, sensitive direction and strong performances, Complicance is a ripped-from-the-headlines thriller that's equal parts gripping and disturbing.
With its delightfully retro production design, Computer Chess is an inventive, intelligent, and humorous comedy that celebrates the eccentricity and uniqueness of its subject.
Con Air won't win any awards for believability - and all involved seem cheerfully aware of it, making some of this blockbuster action outing's biggest flaws fairly easy to forgive.
Though Conan may take itself too seriously for some, this adventure film about a former slave seeking vengeance is full of quotable Schwarzenegger lines and gritty action.
While its relentless, gory violence is more faithful to the Robert E. Howard books, Conan the Barbarian forsakes three-dimensional characters, dialogue, and acting in favor of unnecessary 3D effects.
Conan the Destroyer softens the edges that gave its predecessor gravitas, resulting in a campy sequel without the comparative thrills.
As confrontational as it is ultimately rewarding, Concerning Violence is a scathing indictment of past misdeeds -- and a sobering reminder of how far we still have to go.
Smart, nuanced, and sexy, Concussion transcends its more awkward moments thanks to Robin Weigert's remarkable starring performance.
The Condemned is a morally ambiguous, exceedingly violent and mostly forgettable action film.
Listless, crude, and overall uninspired, Coneheads offers further evidence that stretching an SNL sketch to feature length can be tougher than narfling a garthok.
Rockwell is spot-on as Barris, and Clooney directs with entertaining style and flair.
This middling romantic comedy underutilizes a talented cast and delivers muddled messages on materialism and conspicuous consumption.

movie_title: Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen
critics_consensus: Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen's superficial tendencies are unlikely to appeal to older viewers -- though its colorful candor is decidedly not intended for them in the first place.
This improvised mockumentary has its funny and even sweet moments, but it's not as witty or sharp as Christopher Guest's offerings.
While it may not be the best con in town, the movie still manages to entertain with its colorful cast.
Mired in campy visual effects and charmless characters, Congo is a suspenseless adventure that betrays little curiosity about the scientific concepts it purports to care about.

movie_title: Congo: White King, Red Rubber, Black Death
Connected: An Autoblogography About Love, Death & Technology
Conquest Of The Planet Of The Apes

critics_consensus: The Constant Gardener is a smart, gripping, and suspenseful thriller with rich performances from the leads.
Despite solid production values and an intriguing premise, Constantine lacks the focus of another spiritual shoot-em-up, The Matrix.
Exceptional research elevates Constantine's Sword from a talking heads documentary to a resonant and thought-provoking expose of the church's dark history.
Tense, tightly plotted, and bolstered by a stellar cast, Contagion is an exceptionally smart -- and scary -- disaster movie.
This powerful work of essential cinema joins "meta" with "physique," casting Brigite Bardot and director Godard's inspiration Fritz Lang.
It's more entertaining than your average January action thriller, but that isn't enough to excuse Contraband's lack of originality and unnecessarily convoluted plot.

Control is a work of art, thanks to its evocative black and white cinematography and sensational performances from Sam Riley and Samantha Morton. Even those not familiar with Joy Division can still appreciate the beauty of the film.
This tense, paranoid thriller presents Francis Ford Coppola at his finest -- and makes some remarkably advanced arguments about technology's role in society that still resonate today.
Less compelling -- and more manipulative -- than it should be, Conviction benefits from its compelling true story and a pair of solid performances from Swank and Rockwell.

movie_title: The Cook, the Thief, His Wife & Her Lover
critics_consensus: This romantic crime drama may not be to everyone's taste, but The Cook, the Thief, His Wife & Her Lover is an audacious, powerful film.
Good-natured but prepared with an absence of craft, The Cookout is an unappetizing collection of warmed-over jokes.
Though hampered by Stuart Rosenberg's direction, Cool Hand Luke is held aloft by a stellar script and one of Paul Newman's most indelible performances.
A small movie elevated by superb performances.

Cop Land gifts its star-studded cast with richly imagined characters while throttling the audience with carefully-ratcheted suspense, although this potboiler lacks the moral complexity of the crime classics that it harkens to.
Cop Out is a cliched buddy action/comedy that suffers from stale gags and slack pacing.
A pretentious historical drama that's ultimately a drag, despite Ed Harris' powerful performance.
With its vivid stop-motion animation combined with Neil Gaiman's imaginative story, Coraline is a film that's both visually stunning and wondrously entertaining.
A B-movie with its tongue planted firmly in cheek, The Core is so unintentionally (intentionally?) bad that it's a hoot.
Visceral and visually striking, Ralph Fiennes' Coriolanus proves Shakespeare can still be both electrifying and relevant in a modern context.
Corky Romano continues the trend of bad movies featuring SNL members. The jokes are tired and unfunny, and the slapstick feels forced.

movie_title: Corman's World: Exploits Of A Hollywood Rebel

critics_consensus: The Corporation is a satisfyingly dense, thought-provoking rebuttal to some of capitalism's central arguments.
As can be expected from a Tim Burton movie, Corpse Bride is whimsically macabre, visually imaginative, and emotionally bittersweet.
This uninspiring cop thriller doesn't measure up to Chow Yun-Fat's Hong Kong work.
Though some may find it cold and didactic, Cosmopolis benefits from David Cronenberg's precise direction, resulting in a psychologically complex adaptation of Don DeLillo's novel.
Countdown to Zero is more genuinely frightening than many horror movies -- and more soberly enlightening than the average documentary.
Despite all the celebrities on hand, this spin-off from a theme park attraction still feels tired and hokey.
The cast gives it their all, and Paltrow handles her songs with aplomb, but Country Strong's cliched, disjointed screenplay hits too many bum notes.
Despite a talented cast and some reliably pleasant interplay between Jon Favreau and Vince Vaughn, Couples Retreat leaves viewers stranded in an arid, mirthless comedy.

An emotional and intriguing tale of a military officer who must review the merits of a fallen officer while confronting his own war demons. Effectively depicts the terrors of war as well as its heartbreaking aftermath.
While the filmmaking is fairly competent, Courageous is overall worthless to anybody who doesn't subscribe to its dogmatic agenda.
A witty spoof of medieval swashbuckler movies, The Court Jester showcases Danny Kaye at his nimble, tongue-twisting best.
The Covenant plays out like a teen soap opera, full of pretty faces, wooden acting, laughable dialogue, and little suspense.
Daniel Craig and Harrison Ford are as dependably appealing as ever, but they're let down by director Jon Favreau's inability to smooth Cowboys & Aliens' jarring tonal shifts.
Coyote Ugly has an enthusiastically trashy energy and undeniable aesthetic appeal, but it's nowhere near enough to make up for the film's shallow, unimaginative story.
CQ is a stylish and fun homage to campy 1960s flicks.
Atomospheric but not much else, Cracks is a formless film in search of compelling drama.
Dumb and by-the-numbers, but serviceable.
Witty and provocative.
The Craft's campy magic often overrides the feminist message at its story's core, but its appealing cast and postmodern perspective still cast a sporadic spell.

It's a film about a guy injected with Speed... wait, there's no bus. It's a film about a guy who has to kick a bunch of squirmy butt to stay alive... wait, no snakes or planes here. But it is a film about doing lots of drugs and pulling lots of punches, and it entertains accordingly.
Crank: High Voltage delivers on its promises: a fast-paced, exciting thrill ride that doesn't take itself too seriously.
The Crazies isn't top-shelf Romero, but its blend of genre thrills and social subtext should still be enough to satisfy discerning horror fans.
The story is not new, but the film gets credit for trying to move away from the genre's cliches. Kirsten Dunst and newcomer Jay Hernandez give believable performances.
Thanks to a captivating performance from Jeff Bridges, Crazy Heart transcends its overly familiar origins and finds new meaning in an old story.
Melanie Griffith gets kudos for her performance, but the movie just doesn't seem to come together.
Crazy Love's subjects and story are so compelling that they overcome the doc's dry, talking heads format.
It never lives up to the first part of its title, but Crazy, Stupid, Love's unabashed sweetness -- and its terrifically talented cast -- more than make up for its flaws.
It's uneven, as anthologies often are, but Creepshow is colorful, frequently funny, and treats its inspirations with infectious reverence.
Visually stunning and achingly performed, Ingmar Bergman's chamber piece is a visceral rumination on death and sisterhood.
Despite the beautiful visuals, Crime and Punishment is too somber and pretentious. Also, the acting is of mixed quality.
Though melodramatic, El Crimen del Padre Amaro's critique of the Catholic church is a timely one.
Boasting taut, high energy thrills and some cracking dialogue courtesy of an uncredited Quentin Tarantino, Crimson Tide finds director Tony Scott near the top of his action game.

movie_title: Crna macka, beli macor (Black Cat, White Cat)
critics_consensus: Rambling and eccentric, Emir Kusturica's comedy captures the life and energy of the Gypsy family at the heart of the tale.
Infectiously easygoing charm and a leading man in the role he was born to play help Crocodile Dundee make the most of its familiar fish-out-of-water premise.
A sequel as unnecessary as it is belated, Crocodile Dundee in Los Angeles lacks virtually all of the easygoing humor and charm that delighted fans of the original.
An unsettling and absorbing cautionary tale with John Leguizamo playing an unscrupulous TV reporter who uses the medium to further his own goals.
Guillermo del Toro's unique feature debut is not only gory and stylish, but also charming and intelligent.
Riveting and bone-chillingly creepy, Cropsey manages to be one of the best documentaries and one of the best horror movies of the year.
Crossing Over is flagrant and heavy-handed about a situation that deserves more deliberate treatment, and joins its characters with coincidences that strain believability.
An engrossing look at the aftermath of largely forgotten events during the Cold War, Crossing the Line raises questions that will haunt the viewer after the credits roll.
This heartfelt but incompetent, cliche-ridden sports picture is the cinematic equivalent of an airball.

The movie that catapulted Ang Lee into the ranks of upper echelon Hollywood filmmakers, Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon features a deft mix of amazing martial arts battles, beautiful scenery, and tasteful drama.
Filled with style and dark, lurid energy, The Crow is an action-packed visual feast that also has a soul in the performance of the late Brandon Lee.
The Crow: Salvation adds nothing new to the series and is plagued by bad acting and dialogue.
The Crow: City of Angels is a sloppy pretender that captures neither the mood nor energy of the original.
This darkly comic drama and its attractive young cast are easy on the eyes, but uneven performances and an uninspired script conspire to foil Cruel Intentions.

Cruising glides along confidently thanks to filmmaking craft and Al Pacino's committed performance, but this hot-button thriller struggles to engage its subject matter sensitively or justify its brutality.

Crumb is a frank and surreal chronicle of artistic expression and family trauma, offering an unblinking gaze into the mind and work of cartoonist Robert Crumb that will endear as much as it unsettles.
John Waters' musical ode to the teen rebel genre is infectious and gleefully camp, providing star Johnny Depp with the perfect vehicle in which to lampoon his pin-up image.

movie_title: Evil Angels (A Cry in the Dark)

critics_consensus: Dull and derivative, Cry_Wolf is a subpar slasher that even ardent fans of the genre may find difficult to enjoy.
The Crying Game is famous for its shocking twist, but this thoughtful, haunting mystery grips the viewer from start to finish.
Slight and unpolished, The Crystal Fairy is held together with Sebastian Silva's assured direction and a pair of strong, committed performances from Michael Cera and Gaby Hoffman.

movie_title: CSA: The Confederate States of America
critics_consensus: Through the eyes of a British "documentary", this film takes a satirically humorous, and sometimes frightening, look at the history of an America where the South won the Civil War.
Half concert doc, half political exposition, CSNY: DeJa Vu straddles the old and new slant on politics in music with diligence and not a little self-promotion.
Nick Frost and Chris O'Dowd remain as undeniably likable as ever, but Cuban Fury saddles them with a contrived and predictable plot that's far too short on laughs.
Cube sometimes struggles with where to take its intriguing premise, but gripping pace and an impressive intelligence make it hard to turn away.
Cujo is artless work punctuated with moments of high canine gore and one wild Dee Wallace performance.

movie_title: The Curious Case of Benjamin Button
critics_consensus: Curious Case of Benjamin Button is an epic fantasy tale with rich storytelling backed by fantastic performances.

movie_title: The Curse of the Cat People
critics_consensus: Foregoing the horror thrills of its predecessor in favor of childhood fantasy, Curse of the Cat People is a touching and psychologically complex family film couched in a ghost story.
Melodrama, swordplay, and CG armies -- fans of martial arts epic will get what they bargain for, though the baroque art direction can be both mesmerizing and exhaustively excessive.

movie_title: The Curse of the Jade Scorpion
critics_consensus: The writing for Scorpion is not as sharp as Woody Allen's previous movies as most of the jokes fall flat.
A beautifully-made documentary that explores the challenges and richness of both marriage and art through the lens of a fascinating and complex couple.
A suitably cynical neo-noir that echoes the disillusionment of its era, Cutter's Way relies on character-driven drama further elevated by the work of an outstanding cast.

Cutthroat Island may aspire towards the earnest thrills of classic swashbucklers, but a distinct lack of charm and stilted script make this adventure a joyless hodgepodge of the pirate genre's flotsam and jetsam.
While it may strike some viewers as slight, Cyrus is a successful hybrid of mainstream production values and the mumblecore ideals of directors Jay and Mark Duplass.
Whether it's being presented as D-Tox or Eye See You, this Stallone starring vehicle is a slapdash thriller to actively avoid.
What makes Dan Brown's novel a best seller is evidently not present in this dull and bloated movie adaptation of The Da Vinci Code.
A mirthless, fairly desperate family film, Daddy Day Camp relies too heavily on bodily functions for comedic effect, resulting in plenty of cheap gags but no laughs.
Daddy Day Care does its job of babysitting the tots. Anyone older will probably be bored.
Daddy's Little Girls boasts fine performances and a poignant message, but is ultimately let down by amateurish filmmaking.
Hitoshi Matsumoto's indescribably odd mockumentary is undeniably inspired.
Dallas Buyers Club rests squarely on Matthew McConaughey's scrawny shoulders, and he carries the burden gracefully with what might be a career-best performance.
Damien dishes out ghoulish scares and a biblical body count to generate some morbid fun, but this repetitious sequel lacks the sophistication of its predecessor.
Better than your average football pic, Damned United is carried by another star turn from Michael Sheen as Brian Clough.
Damsels in Distress can sometimes feel mannered and outlandish, but it's redeemed by director Whit Stillman's oddball cleverness and Greta Gerwig's dryly funny performance.
The fine performances elevate Dan in Real Life beyond its sentimental plot.
Dance Flick scores a few laughs thanks to the Wayans brothers' exuberance, but it's ultimately a scattershot collection of gags without much direction.
Shallow script, weak direction.
Dancer in Dark can be grim, dull, and difficult to watch, but even so, it has a powerful and moving performance from Bjork and is something quite new and visionary.
The Dancer Upstairs benefits from a talented cast and alluring intelligence, although pacing problems prevent this John Malkovich-directed mystery from reaching its full potential.
A grand, sweeping epic with inarguably noble intentions and arresting cinematography, but one whose center, arguably, is not as weighty as it should be.
Dancing in Jaffa uses art to frame a cultural journey that's equal parts entertaining, uplifting, and edifying.

movie_title: The Dangerous Lives of Altar Boys
critics_consensus: The inter-cutting of animation by Spawn's creator, Todd McFarlane, doesn't always work, but the performances by the young actors capture the pains of growing up well.
Rife with stereotypes that undermine its good intentions, Dangerous Minds is too blind to see that the ones it hurts are the audience.

Danny Deckchair mines some earnest pleasure from a concept with its head in the clouds and two stars whose chemistry is grounded, but the comedy quickly runs out of air when the premise comes back down to the earth.
Jet Li gets to emote in some emotionally awkward scenes, but the gritty fight sequences come through in what is Li's best English language film.
The movie works when things are on fire, but everything else - from dialogue to characters - is scathingly bad.

movie_title: Darby O'Gill and the Little People

critics_consensus: While Ben Affleck fits the role and the story is sporadically interesting, Daredevil is ultimately a dull, brooding origin story that fails to bring anything new to the genre.
With the requisite combination of humor, sorrow and outstanding visuals, The Darjeeling Limited will satisfy Wes Anderson fans.
The visuals are top notch but Tim Burton never finds a consistent rhythm, mixing campy jokes and gothic spookiness with less success than other Johnny Depp collaborations.
Kurt Russell gives a good performance. Too bad there's nothing here that you haven't seen before.
While it's better than Pearl Harbor, Dark Blue World still spends too much time on a trite love triangle.
Stylishly gloomy, Dark City offers a polarizing whirl of arresting visuals and noirish action.
The Dark Crystal's narrative never quite lives up to the movie's visual splendor, but it remains an admirably inventive and uniquely intense entry in the Jim Henson canon.
Marc Singer's documentary about a group of homeless people living beneath the streets of New York City is haunting and uplifting in equal measure.
The Dark Half is a highly serious psychological study that can be faulted for being more curious than actually scary.
Typically misanthropic yet curiously satisfying and incisive, Dark Horse is a movie that preaches to the cynical converted.
The creaky plotting, inscrutable characters, and unconvincing ending make it difficult for audiences to connect with Dark Matter.

Dark Skies writer director Scott Stewart has a solid cast, an interesting premise, and some admirable ambitions, but he can't figure out what to do with any of them, and the result is a dull, muddled effort that will bore all but the most devoted horror buffs.
Shallow and brackish, Dark Tide fails to rise.
All the atmospherics in Dark Water can't make up for the lack of genuine scares.
Gruesome and deliciously broad, Sam Raimi's Darkman bears the haunted soulfulness of gothic tragedy while packing the stylistic verve of onomatopoeia springing off a comic strip page.

movie_title: Darkman II: The Return of Durant

critics_consensus: Yet another predictable variation on the hoary old haunted-house movie, Darkness is an illogical, portentous mess.
A derivative movie where the scares are few and things don't make much sense.
An uneasy blend of action and comedy, Date Night doesn't quite live up to the talents of its two leads, but Steve Carell and Tina Fey still manage to shine through most of the movie's flaws.
An emotionally wrenching portrayal of a family reunion that doesn't turn out as expected.
Daughters of the Dust addresses its weighty themes with lovely visuals and a light, poetic touch, offering an original, absorbing look at a largely unexplored corner of American culture.
Ivan Reitman's refreshingly earnest political comedy benefits from an understated, charming script and a breezy performance by Kevin Kline.
Earnest and well-intentioned, "David & Layla" stumbles over itself too often to achieve its goals.

movie_title: Davy Crockett, King of the Wild Frontier

critics_consensus: A kinetic, violent and surprisingly worthy remake of George Romero's horror classic that pays homage to the original while working on its own terms.

movie_title: Dawn Of The Planet Of The Apes
critics_consensus: With intelligence and emotional resonance to match its stunning special effects, Dawn of the Planet of the Apes expands on its predecessor with an exciting and ambitious burst of sci-fi achievement.
The Day After Tomorrow is a ludicrous popcorn thriller filled with clunky dialogue, but spectacular visuals save it from being a total disaster.
A sweet counterpoint to Godard's Contempt, Truffaut's Day for Night is a congenial tribute to the self-afflicted madness that is making a movie.
Day Night Day Night is a minimalist drama that refuses to indulge in stereotypes, making it all the more realistic and chilling.
The Day of the Jackal is a meticulously constructed thriller with surprising irreverence and taut direction.

movie_title: The Day the Earth Stood Still
critics_consensus: Heavy on special effects, but without a coherent story at its base, The Day the Earth Stood Still is subpar re-imagining of the 1951 science-fiction classic.
Day Watch is frequently cheesy but it offers enough twists, surprises, and inventive action sequences to maintain viewer interest.
Though it arrives during an unfortunate glut of vampire movies, Daybreakers offers enough dark sci-fi thrills -- and enough of a unique twist on the genre -- to satisfy filmgoers.
The opening's got a great fiery explosion and Stallone puts in another earnest, sympathetic performance, but all else in Daylight feels designed to annoy the audience into submission.
This poorly executed brit crime caper wants to be a Guy Ritchie film, but ends up more like an extended Eastenders episode.
An elegantly acted art house film about a middle class couple's struggle to hold their lives together, Days and Cloud is both sensitive and engrossing.
Days of Glory is a powerful historical epic that pays homage to a valiant group of soldiers whose sacrifices have largely been forgotten.
Illuminated by magic hour glow and wistful performances, Days of Heaven is a visual masterpiece that finds eloquent poetry in its spare scenario.
Days of Thunder has Tom Cruise and plenty of flash going for it, but they aren't enough to compensate for the stock plot, two-dimensional characters, and poorly written dialogue.
Featuring an excellent ensemble cast, a precise feel for the 1970s, and a killer soundtrack, Dazed and Confused is a funny, affectionate, and clear-eyed look at high school life.

movie_title: De rouille et d'os (Rust and Bone)
critics_consensus: Surging on strong performances from Marion Cotillard and Matthias Schoenaerts, Rust and Bone is as vibrant and messily unpredictable as life itself.

movie_title: De zaak Alzheimer (The Memory of a Killer)
critics_consensus: Even though The Memory of a Killer is standard genre fare, it is also engaging and stylish.
Poor performances, stiff dialogue, flat characters, and an unimaginative stab at the mood of the Guy Ritchie crime caper make Dead Man Running into a hooligan tale with little to offer.
An uninspired, feebly-acted horror/comedy that produces little scares and laughs.
The delightfully gonzo tale of a lovestruck teen and his zombified mother, Dead Alive is extremely gory and exceedingly good fun, thanks to Peter Jackson's affection for the tastelessly sublime.
While decidedly not for all tastes, Dead Man marks an alluring change of pace for writer-director Jim Jarmusch that demonstrates an assured command of challenging material.
While the fine cast keeps Dead Man Down watchable throughout, the film is weighted down by absurd plot twists and a slack pace.
Not much of a story.
Though enhanced by cramped, gritty camerawork, this unsettling look at violence and revenge lacks the provocative edge needed to give it a substantial kick.
Affecting performances from the young cast and a genuinely inspirational turn from Robin Williams grant Peter Weir's prep school drama top honors.
While it offers its fair share of violent thrills and tough wit, The Dead Pool ends the Dirty Harry series on an uninspired note.
Dead Ringers serves up a double dose of Jeremy Irons in service of a devilishly unsettling concept and commandingly creepy work from director David Cronenberg.
More tasteful than recent slasher flicks, but Dead Silence is undone by boring characters, bland dialogue, and an unnecessary and obvious twist ending.
Though it doesn't cover new ground, Dead Snow is an entertaining mix of camp, scares, and blood and guts.

movie_title: Dead Snow 2: Red vs. Dead (DÃ¸d snÃ¸ 2)
critics_consensus: Dead Snow 2: Red vs. Dead expands the original's canvas without sacrificing any of its bloody fun, adding up to a sequel that fans of the first are bound to enjoy.
The Dead Zone combines taut direction from David Cronenberg and and a rich performance from Christopher Walken to create one of the strongest Stephen King adaptations.
Dear Frankie is a small, good-hearted film with fine performances.
Built from many of the same ingredients as other Nicholas Sparks tearjerkers, Dear John suffers from its cliched framework, as well as Lasse Hallstrom's curiously detached directing.
A film with numerous ideas but little grasp of how to effectively communicate them, Dear Wendy lacks the intelligence or insight that its difficult subject matter demands.
Dear White People adds a welcome new voice to cinema's oft-neglected discussion of race, tackling its timely themes with intelligence, honesty, and gratifyingly sharp wit.
Death At A Funeral is a rousing British farce, with enough slapstick silliness to overcome its faults.
It's amusing and it assembles a talented cast, but Neil LaBute's surprisingly faithful remake of the 2007 Frank Oz dramedy ultimately falls short of the original.
Hawn and Streep are as fabulous as Death Becomes Her's innovative special effects; Zemeckis' satire, on the other hand, is as hollow as the world it mocks.
Pretty but dull, with unconvincing turns from Zeta-Jones and Pearce. If you want a period magician movie, seek out The Prestige or The Illusionist instead.

movie_title: Death of a Cyclist (Muerte de un ciclista)

critics_consensus: In this unconvincing fictional documentary, the tense 30 minutes that lead into the title event is outweighed by the boring, melodramatic hour preceding it.
Death Proof may feel somewhat minor in the context of Tarantino's larger filmography, but on its own merits, it packs just enough of a wallop to deliver sufficiently high-octane grindhouse goods.
Mindless, violent, and lightning-paced, Death Race is little more than an empty action romp.
Death Race 2000 is a fun, campy classic, drawing genuine thrills from its mindless ultra-violence.

movie_title: Da uomo a uomo (Death Rides A Horse) (As Man to Man)

critics_consensus: A nonsensical plot and an absurd amount of violence make this revenge pic gratuitous and overwrought.
The talent involved can't save a script that has nowhere to go with its promising premise.
Death Wish is undeniably exploitation fare -- and also undeniably effective.

movie_title: Death Wish V: The Face of Death

critics_consensus: Lacking enough material for a full-length movie, D.E.B.S. is short on both plot and laughs.
December Boys' location and settings are invitingly gorgeous, but the coming-of-age drama that takes place on them is uneventful and far too sentimental.
Deception is a middling, predictable potboiler with mediocre dialogue and ludicrous plot twists.

movie_title: Deceptive Practice: The Mysteries and Mentors of Ricky Jay

critics_consensus: Relying on flat humor and a preposterous plot, Deck the Halls is an unnecessarily mean-spirited holiday movie that does little to put viewers in a holiday mood.

movie_title: The Decline of Western Civilization Part II: The Metal Years

critics_consensus: Mandy Moore and Billy Crudup's lack of chemistry in Dedication makes it hard to maintain interest in this confused love story.
A well-acted film noir with arresting visuals.

movie_title: The Deep End of the Ocean

critics_consensus: A tidal wave of melodrama sinks Deep Impact's chance at being the memorable disaster flick it aspires to be.
The kinetic camerawork and brutal over-the-top gore that made Dario Argento famous is on full display, but the addition of a compelling, complex story makes Deep Red a masterpiece.
Viewers will welcome being whisked away to this magical world of exotic sea life.
Defendor's reach occasionally exceeds its grasp, but this unique take on the superhero genre is held together by Woody Harrelson's solid performance.

movie_title: Defence of the Realm (Defense of the Realm)

critics_consensus: Professionally made but artistically uninspired, Ed Zwick's story of Jews surviving WWII in the Belarus forest lacks the emotional punch of the actual history.
Tony Scott tries to combine action, science fiction, romance, and explosions into one movie, but the time travel conceit might be too preposterous and the action falls apart under scrutiny.
Delgo features a blend of plot elements from earlier (and superior) fantasy films, with weaker animation and dull characters.
Director Jean-Pierre Jeunet deftly combines horror, sci-fi, and humor in Delicatessen, a morbid comedy set in a visually ravishing futuristic dystopia.
Though Union and LL Cool J are appealing romantic leads, Deliver Us From Eva is too predictable and contrived.

Deliver Us From Evil is a superb documentary and a searing look at an institution protecting its leaders at the expense of its followers. A profoundly disturbing chronicle of a wolf in sheep's clothing, the film builds a clear-eyed case against pedophile priest Oliver O'Grady, and the Catholic bureaucracy that protected him. The recollections of O'Grady's victims are nothing short of shocking and heartbreaking.
Director Scott Derrickson continues to have a reliably firm grasp on creepy atmosphere, but Deliver Us from Evil's lack of original scares is reflected in its shopworn title.
It has an undeniably sweet charm, and Vince Vaughn is eminently likable in the lead role, but The Delivery Man suffers in comparison to Starbuck, the hit Canadian comedy that inspired it.
Musical numbers save movie from cliches.
Too afraid to be a real satire of the Iraq War, Delta Farce instead devolves into a reprehensible, unfunny mix of slapstick, gay panic, and flatulence jokes.
A better-than-average sci-fi shoot-em-up with a satirical undercurrent, Demolition Man is bolstered by strong performances by Sylvester Stallone, Wesley Snipes, and Sandra Bullock.
A stylish but convoluted mess without any sympathetic characters.
Walter Matthau does a nice job as Mr. Wilson, but Dennis the Menace follows the Home Alone formula far too closely.
Featuring outstanding work from an excellent cast, The Departed is a thoroughly engrossing gangster drama with the gritty authenticity and soupy morality we come to expect from Martin Scorsese.
With miscast stars, a ludicrous plot and an obvious twist, Derailed embodies its name all too aptly.
Derrida's intelligence and engaging personality make him an intriguing documentary subject.
Deft direction and strong performances from its all-female cast guide The Descent, a riveting, claustrophobic horror film.
Although the presentation is sometimes clumsy, the compelling interviews and story make Desert Bayou always informative and enthralling.
Desk Set reunites one of cinema's most well-loved pairings for a solidly crafted romantic comedy that charmingly encapsulates their timeless appeal.
Desperately Seeking Susan works with its fairy tale depiction of New York and the fun, frothy chemistry generated by its two leads.
Despicable Me 2 offers plenty of eye-popping visual inventiveness and a number of big laughs.
Detachment's heart is in the right place, but overall it doesn't offer any solutions to its passionate ranting.

movie_title: Detective Dee and the Mystery of the Phantom Flame

critics_consensus: Silly plot, over-the-top directing style.
Detropia takes a comprehensive yet intimate -- and above all devastatingly powerful -- look at the rise and economic ruin of an American city.
According to critics, Deuce Bigalow is just too dumb and filled with old, tired gags.
A witless follow-up to the surprise 1999 hit, Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo is raunchy, politically incorrect, and not particularly funny.
Melodramatic and weighted down with silly dialogue, Deuces Wild is a forgettable, overheated thriller that leaves no cliche unturned.
It's better than many of the other films M. Night Shyamalan has been associated with, but Devil never gets more than a few low-budget thrills out of its fiendishly promising premise.
The Devil Came on Horseback is both a strong primer on the complexities of the situation in Darfur and a harrowing first-person doc.
Humor, interesting characters, and attention to details make the stylish Devil in a Blue Dress an above average noir.
Though it is ultimately somewhat undone by its own lofty ambitions, The Devil's Advocate is a mostly effective blend of supernatural thrills and character exploration.

movie_title: The Devil's Backbone (El Espinazo del diablo)
critics_consensus: Creepily atmospheric and haunting, The Devil's Backbone is both a potent ghost story and an intelligent political allegory.
Derivative and mostly uninspired, Devil's Due adds little to either the found-footage or horror genres that it's content to mimic.
Devil's Knot covers fact-based ground that's already been well-traveled with multiple (and far more compelling) documentaries.

movie_title: Devils on the Doorstep (Guizi lai le)

critics_consensus: Zombie has improved as a filmmaker since "House of 1000 Corpses" and will please fans of the genre, but beware -- the horror is nasty, relentless, and sadistic.
This thoughtful if rough hewn doc about death row inmates who discover Buddhism inspires hope that all of us are worthy of redemption.

Dial M for Murder may be slightly off-peak Hitchcock, but by any other standard, it's a sophisticated, chillingly sinister thriller -- and one that boasts an unforgettable performance from Grace Kelly to boot.
Diamonds are Forever is a largely derivative affair, but it's still pretty entertaining nonetheless, thanks to great stunts, witty dialogue, and the presence of Sean Connery.
Naomi Watts tries hard in the title role, but Diana buries her efforts under a shoddy script and clumsy direction.

movie_title: Diana Vreeland: The Eye Has To Travel
critics_consensus: An affectionate portrait created with visual flair, Diana Vreeland is entertaining, informative, and stylish, due in large part to its charismatic subject.
As Diary of the Dead proves, time hasn't subdued George A. Romero's affection for mixing politics with gore, nor has it given him cinematic grace or subtlety.

movie_title: Diary of a Chambermaid (Le journal d'une femme de chambre)
Diary of a Mad Black Woman
critics_consensus: Tyler Perry's successful play can't make the move to the screen; this mix of slapstick, melodrama and spirituality lacks a consistent tone.
Unlike its bestselling source material, Diary of a Wimpy Kid fails to place a likable protagonist at the center of its middle-school humor -- and its underlying message is drowned out as a result.

movie_title: Diary of a Wimpy Kid 2: Rodrick Rules
critics_consensus: Moderately witty and acceptably acted, Diary of a Wimpy Kid 2 isn't much worse than the first installment.

movie_title: Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Dog Days
critics_consensus: Overly familiar and a bit too reliant on slapstick, the sitcom-like Dog Days fails to improve upon previous installments and will likely appeal to few outside its target audience.
A so-so David Spade comedy with a few laughs.
Its action may be bit too over-the-top for some, but Die Another Day is lavishly crafted and succeeds in evoking classic Bond themes from the franchise's earlier installments.
Its many imitators (and sequels) have never come close to matching the taut thrills of the definitive holiday action classic.

It lacks the fresh thrills of its predecessor, but Die Hard 2 still works as an over-the-top -- and reasonably taut -- big-budget sequel, with plenty of set pieces to paper over the plot deficiencies.
Die Hard with a Vengeance benefits from Bruce Willis and Samuel L. Jackson's barbed interplay, but clatters to a bombastic finish in a vain effort to cover for an overall lack of fresh ideas.
Die Wand (The Wall) preserves its source material's thought-provoking themes -- and serves as a brilliant showcase for Martina Gedeck, whose performance carries the film.

So you wanna be a rock 'n' roll star? Dig! compellingly chronicles the ups and downs of the Dandy Warhols and the Brian Jonestown Massacre, two ambitious bands whose love/hate relationship embodies many of the potential pratfalls of the music business.
Though the plot may be familiar, Diggers is just pleasant, charming, and heartwarming enough to make it worth your while.

movie_title: Dil Bole Hadippa! (My Heart Goes Hooray!)
Dim Sum: A Little Bit of Heart

critics_consensus: This low-key comedy about memory loss offers mild pleasures but is too bland to fully resonate.
It doesn't honor its source material -- or its immensely likable leads -- as well as it should, but Dinner for Schmucks offers fitfully nourishing comedy.

movie_title: The Dinner Game (Le DÃ®ner de cons)

critics_consensus: It's undeniably slanted and doesn't cover as much of the story as it should, but Dinosaur 13 makes for gripping documentary viewing, flaws and all.
For filmgoers who value character development and smart dialogue over plot, Diplomacy yields rich, powerfully acted rewards.
Like its winsome characters, Dirty Dancing uses impressive choreography and the power of song to surmount a series of formidable obstacles.
Cheesy, unnecessary remake.
Amoral on the surface and exuding testosterone, The Dirty Dozen utilizes combat and its staggering cast of likable scoundrels to deliver raucous entertainment.
As tough and taciturn as its no-nonsense hero, Dirty Harry delivers a deceptively layered message without sacrificing an ounce of its solid action impact.
The laugh-free Dirty Love is a comedy dead zone -- it's aggressively crude and shoddily constructed.
An illuminating and nuanced film about the exploitation of illegal immigrants.
A buoyant, clever update of the conman flick Bedtime Story, with plenty of comedic jousting resulting from a winning chemistry between Michael Caine and Steve Martin.
John Waters casts his provocative eye toward libido in a sex satire that won't leave audiences feeling too Dirty, but this sophomoric farce doesn't strike a nerve like his best work -- a real Shame.

Some viewers may find fault with director Rick Rowley's filmmaking methods, but they aren't distracting enough to keep Dirty Wars from serving as a terribly compelling argument against elements of American foreign policy.
Disappearances benefits from a well-cast Kris Kristofferson in the lead role, but his presence isn't always enough to disguise an increasingly nonsensical story.

Returning to their seemingly bottomless well of flatulence humor, racial stereotypes, and stale pop culture gags, Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer have produced what is arguably their worst Movie yet.
It's didactic in spots and melodramatic in others, but Disconnect's strong cast helps make it a timely, effective exploration of modern society's technological overload.

movie_title: The Discreet Charm Of The Bourgeoisie (Le Charme Discret de la Bourgeoisie)

critics_consensus: Featuring outstanding performances from John Malkovich and newcomer Jessica Haines, Disgrace is a disturbing, powerful drama.
A feel good movie without an abundance of mush.
Sweet, beautifully filmed, and admirably short on sugarcoating, Bears continues Disneynature's winning streak.
Chimpanzee often anthropomorphizes its subjects, but it's a beautifully filmed, remarkably intimate look at the lives of a family of primates.
With its spectacular and extensive footage, Earth is both informative and entertaining.
Oceans adds another visually stunning chapter to the Disney Nature library.
A highly entertaining entry in Disney's renaissance era," Aladdin is beautifully drawn, with near-classic songs and a cast of scene-stealing characters.
District 13 bites off more than it can chew with its political subtext and questionable script, but the many action sequences are never less than entertaining.
Technically brilliant and emotionally wrenching, District 9 has action, imagination, and all the elements of a thoroughly entertaining science-fiction classic.
A nonstop thrill ride, District B13's dizzying action sequences more than make up for any expository flaws.
Aside from its clichÃ©d resolution, Disturbia is a tense, subtle thriller with a noteworthy performance from Shia LaBeouf.
It doesn't even feign impartiality, but this family-made documentary about the famously rabble-rousing attorney shines a light on the life and times of a divisive public figure.
With an adherence to YA formula that undercuts its individualistic message, Divergent opens its planned trilogy in disappointingly predictable fashion.
Divided We Fall takes a complex look at World War II, skillfully balancing humor and gravity.

movie_title: Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood
critics_consensus: Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood is more melodramatic than emotionally truthful, and uneven in its mixture of time periods, actresses, laughter and tears.

movie_title: Dixie Chicks - Shut Up and Sing
critics_consensus: Though ostensibly an intimate look at the Dixie Chicks after their 2003 anti-Bush remark, the film achieves broader relevance by exploring how media, politics, and celebrities intertwine.
Bold, bloody, and stylistically daring, Django Unchained is another incendiary masterpiece from Quentin Tarantino.
