critics_consensus: While fans of the Hasbro toy franchise may revel in a bit of nostalgia, G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra is largely a cartoonish, over-the-top action fest propelled by silly writing, inconsistent visual effects, and merely passable performances.

movie_title: Gianni e le donne (The Salt of Life)

critics_consensus: Giant earns its imposing name with a towering narrative supported by striking cinematography, big ideas, and powerful work from a trio of legendary Hollywood leads.
It may not be one of Vincente Minnelli's best, but the charming and flawlessly acted Gigi still offers enough visual and musical treats to satisfy.
Bizarre and clumsily plotted, Gigli is a mess. As for its stars, Affleck and Lopez lack chemistry.
In spite of its obvious good intentions -- and the compelling true story that inspired it -- the heavy-handed Gimme Shelter can't overcome its cliche-riddled script.
Thanks to energetic performances from its young leads, Gimme The Loot captures a slice of city life with warmth and exuberance.
Elle Fanning gives a terrific performance in this powerful coming-of-age tale about a pair of teenage girls whose friendship is unnerved by the threat of nuclear war.
The strong female cast and biting satire of teenage life makes Ginger Snaps far more memorable than your average werewolf movie -- or teen flick.

movie_title: La Fille CoupÃ©e en Deux (The Girl Cut in Two) (A Girl Cut in Two)
critics_consensus: Nouvelle Vague master Claude Chabrol balances subtle stabs of humor and biting class criticism to explore a love story and the seedier side of the haute bourgeois.

movie_title: La Fille de Monaco (The Girl from Monaco)
critics_consensus: Undeniably slight, this satiric thriller suffers from an uneven tone and a relative lack of thrills, but solid performances from the cast help keep it afloat.
Despite a well-intentioned and novel premise, Girl in Progress is plagued by jarring tonal shifts and does little to break its characters out of clichÃ©.
Angelina Jolie gives an intense performance, but overall Girl, Interrupted suffers from thin, predictable plotting that fails to capture the power of its source material.
Largely witless and disappointingly dull, Girl Most Likely strands the gifted Kristen Wiig in a blandly hollow foray into scattershot sitcom territory.

movie_title: The Girl Who Played with Fire (Flickan som lekte med elden)
critics_consensus: Noomi Rapace and Michael Nyqvist remain extraordinarily well-suited to their roles, but the second installment in Stieg Larsson's Millennium Trilogy doesn't pack quite as much punch as the first.
Visually arresting, but the story could be told with a bit more energy.
Amanda Seyfried is magnetic in Red Riding Hood's starring role, but she's let down by her uninspired leading men and a painfully cliched script.
Michelle Rodriguez gives a compelling performance, despite lack of a boxing background; Karyn Kusama packs a punch with this directorial debut.
Steven Soderbergh's latest lo-fi production is strikingly crafted but emotionally vague.
An intimate, compassionate look at two teenagers in juvenile hall.
The well-acted Girls Can't Swim is a sensitive depiction of two girls' coming-of-age.

movie_title: Girls Just Want to Have Fun

critics_consensus: Vulgar but entertaining camp.
Though he may be preaching to the choir, Keating provides plenty of evidence to back his claims about the former NYC mayor.

movie_title: Donne-moi la main (Give Me Your Hand)

critics_consensus: Ridley Scott and an excellent cast successfully convey the intensity of Roman gladitorial combat as well as the political intrigue brewing beneath.

movie_title: Glass: A Portrait of Philip in Twelve Parts

critics_consensus: Due to obvious plot twists and foreshadowing, The Glass House fails to thrill. By the end, it degenerates into ludicrousness.
The unconverted will remain just as perplexed as ever, but for gleeful Gleeks, The 3D Concert Movie delivers exactly what it promises.
The heartrendingly honest Glen Campbell: I'll Be Me offers a window into Alzheimer's that should prove powerful viewing for Campbell fans and novices alike.
Glen or Glenda? remains an interesting artifact from one of Hollywood's more colorful careers -- albeit not one that holds up particularly well as a movie.
This adaptation of David Mamet's play is every bit as compelling and witty as its source material, thanks in large part to a clever script and a bevy of powerhouse actors.
Glitter is a hodgepodge of movie cliches and bad acting that's sure to generate unintentional laughs. Unfortunately, the movie is not bad enough to be good.

Marvelously directed by Sebastian Lelio and beautifully led by a powerful performance from Paulina Garcia, Gloria takes an honest, sweetly poignant look at a type of character that's all too often neglected in Hollywood.
While it has moments of inspiration, Gnomeo and Juliet is often too self-referential for its own good.
Meandering and diffuse, Go for Sisters proves a letdown for all but the most ardent John Sayles enthusiasts.
Go Tigers! is both an absorbing and evenhanded documentary, a perceptive look into the world of high school sports and its impact on a community.
A darkly comic polemic on modern culture, God Bless America is uneven and somewhat this but the ideas behind this revenge fulfillment journey has primal appeal.
Not just a powerful telling of the journey of exiled Sudanese boys, God Grew Tired of Us is also a poignant account of the determination of the human spirit.
While it may strike harder-hearted viewers as excessively twee, God Help the Girl floats by on its sweet charm and talented cast.
God Said, Ha! plumbs poignant depths, but Julia Sweeney's sharp, graceful wit makes this one-woman monologue a wise, big-hearted burst of uplifting -- and perhaps therapeutic -- entertainment.
One of Hollywood's greatest critical and commercial successes, The Godfather gets everything right; not only did the movie transcend expectations, it established new benchmarks for American cinema.
Drawing on strong performances by Al Pacino and Robert De Niro, Francis Ford Coppola's continuation of Mario Puzo's Mafia saga set new standards for sequels that have yet to be matched or broken.

The final installment of The Godfather saga recalls its predecessors' power when it's strictly business, but underwhelming performances and confused tonality brings less closure to the Corleone story.
Filled with two-dimensional characters and pompous self-righteousness, Gods and Generals is a long, tedious sit. Some may also take offense at the pro-Confederate slant.
Gods and Monsters is a spellbinding, confusing piece of semi-fiction, featuring fine performances; McKellen leads the way, but Redgrave and Fraser don't lag far behind.

movie_title: The Gods Must Be Crazy II
Gods of the Plague (Gotter der Pest)

critics_consensus: Well-cast but frustratingly clichÃ©d, God's Pocket fails to strike a sensible balance between comedy and drama.
A murky thriller with few chills, Godsend features ludicrous dialogue, by-the-numbers plotting, and an excess of cheap shocks.
Without compelling characters or heart, Godzilla stomps on everything that made the original (or any monster movie worth its salt) a classic.

movie_title: Godzilla, Mothra and King Ghidorah: Giant Monsters All-Out Attack
Godzilla Vs Mechagodzilla II (Gojira VS Mekagojira)

critics_consensus: More than straight monster-movie fare, Gojira offers potent, sobering postwar commentary.
Godzilla 2000 is cheesy, laughable, and good entertaining fun.
With just enough human drama to anchor the sweeping spectacle of giant monsters smashing everything in sight, Gareth Edwards' Godzilla satisfyingly restores the franchise's fire-breathing glory.

movie_title: Godzilla and Mothra: The Battle for Earth (Gojira vs. Mosura)
Godzilla vs. King Ghidorah (Gojira tai Kingu GidorÃ¢)
Godzilla vs. Space Godzilla (Gojira vs. Supesugojira)

critics_consensus: Bing Crosby and Barry Fitzgerald are eminently likable, and film is pleasantly sentimental, but Going My Way suffers from a surplus of sweetness.
Much like a bad trip to the mall, Going Shopping starts out fun but eventually degenerates into a shallow and unsatisfying experience.
This sequel is full of lavish costumes and elaborate sets, but lacks the heart and creativity of the original Elizabeth
Coming from the Merchant-Ivory team, The Golden Bowl is visually stunning, but the filmmakers have difficulty in transporting the characterizations of the Henry James novel to the screen.
Slow-moving but ultimately rewarding, Golden Door is a profound drama with scenes of fantastical magical realism, lively humor, and stunning images.
The first and best Pierce Brosnan Bond film, GoldenEye brings the series into a more modern context, and the result is a 007 entry that's high-tech, action-packed, and urbane.

Goldfinger is where James Bond as we know him comes into focus - it features one of 007's most famous lines ("A martini. Shaken, not stirred") and a wide range of gadgets that would become the series' trademark.
Portraying organised crime with an unflinching realism, this gritty and searing Italian crime masterpiece pulls no punches.
Ben Affleck proves his directing credentials in this gripping dramatic thriller, drawing strong performances from the excellent cast and bringing working-class Boston to the screen.
Sloppy, formulaic, and unfunny, Gone Fishin' marks a painful low point in the careers of its two talented leads.
Dark, intelligent, and stylish to a fault, Gone Girl plays to director David Fincher's sick strengths while bringing the best out of stars Ben Affleck and Rosamund Pike.
Filmed and presented on a scale not seen in modern productions, Gone with the Wind is, if not the definitive Hollywood film, then certainly near the top of the list.

movie_title: Gonzo: The Life and Work of Hunter S. Thompson
critics_consensus: While not the comprehensive profile of the man that his die-hard fans might have hoped for, Gonzo remains an insightful introduction to the life of rebellious writer Hunter S. Thompson and his influences.

Good Burger might please hardcore fans of the 1990s Nickelodeon TV series that launched leads Kenan and Kel to stardom, but for all others, it will likely prove a comedy that is neither satisfyingly rare nor well done.
Funny and poignant social critique of German reunification.

movie_title: A Good Day to Be Black & Sexy

critics_consensus: Marianna Palka's quirky indie debut centred on two dysfunctional loners is hit and miss, but has enough originality to see it through.
Though Steven Soderbergh succeeds in emulating the glossy look of 1940s noirs, The Good German ultimately ends up as a self-conscious exercise in style that forgets to develop compelling characters.
The Good Guy has an attractive cast, but they aren't done any favors by the film's cardboard characters and cliched plot.
Funny, informative, and occasionally sad, Good Hair is a provocative look at the complex relationship between African Americans and their hair.
A shortage of laughs and an undercurrent of mean-spiritedness undermine Good Luck Chuck, squandering a decent premise on gross-out humor and shopworn slapstick.
A well-calibrated blend of manic comedy and poignant drama, Good Morning, Vietnam offers a captivating look at a wide range of Robin Williams' cinematic gifts.

movie_title: The Good Mother (The Price of Passion)

critics_consensus: That The Good Night is the work of a first-time writer/director is apparent, as the story feels disjointed and never connects with the audience.
Good Ol' Freda proves that even after all these years, some corners of Beatles history remain unexplored -- and just as fascinating as the chapters we all know by heart.
Though ambitious and confidently directed by Robert De Niro, The Good Shepherd is ultimately a tedious drama that holds few surprises and succumbs to self-seriousness.

It follows a predictable narrative arc, but Good Will Hunting adds enough quirks to the journey -- and is loaded with enough powerful performances -- that it remains an entertaining, emotionally rich drama.
This adaptation of Wilde's Lady Windermere's Fan lacks bite due to liberties taken with the source material, coupled with uneven performances.
A Good Year is a fine example of a top-notch director and actor out of their elements, in a sappy romantic comedy lacking in charm and humor.
Half-baked plot twists disorient rather than build drama.
An original and thoughtful human drama, Goodbye Solo looks at relationships and loneliness while proving director Ramin Bahrani's is an important American voice.

movie_title: The Goods: Live Hard, Sell Hard
critics_consensus: Despite the talent in front of and behind the camera, The Goods: Live Hard, Sell Hard largely misfires, proving a squandered opportunity for all involved.
Goon is a crude slapstick comedy with well-formed characters and a surprising amount of heart.
An energetic, sometimes noisy mix of Speilbergian sentiment and funhouse tricks that will appeal to kids and nostalgic adults alike.

movie_title: Gore Vidal: The United States Of Amnesia
Gorillas in the Mist: The Story of Dian Fossey

critics_consensus: A mixture of Upstairs, Downstairs, Clue, and perceptive social commentary, Gosford Park ranks among director Altman's best.
While it features outstanding musical numbers, The Gospel reduces a series of worthy themes -- faith, family, forgiveness -- to soapy, banal clichÃ©s.

movie_title: Il Vangelo Secondo Matteo (The Gospel According to St. Matthew)
critics_consensus: The Gospel According to St. Matthew forgoes the pageantry of biblical epics in favor of a naturalistic retelling of the Christ story, achieving a respectful if not reverent interpretation with political verve.
Gossip drags on far beyond its entertainment value.
Berry's acting talents can't save Gothika from its preposterous plot and bad dialogue.

movie_title: Gottfried Helnwein and the Dreaming Child

critics_consensus: Ornate costumes and a talented cast can't make up for Ghosts' glacial pace and confused plot.
A refreshing departure from the current crop of Iraq war dramas, Grace is Gone is a heartfelt, finely acted portrayal of grief and healing.
Gracie can be rousing and touching in spots, but is ultimately undone by its predictable story arc and a lack of nuance.
The music, the performances, the precision in capturing the post-college malaise -- The Graduate's coming-of-age story is indeed one for the ages.
Though a minor entry in Eastwood's body of work, Gran Torino is nevertheless a humorous, touching, and intriguing old-school parable.

movie_title: Grand Canyon Adventure: River at Risk

critics_consensus: Perhaps less a true film than a series of star-studded vignettes, Grand Hotel still remains an entertaining look back at a bygone Hollywood era.
Grand Piano is so tense in its best moments -- and appealingly strange overall -- that it remains rewarding in spite of its flaws.
Grand Theft Parsons pays tribute to a rock legend without following biopic formula -- and proves that a unique perspective doesn't always mean a worthwhile film.
A gross-out comedy that's more gross than comedic, Grandma's Boy is lazy and unrewarding.
A potent drama that is as socially important today as when it was made, The Grapes of Wrath is affecting, moving, and deservedly considered an American classic.

movie_title: Grave of the Fireflies (Hotaru no haka)
critics_consensus: An achingly sad anti-war film, Grave of the Fireflies is one of Studio Ghibli's most profoundly beautiful, haunting works.
Alfonso CuarÃ³n's Gravity is an eerie, tense sci-fi thriller that's masterfully directed and visually stunning.
Grease is a pleasing, energetic musical with infectiously catchy songs and an ode to young love that never gets old.
Grease 2 is undeniably stocked with solid songs and well-choreographed dance sequences, but there's no getting around the fact that it's a blatant retread of its far more entertaining predecessor.
A wonderful cast and top-notch script elevate The Great Debaters beyond a familiar formula for a touching, uplifting drama.
Charlie Chaplin demonstrates that his comedic voice is undiminished by dialogue in this rousing satire of tyranny, which may be more distinguished by its uplifting humanism than its gags.
Furnished with striking visual detail and told with great narrative economy by director David Lean, Great Expectations is an exemplary adaptation of Charles Dickens' dense and episodic novel.
Not the best version of the oft-filmed Dickens classic but far from the worst, Mike Newell's Great Expectations breathes just enough life into the source material to justify yet another adaptation.
The Great Muppet Caper is overplotted and uneven, but the appealing presence of Kermit, Miss Piggy and the gang ensure that this heist flick is always breezily watchable.

Set in post-9/11 New York, this largely evocative dramedy interweaves the stories of five disconnected individuals who share an unspoken emotional malaise that shadows their attempts at returning to normal life.
Though the climax of the film -- the actual raid -- is exciting, the rest of it is bogged down in too many subplots and runs on for too long.
The Great World Of Sound is a charming and unassuming film, thanks to breakthrough performances from Pat Healy and Kene Holiday.
This biopic is undeniably stylish, but loses points for excessive length, an overreliance on clichÃ©s, and historical inaccuracies.
Despite all the underdog sports movie conventions, the likable cast and lush production values make The Greatest Game Ever Played a solid and uplifting tale.
The Greatest Show on Earth is melodramatic, short on plot, excessively lengthy and bogged down with clichÃ©s, but not without a certain innocent charm.
It's not particularly subtle, but Greedy Lying Bastards is effective in questioning the motives of climate change deniers.
It's sporadically entertaining, but The Green Hornet never approaches the surreal heights suggested by a Michel Gondry/Seth Rogen collaboration.
Noisy, overproduced, and thinly written, Green Lantern squanders an impressive budget and decades of comics mythology.
Though The Green Mile is long, critics say it's an absorbing, emotionally powerful experience.
When it comes to the subculture of soccer thugs, Green Street Hooligans lacks sufficient insight, and instead comes off as a Fight Club knock-off.
Greenberg's title character is harder to like than most, but Ben Stiller's nuanced performance and a darkly funny script help take the misanthropic edge off.
Greenfingers follows the British feel-good formula of underdogs somehow beating the odds, adding nothing new to this already saturated genre.

movie_title: Greenwich Village: Music That Defined a Generation

critics_consensus: Slight yet resonant, Greetings from Tim Buckley honors a family's musical legacy while offering Penn Badgley a remarkable opportunity to display his dramatic gifts.
Whether you choose to see it as a statement on consumer culture or simply a special effects-heavy popcorn flick, Gremlins is a minor classic.
Gremlins 2 trades the spiky thrills of its predecessor for looney satire, yielding a succession of sporadically clever gags that add some flavor to a recycled plot.
Grey Gardens offers few new revelations about the eccentric Edie's, but is elevated thanks to powerhouse performances from Drew Barrymore and Jessica Lange.

movie_title: Greystoke: The Legend of Tarzan, Lord of the Apes

critics_consensus: The role of probation officer Sean Porter fits Dwayne "The Rock" Johnson like a glove; however, the execution is so cliched, the youths' stories (based on real events), fail to inspire.

movie_title: Touchez Pas au Grisbi (Hands Off the Loot)

critics_consensus: Whatever opinion you come to have of the obsessive Treadwell, Herzog has once again found a fascinating subject.

movie_title: Le fils de l'Ã©picier (The Grocer's Son)
critics_consensus: A noteworthy performance by Eric Guirado makes this gently pastoral film a moving coming-of-age story.
Director and star Burns returns to his home turf -- dialogue-driven examinations of the relationships between men and women -- with uneven results.
Though high on energy and great techno tunes, Groove's characters and plotlines are too cliched to be engaging.
A high-concept high school reunion movie with an adroitly cast John Cusack and armed with a script of incisive wit.
Smart, sweet, and inventive, Groundhog Day highlights Murray's dramatic gifts while still leaving plenty of room for laughs.
Grown Ups' cast of comedy vets is amiable, but they're let down by flat direction and the scattershot, lowbrow humor of a stunted script.
While it's almost certainly the movie event of the year for filmgoers passionate about deer urine humor, Grown Ups 2 will bore, annoy, and disgust audiences of nearly every other persuasion.
A diminished sequel that makes even less sense than The Grudge 1.
Grudge Match is sporadically funny but meandering, and its strong cast largely mired in a plot that's overrun with clichÃ©s.
A coming-of-age drama entwined with a political statement, In Bloom underscores its well-worn themes with strong performances and palpable real-world tension.
Guardians of the Galaxy is just as irreverent as fans of the frequently zany Marvel comic would expect -- as well as funny, thrilling, full of heart, and packed with visual splendor.

movie_title: Guerrilla: The Taking of Patty Hearst
critics_consensus: Guerilla is a riveting documentary that chronicles in enlightening fashion the 1974 kidnapping of heiress Patty Hearst.
Despite the chemistry of its stars, Guess Who, a loose remake of Guess Who's Coming to Dinner, lacks the political relevance of the original.
More well-intentioned than insightful in its approach to interracial marriage, Guess Who's Coming to Dinner succeeds thanks to the fizzy chemistry of its star-studded ensemble.
The filmmakers' motivations may be suspect, but this inside look at New York art legend Cindy Sherman -- and, by extension, the culture she inhabits -- is undeniably satisfying.
Though Jack Black is back doing what he does best, Gulliver's Travels largely fails to do any justice to its source material, relying instead on juvenile humor and special effects.
Equal parts absorbing and educational, Gun Hill Road wears its heart on its sleeve through tender performances that make up for its narrative familiarity.
A dark comedy of the low brow nature -- filled with fart and gay jokes. Even Liam Neeson and Sandra Bullock cannot save this failure.
Beastie Boy Adam Yauch proves his worth as a director with Gunnin' for That #1 Spot, a fun-filled chronicle of the top high school hoopsters of 2006.
Bolstered by a cast of memorable stars and an impressive sense of scale, The Guns of the Navarone fires with vivid characterization and entertaining spectacle.

movie_title: Guy and Madeline on a Park Bench
critics_consensus: Bursting with scrappy energy and shot with preternatural skill, Guy and Madeline on a Park Bench is an auspicious debut for director Damien Chazelle.
This coming-of-age story of alienated youth is too familiar.

movie_title: When the Road Bends: Tales of a Gypsy Caravan
critics_consensus: A dynamic doc following five Romani bands is a pleasure for the senses thanks to vibrant colors and eclectic music.
Zombie shows flashes of vision in the follow-up to his Halloween reboot, but they're smothered by mountains of gore and hackneyed, brutal violence.
Hackers has a certain stylish appeal, but its slick visuals and appealing young cast can't compensate for a clichÃ©d and disappointingly uninspired story.
Spiritedly performed by a groovy cast and imaginatively directed by Milos Forman, Hair transports audiences straight to the Age of Aquarius.
Hair High isn't first-tier Plympton, but like the rest of the animator's work, this is an assuredly odd tale that should resonate with fans of strange cinema.
Hairspray is an energetic, wholly entertaining musical romp; a fun Summer movie with plenty of heart. Its contagious songs will make you want to get up and start dancing.
You'd have to be high to dig Half Baked's half baked production and scattershot sense of humor -- although maybe that was the point of this Dave Chapelle-led joint.
Half Nelson features powerful performances from Ryan Gosling and Shareeka Epps. It's a wise, unsentimental portrait of lonely people at the crossroads.
While it doesn't quite do justice to the source material, Half of a Yellow Sun adapts Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie's novel with committed performances and narrative nuance.
Seagal is now too bulky to make a convincing action hero, and Half Past Dead is too silly and incoherent to deliver any visceral kicks.
Some filmgoers may be surprised by the Farrellys' defense of traditional domestic values in Hall Pass -- unfortunately, they'll probably also be dismayed by the absence of laughs.
Rob Zombie doesn't bring many new ideas to the table in Halloween, making it another bloody disappointment for fans of the franchise.

movie_title: Halloween 4: The Return of Michael Myers
critics_consensus: Halloween 4: The Return Of Michaels Myers may bring the series' masked killer back into the fold, but fails to offer the visceral scares and inventiveness of the original.

movie_title: Halloween 5: The Revenge of Michael Myers
critics_consensus: Halloween 5: The Revenge Of Michael Myers finds the series embracing crude slasher conventions with pedestrian scares, disposable characters, and aimless plotting.
Halloween: H2O is the best of the many sequels, yet still pales in comparison to the original Halloween.
Halloween II picks up where its predecessor left off - and quickly wanders into a dead end that the franchise would spend decades struggling to find its way out of.

movie_title: Halloween III: Season of the Witch
critics_consensus: Its laudable deviation from series formula not withstanding, Halloween III: Season Of The Witch offers paltry thrills and dubious plotting.
The only thing this tired slasher flick may resurrect is nostalgia for when the genre was still fresh and scary.

movie_title: Halloween - The Curse of Michael Myers (Halloween 6)
critics_consensus: Halloween: The Curse of Michael Myers trades the simple, brutal effectiveness of the original for convoluted mysticism, with disastrously dull results.
The script's biting premise and Steve Coogan's endearing, off-the-handle performance make Hamlet 2 an hysterical -- if slightly painful -- ride.
Though it begins with promise, Hancock suffers from a flimsy narrative and poor execution.
Handsome Harry offers more than enough of a satisfying actors' showcase for its impressively stocked cast to overcome a handful of storytelling struggles.

Though the screenplay and the novel it's based on were both written by the same person, critics say Hanging Up is an unsuccessful adaptation. The acting is praised as solid, but is ultimately unable to save the film.
Fantastic acting and crisply choreographed action sequences propel this unique, cool take on the revenge thriller.

movie_title: Hannah Montana/Miley Cyrus: Best of Both Worlds Concert Tour
critics_consensus: This high-energy concert film should please Cyrus' rabid pre-teen fan base -- and may come as a pleasant surprise for parents.
Smart, tender, and funny in equal measure, Hannah and Her Sisters is one of Woody Allen's finest films.
Led by a powerful performance from Barbara Sukowa, Hannah Arendt does a commendable job of dramatizing the life of a complex public figure.
While youthful Miley fans won't complain, Hannah Montana the Movie is little more than a formulaic Disney Channel episode stretched thin.
Although not terribly focused, Hannah Takes the Stairs contains refreshing realism.
Hannibal Rising reduces the horror icon to a collection of dime-store psychological traits.
Alternately bloody and silly, Hansel and Gretel: Witch Hunters fails as both a fantasy adventure and as a parody of same.
Happily N'Ever After has none of the moxy, edge, or postmodern wit of the other fairy-tales-gone-haywire CG movie it so blatantly rips off.
If nothing else, Happiness of the Katakuris scores points for its delirious, over-the-top originality.
Happy Accidents has enough quirkiness and charm to rise above the more formulaic entries in the romantic comedy genre.
Intelligent, well-acted, and satisfyingly low-key, Happy Christmas marks another step in prolific filmmaker Joe Swanberg's creative evolution.
Despite strong individual performances, the overlong, disjointed plot of Happy Endings self-indulgently rambles.
Visually dazzling, with a thoughtful storyline and catchy musical numbers, Happy Feet marks a successful animated debut from the makers of Babe.
The animation is as eye-popping as ever, but Happy Feet Two's narrative is too noisily incoherent to recapture the Oscar-winning charm of its predecessor.
Happy Here and Now has a rich setting and some interesting ideas, but the story frustratingly refuses to spark to life.

movie_title: Happy People: A Year in the Taiga
critics_consensus: Filled with breathtaking images of the foreboding Siberian countryside, Happy People: A Year in the Taiga is a fascinating look at an isolated society.
A smart, light-hearted romantic comedy, Happy, Texas uses its well-written script and exceptional cast to prove there's still life left in the fish-out-of-water caper genre.
Sober, even-handed, and quietly devastating, Happy Valley illuminates the wreckage of a tragedy while leaving viewers room to draw their own conclusions.
Hara-Kiri: Death of a Samurai adds an atypically restrained entry to the Takashi Miike filmography that loses little impact in favoring human drama over action.

Disturbing, controversial, but entirely engrossing, Hard Candy is well written with strong lead performances, especially that of newcomer Ellen Page. A movie that stays with the viewer long after leaving the theater.
An absorbing showcase for Philip Baker Hall, Paul Thomason Anderson's feature debut is a gamble that pays off handsomely.
Hard Rain is an implausible heist movie soaked in disaster movie trappings.
Hard Target gets a boost from John Woo's stylish direction, but at heart, it's still another silly, explosion-dependent action thriller in the Jean-Claude Van Damme oeuvre.
The Hard Way's overly familiar formula is enlivened by a witty script and the excellent comedic chemistry between Michael J. Fox and James Woods.
This caper flick lacks the originality necessary to elevate it above other films of its genre.
Although Hardball contains some touching moments, they are not enough to transcend the sports formula.
An all-star comedy lineup is wasted on a paper-thin plot and painfully clunky dialogue.

movie_title: Harley Davidson and the Marlboro Man

critics_consensus: Harmontown offers a look at an artist grappling with his own flaws -- as well as some interesting insights about the nature of hardcore fandom in the internet age.

movie_title: Harold & Kumar Escape from Guantanamo Bay
critics_consensus: It may not equal its predecessor, but Harold and Kumar Escape from Guantanamo Bay is still good for some laughs -- and food for thought.

movie_title: Harold & Kumar Go to White Castle
critics_consensus: The likable leads and subversion of racial stereotypes elevate Harold and Kumar above the typical stoner comedy.
Hal Ashby's comedy is too dark and twisted for some, and occasionally oversteps its bounds, but there's no denying the film's warm humor and big heart.
Though it presents the war in shockingly gritty, realistic terms, Harrison's Flowers uses such scenes as background for a trite love story.

movie_title: Harry and Walter Go to New York

critics_consensus: Its lurid violence may put off some viewers, but Harry Brown is a vigilante thriller that carries an emotional as well as a physical punch, thanks to a gripping performance from Michael Caine in the title role.

movie_title: Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets
critics_consensus: Though perhaps more enchanting for younger audiences, Chamber of Secrets is nevertheless both darker and livelier than its predecessor, expanding and improving upon the first film's universe.

movie_title: Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows - Part 1
critics_consensus: It can't help but feel like the prelude it is, but Deathly Hallows: Part I is a beautifully filmed, emotionally satisfying penultimate installment for the Harry Potter series.

movie_title: Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows - Part 2
critics_consensus: Thrilling, powerfully acted, and visually dazzling, Deathly Hallows Part II brings the Harry Potter franchise to a satisfying -- and suitably magical -- conclusion.

movie_title: Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire
critics_consensus: The main characters are maturing, and the filmmakers are likewise improving on their craft; vibrant special effects and assured performances add up to what is the most complex yet of the Harry Potter films.

movie_title: Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince
critics_consensus: Dark, thrilling, and occasionally quite funny, Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince is also visually stunning and emotionally satisfying.

movie_title: Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix
critics_consensus: It's not easy to take the longest Harry Potter book and streamline it into the shortest HP movie, but director David Yates does a bang up job of it, creating an Order of the Phoenix that's entertaining and action-packed.

movie_title: Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban
critics_consensus: Under the assured direction of Alfonso Cuaron, Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban triumphantly strikes a delicate balance between technical wizardry and complex storytelling.

movie_title: Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone
critics_consensus: Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone adapts its source material faithfully while condensing the novel's overstuffed narrative into an involving -- and often downright exciting -- big-screen magical caper.
Despite a dedicated performance by Christian Bale, Harsh Times suffers from a heavy-handed and overly bleak plot.
Well-made and solidly acted, Hart's War is modestly compelling. However, the movie suffers from having too many subplots.
Harvard Beats Yale 29-29 is compelling viewing even though it spoils the score of the titular college football matchup - and even if you aren't a fan of the sport.
Harvard Man is a pretentious, incoherent mess.
The over-the-top gore, campy acting, and dim cinematography may be part of Hatchet's self-described old-school ethos, but irony alone can't sustain a horror film.

movie_title: Hatchet for the Honeymoon (Il rosso segno della follia)

critics_consensus: Funnier and more gleefully gory than most slasher sequels, Hatchet II aims for so-bad-it's-good territory, but can't quite hack it.
Kristen Wiig's vibrant performance is almost worth the price of admission -- and it has to be, because Hateship Loveship doesn't have much else going for it.
Neither scary nor funny, The Haunted Mansion is as lifeless as the ghosts in the movie.

movie_title: The Haunted World of El Superbeasto

critics_consensus: Haunter's premise is intriguing enough, though the film's too low budget to truly pull it off.
The Haunting of Molly Hartley is a rather lifeless horror endeavor, with a pedestrian plot and few scares.
House is a gleefully demented collage of grand guginol guffaws and bizarre sequences.

movie_title: HÃ¤xan (HÃ¤xan: Witchcraft Through the Ages) (The Witches)

critics_consensus: MMA star and first-time actress Gina Carano displays ample action-movie chops in Haywire, a fast-paced thriller with a top-notch cast and outstanding direction from Steven Soderbergh.

Though not without its flaws, He Got Game finds Spike Lee at or near the top of his late-period game, combining trenchant commentary with his signature visuals and a strong performance from Denzel Washington.

movie_title: He Loves Me, He Loves Me Not
critics_consensus: This romantic thriller puts Tautou's sweetheart Amelie image to good use.
Head of State squanders its potentially ripe premise with watered-down satire and formulaic gags.
Head On's narrative rambles at times, but its raw, sensual approach creates a powerful, resonant rumination on identity.
Grisly, twisty, and darkly comic, Headhunters is an exhilaratingly oddball take on familiar thriller elements.

movie_title: The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter

critics_consensus: Proving that it's neither better to burn out nor fade away, Neil Young: Heart of Gold works both as a concert film and a meditation on mortality.
Gripping and provocative psychological thriller about corporate responsibility remains tense throughout and despite its long running time.
A powerful, unflinching exploration of the Vietnam War, with first-person stories from both sides of the conflict, Hearts and Minds still hits the mark decades after its release.
Hearts in Atlantis is well-acted and beautiful to look at, but the movie is nothing more than a mood piece.

movie_title: Hearts of Darkness: A Filmmaker's Apocalypse
critics_consensus: Chronicling the filming of Apocalypse Now through Eleanor Coppola's empathetic and frank point of view, Hearts of Darkness is a revelatory investigation of moviemaking and how creative obsession can impact an artist's family.
Dark, cynical, and subversive, Heathers gently applies a chainsaw to the conventions of the high school movie -- changing the game for teen comedies to follow.
The story is the weakest link in this gorgeous and well-acted film.
Heaven Is for Real boasts a well-written screenplay and a talented cast, but overextends itself with heavy-handed sequences depicting concepts it could have trusted the audience to take on faith.
Dark, stylish, and captivating, Heavenly Creatures signals both the auspicious debut of Kate Winslet and the arrival of Peter Jackson as more than just a cult director.
Heaven's Gate contains too many ideas and striking spectacle to be a disaster, but this western buckles under the weight of its own sprawl.

Despite being a Gonzo-esque rockumentary following the fortunes of Iraq's one and only heavy metal band, Acrassicauda, Heavy Metal is actually a moving and impassioned account of the middle-east crisis.

movie_title: Hector And The Search For Happiness
critics_consensus: Simon Pegg remains as charming as ever, but Hector and the Search for Happiness drowns his appeal in schmaltz.
Hedwig and the Angry Inch may very well be the next Rocky Horror midnight movie. It not only knows how to rock, but Hedwig's story has an emotional poignancy.
Yet another movie about relationships in the Big Apple, Heights is never dull thanks to a competent cast.
Lackluster performances and fluff humor can't keep this wreck from sinking.

There's no denying the seriousness of Heli's story or the raw power of its more uncomfortable moments, but they're used in service of a grimly alienating film that many viewers may ultimately find unrewarding.
Though its brand of immature comedy may appeal to some, Hell Baby misses the mark with much of its humor, rendering it a largely ineffective -- and often crass -- genre sendup.
A fascinating, even-handed account of Hell Houses.
Hellbound: Hellraiser II retains the twisted visual thrill of its predecessor, although seams in the plot are already starting to show.
With wit, humor and Guillermo del Toro's fantastic visuals, the entertaining Hellboy transcends the derivative nature of the genre.
Guillermo del Toro crafts a stellar comic book sequel, boasting visuals that are as imaginative as the characters are endearing.
Though Streisand charms, she's miscast as the titular middle-aged widow in Gene Kelly's sluggish and over-produced final directorial effort.
Hello I Must Be Going offers an offbeat twist to the romance genre, a solid character study for fans of grown-up drama, and a career-making breakout vehicle for Melanie Lynskey.

movie_title: Hello Mary Lou: Prom Night II

critics_consensus: Elevated by writer-director Clive Barker's fiendishly unique vision, Hellraiser offers a disquieting - and sadistically smart - alternative to mindless gore.

movie_title: Henri Langlois: The Phantom of the Cinematheque
Henry: Portrait of a Serial Killer
critics_consensus: Henry: Portrait of a Serial Killer is an effective, chilling profile of a killer that is sure to shock and disturb.
Full of Hallmark-truisms and pop songs presented with strained significance, this comic foible intends less to convert than to preach to the choir.

movie_title: Henry V (The Chronicle History of King Henry the Fift with His Battell Fought at Agincourt in France)
critics_consensus: A patriotic booster, Laurence Olivier's directorial debut and star turn as Henry V result in a sharply realized and resonant take on Shakespeare's deeply British warrior king.
Supporting actors Vera Farmiga and James Caan give the movie a little heft, but Henry's Crime is an otherwise predictable heist/comedy with slow pacing.
Sweet, soulful, and smart, Spike Jonze's Her uses its just-barely-sci-fi scenario to impart wryly funny wisdom about the state of modern human relationships.
While perhaps not as probing as it could have been, Megumi Sasaki's languidly paced documentary is as entertaining as it is inspiring.
Precious to a fault, Wild Grass finds 88-year-old director Alain Resnais as joyously unconstrained as ever.
Herbie: Fully Loaded is a decent kids movie that is pretty undemanding for adult viewers.
Fast-paced and packed with dozens of pop culture references, Hercules might not measure up with the true classics of the Disney pantheon, but it's still plenty of fun.
Hercules has Brett Ratner behind the cameras and Dwayne Johnson rocking the loincloth -- and delivers exactly what any reasonable person reading that description might expect.
Here Comes the Boom benefits from Kevin James's genial presence but the film doesn't deliver enough laughs to live up to its title -- or enough satisfying plot to make up the difference.
The power of Here Comes the Devil's atmospheric dread compels, but the plot and mystery are too muddled to leave a lasting impression.

Critics say Here on Earth's weakness comes from its script. The story may appeal to young teenage girls, but it suffers from being overly sentimental and formulaic. The cinematography, however, is lovely in how it captures its Minnesota setting.

Despite a thought-provoking premise and Clint Eastwood's typical flair as director, Hereafter fails to generate much compelling drama, straddling the line between poignant sentimentality and hokey tedium.
With death-defying action sequences and epic historic sweep, Hero offers everything a martial arts fan could ask for.

movie_title: He's Just Not That Into You
critics_consensus: Despite the best efforts of a talented cast, He's Just Not That Into You devotes too little time to each of its protagonists, thus reducing them to stereotypes.

movie_title: He's Way More Famous Than You

critics_consensus: It has a dark sense of humor and a refreshing lack of sentimentality, but like its title character, Hesher isn't really interested in going anywhere.
Bland, unoriginal, and lacking the wit of the TV series, Hey Arnold is a 30 min cartoon stretched beyond its running time.

movie_title: Hey, Boo: Harper Lee and 'To Kill a Mockingbird'

critics_consensus: Hick's talented young star is ill served by a film whose story wavers between discomfitingly inappropriate and simply muddled.
The scenery looks great, but this overstuffed horse story contains too much cheese.
A slow and steady samurai flick a la John Ford that brings emotions and psychology to an epic-scale adventure.
Cleverly written and directed, this is a tight, atmospheric and claustrophobic low budget British thriller.
There is indeed a good amount of tension in this French slasher, but the dubbing is bad and the end twist unbelievable.
Uneven but hilarious when it hits, this spoof of Hitchcock movies is a minor classic in the Mel Brooks canon.
A surprisingly sultry performance from Ally Sheedy elevates High Art from pretentious melodrama to compelling -- if still a little pretentious -- romance.
Ashley Judd and Morgan Freeman make this predictable affair watchable.
Clint Eastwood's sophomore outing as director sees him back in the saddle as a mysterious stranger, as the result is one of his most memorable Westerns.
High School Musical is brazenly saccharine, but it makes up for it with its memorable show tunes, eye-popping choreography, and appealing cast.
Surprisingly better than its predecessor, High School Musical 2 returns to enchant tweens with its snappy songs, wicked dance moves, and peppy spirit.
With Higher Ground, star and debuting director Vera Farmiga takes viewers on a challenging spiritual journey whose missteps are easily overcome by its many rich rewards.
It's hard to fault Higher Learning's goals; unfortunately, writer-director John Singleton too often struggles to fit his themes within a consistently engaging story.
People hate Highlander because it's cheesy, bombastic, and absurd. And people love it for the same reasons.
There should have been only one.

movie_title: Highlander III: The Sorcerer (Highlander: The Final Dimension)
critics_consensus: Borderline unwatchable and unspeakably dull, Highlander III is a sloppy third installment that still somehow manages to mark a slight improvement over its predecessor.
The fourth and supposedly last Highlander movie is a confusing mess, complete with bad acting and dialogue.
Brilliant performances, lush cinematography, and complex storytelling deserve audience's attention.
Faster paced for today's audiences, this Hills remake ratchets up the gore for the hardcore horror fans, but will turn away casual audiences.
The Hills Have Eyes 2 is a completely unoriginal sequel offers plenty of gore and clichÃ©s, but few scares.
Unlike the overproduced and overbudgeted Hollywood blockbusters, Himalaya is a stunningly photographed movie that offers an intimate look into the lives of a Dolpo tribe.
Himizu tells a coming-of-age story writ large, with powerfully realized characters used to explore impactful -- albeit uncomfortable -- ideas on a national scale.
Director Matt Ruskin's enthusiasm for the project is readily apparent, but his film is unfocused, meandering, and frustrating to watch.
Breezy, colorful, and suffused with joy, Hipsters offers audiences an engaging Cold War musical told from the other side of the Iron Curtain.
Distinguished by innovative technique and Emmanuelle Riva's arresting performance, Hiroshima Mon Amour is a poignant love story as well as a thoughtful meditation on international trauma.
Without the bite or the controversy of the source material, The Golden Compass is reduced to impressive visuals overcompensating for lax storytelling.
Anchored by stellar performances from Cary Grant and Rosalind Russell, His Girl Friday is a classic screwball romantic comedy.

movie_title: Historias que so existem quando lembradas (Found Memories)

critics_consensus: While not quite having the impact of its original stage version, The History Boys nevertheless is a witty and involving school drama.

A History of Violence raises compelling and thoughtful questions about the nature of violence, while representing a return to form for director David Cronenberg in one of his more uncharacteristic pieces.
Though Hit & Run has some surprisingly oft-kilter filmmaking, the action doesn't add to much and the writing's a bit smug.
This Odd Couple comedy misses more than hits in terms of laughs, and the plot twists make little sense.
Despite Hitch's predictability, Will Smith and Kevin James win praise for their solid, warmhearted performances.
Though it suffers from tonal inconsistency and a lack of truly insightful retrospection, Hitchcock is elevated by inspired performances from its two distinguished leads.
Sean Bean tries giving motive and emotion to The Hitcher, but director Dave Meyers is more interested in cheap shocks, and gratuitous gore and torture.

movie_title: The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy
critics_consensus: A frantic and occasional funny adaptation of Douglas Adams' novel. However, it may have those unfamiliar with the source material scratching their heads.
Hitman features the unfortunate combination of excessive violence, incoherent plot, and inane dialogue.
It certainly isn't subtle -- or even terribly smart -- but as a gleefully gory homage to low-budget exploitation thrillers, Hobo with a Shotgun packs plenty of firepower.
Harmlessly hokey yet never much more than mediocre, Hocus Pocus is a muddled family-friendly effort that fails to live up to the talents of its impressive cast.
Jack Nicholson embodies Hoffa with malevolent relish, but a dearth of meaningful insight knocks this crime epic off the mark by a nose.

movie_title: HÃ¥l i mitt hjÃ¤rta, Ett (A Hole In My Heart)

critics_consensus: Faithful to its literary source, this is imaginative, intelligent family entertainment.
With the combined might of Bing Crosby, Fred Astaire, and Irving Berlin working in its favor, Holiday Inn is a seasonal classic -- not least because it introduced "White Christmas" to the world.
Despite awesome special effects, Hollow Man falls short of other films directed by Paul Verhoeven. This flick over time degenerates into a typical horror film.
Despite some execution problems, Holly remains a realistic and gritty look at child sex slavery.
Although Hollywood Ending contains some zany one-liners, its promising premise is far from developed.
Hollywood Homicide suffers from too many subplots and not enough laughs.
Hollywood Shuffle overcomes budgetary constraints with sharp humor and infectious energy, heralding the arrival of an exciting new filmmaking talent in the bargain.
More than a movie star murder mystery, Hollywoodland takes it slow in order to reveal the intriguing details of the rise and fall of superstar fame.
Cloying and unfunny, Holy Man wastes the repartee between Eddie Murphy and Jeff Goldblum on the gospel of toothless satire and unearned sentimentality.
Mesmerizingly strange and willfully perverse, Holy Motors offers an unforgettable visual feast alongside a spellbinding -- albeit unapologetically challenging -- narrative.
A visual treat rich in symbolism, The Holy Mountain adds another defiantly idiosyncratic chapter to Jodorowsky's thoroughly unique filmography.
Despite a promising premise and a solid central performance from Jesse Eisenberg, Holy Rollers lacks the depth necessary to overcome its cliched script.
Superb performances hindered by weak script and incoherent story.
Home Alone uneven but frequently funny premise stretched unreasonably thin is buoyed by Macaulay Culkin's cute performance and strong supporting stars.

movie_title: Home Alone 2: Lost in New York
critics_consensus: A change of venue -- and more sentimentality and violence -- can't obscure the fact that Home Alone 2: Lost in New York is a less inspired facsimile of its predecessor.

movie_title: A Home at the End of the World
critics_consensus: A Home at the End of the World aims for profundity, but settles for stale melodrama, yielding a slew of sensitive performances that are nevertheless in service of characters who prove to be ciphers.
Screenwriter Vince Gilligan's mordant sense of humor strikes a discordant note in Home Fries, a romantic caper full of empty calories.
The ensemble cast works hard, but hammy direction and a script lacking in nuance ruins this movie's noble intentions.
Though Home on the Range is likeable and may keep young children diverted, it's one of Disney's more middling titles, with garish visuals and a dull plot.
Honorable intentions and some strong performances aren't enough to keep Home Room from occasionally slipping into distractingly didactic messaging.
While it boasts a capable cast, the disappointingly dull Homefront hearkens back to classic action thrillers without adding anything to the genre.

movie_title: Homeward Bound II - Lost in San Francisco

critics_consensus: Disney's remake of The Incredible Journey successfully replicates, and in some ways improves upon, the simple charms of the original, with its cross-country animal odyssey sure to delight kids.
An attractive Jessica Alba and energetic dance numbers provide some lift to this corny and formulaic movie.

movie_title: Honey, I Blew Up the Kid

critics_consensus: Even as its special effects take center stage, Honey, I Shrunk the Kids still offers a charming, high-spirited sense of adventure for the whole family.
Honeydripper's electric musical numbers and sharp performances make for an exciting film, despite its slow pace.
Smart, stylish, and nail-bitingly tense, Honeymoon packs more slow-building horror than many bigger-budget productions.
Honeymoon in Vegas is a light screwball comedy that has just about what you expect (and nothing you don't).
Clint Eastwood succeeds in revealing his softer side in Honkytonk Man, a surprisingly sweet and heartwarming road movie that hums along at a pleasant pace.
It may add 3D to the original, but Hoodwinked Too! is missing the first installment's wit and refreshingly low-budget charm.
The look of Hook is lively indeed but Steven Spielberg directs on autopilot here, giving in too quickly to his sentimental, syrupy qualities.

One of the most critically acclaimed documentaries of all time, Hoop Dreams is a rich, complex, heartbreaking, and ultimately deeply rewarding film that uses high school hoops as a jumping-off point to explore issues of race, class, and education in modern America.
It may adhere to the sports underdog formula, but Hoosiers has been made with such loving craft, and features such excellent performances, that it's hard to resist.
Lacking energy and humor, Hoot is a ho-hum story of eco-awareness that falls flat as a pancake.
It's impressively animated, but Hop's script is so uninspired that not even James Marsden's frantic mugging can give it any bounce.
Led by a pair of mesmerizing performances from Meryl Streep and Tommy Lee Jones, Hope Springs offers filmgoers some grown-up laughs -- and a thoughtful look at mature relationships.

movie_title: Hornblower: The Examination for Lieutenant (Horatio Hornblower: The Fire Ship)

critics_consensus: Horns is a bit of a tonal jumble, but it offers enough thoughtful horror-comedy -- and strong work from Daniel Radcliffe -- to hook genre enthusiasts.
It's nasty, uneven, and far from original, but thanks to a smartly assembled cast that makes the most of a solid premise, Horrible Bosses works.
Horrible Bosses 2 may trigger a few belly laughs among big fans of the original, but all in all, it's a waste of a strong cast that fails to justify its own existence.
Trading gore for grandeur, Horror of Dracula marks an impressive turn for inveterate Christopher Lee as the titular vampire, and a typical Hammer mood that makes aristocracy quite sexy.
It might be a bit too eager to tug the heartstrings, but The Horse Whisperer is typically graceful, well-crafted Redford -- on both sides of the camera.

movie_title: Dr. Seuss' Horton Hears a Who!
critics_consensus: Horton Hears A Who! is both whimsical and heartwarming, and is the rare Dr. Seuss adaptation that stays true to the spirit of the source material.
Featuring lots of guts and gore, Hostel is a wildly entertaining corpse-filled journey -- assuming one is entertained by corpses, guts, and gore, that is.
Offering up more of the familiar sadism and gore, Hostel: Part II will surely thrill horror fans.
The Hot Chick's one-note concept gets stretched thin, and a lot of the jokes fall flat.
The brilliant minds behind Shaun of the Dead successfully take a shot at the buddy cop genre with Hot Fuzz. The result is a bitingly satiric and hugely entertaining parody.
Hot Rod has brazen silliness and a few humorous set pieces on its side, but it's far too inconsistent to satisfy all but the least demanding slapstick lovers.
Its flagrantly silly script -- and immensely likable cast -- make up for most of its flaws.
Hotel earns a handful of points for sheer ambition, but they aren't enough to carry the movie over its steep pretensions.
Hotel for Dogs may appeal to children and dog lovers, but it's ultimately contrived, predictable, and simplistic.
A sobering and heartfelt tale about massacre that took place in Rwanda while most of the world looked away.
Hotel Transylvania's buoyant, giddy tone may please children, but it might be a little too loud and thinly-scripted for older audiences.
The movie may be a downer, but it packs an emotional wallop. Some fine acting on display here.

movie_title: House at the End of the Street
critics_consensus: Poorly conceived, clumsily executed, and almost completely bereft of scares, House at the End of the Street strands its talented star in a film as bland as its title.
Anna Faris is game, but she can't salvage this middling, formulaic comedy.
There's an abundance of gore in this derivative horror movie, but little sense or wit.
A sincere but inept coming of age story.

movie_title: Lisa And The Devil (Lisa e il diavolo) (The Devil in the House of Exorcism)

critics_consensus: The visual splendor of the movie makes up for the weak story.
House of Fools has a potentially intriguing fact-based story to tell, but an insensitive approach to depicting mental illness undermines its effectiveness.
Galvanized by David Mamet's punchy dialogue and a a winding succession of surprises, House of Games is a terse thriller where confidence is currency.
Powerful and thought provoking film.
Bearing little resemblance to the 1953 original, House of Wax is a formulaic but better-than-average teen slasher flick.
House Party is a light, entertaining teen comedy with an infectious energy.
Alternately hilarious, gross, and simply diverting, Housebound is the rare horror-comedy that delivers on both fronts.
Perplexingly unfunny given the involvement of its two hilarious leads, Houseguest wears out its welcome almost immediately.
How Do You Know boasts a quartet of likeable leads -- and they deserve better than this glib, overlong misfire from writer/director James L. Brooks.
Though it perhaps strays into overly maudlin territory, this working-class drama is saved by a solid cast and director John Ford's unmistakeable style.
How High is a sloppily constructed stoner movie filled with lame, vulgar jokes.
Led by another strong performance from Saoirse Ronan and a screenplay that subverts YA clichÃ©s, How I Live Now blends young love with post-apocalyptic drama.
Despite a formulaic plot, the energetic and gritty How She Move is elevated by a commanding debut performance by Rutina Wesley.

movie_title: How Stella Got Her Groove Back
Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas
critics_consensus: Jim Carrey shines as the Grinch. Unfortunately, it's not enough to save this movie. You'd be better off watching the TV cartoon.
This charming doc takes its time while focusing on food, but highlights larger lessons that audiences will reflect upon long after leaving the theater.
Soap opera for teens.
This Fear Factor for kids is good-natured and tasty enough.

movie_title: How to Eat Your Watermelon in White Company (And Enjoy It)
How to Lose a Guy in 10 Days
critics_consensus: Matthew McConaughey and Kate Hudson are charming together, but they can't overcome  How to Lose a Guy in 10 Days' silly premise and predictable script.

movie_title: How to Lose Friends & Alienate People
critics_consensus: A decent performance from Pegg in a disappointing film. Neither sharp nor satirical, Weide's adaptation relies too heavily on slapstick, and misses the point of the source material in the process.

movie_title: How to Make an American Quilt
critics_consensus: How to Make an American Quilt is a bit of a patchwork from a storytelling standpoint, but a strong ensemble cast led by Winona Ryder helps hold it all together.

movie_title: How To Make Money Selling Drugs
How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying

critics_consensus: Angry, powerful, and stirring, How to Survive a Plague is a brilliantly constructed documentary about the activists who pushed for action to combat the AIDS epidemic.
Boasting dazzling animation, a script with surprising dramatic depth, and thrilling 3-D sequences, How to Train Your Dragon soars.
Exciting, emotionally resonant, and beautifully animated, How to Train Your Dragon 2 builds on its predecessor's successes just the way a sequel should.
While it has its moments, Howard the Duck suffers from an uneven tone and mediocre performances.

movie_title: Howard Zinn: You Can't Be Neutral on a Moving Train

critics_consensus: A superbly-mounted adaptation of E.M. Forster's tale of British class tension, with exceptional performances all round, Howard's End ranks among the best of Merchant-Ivory's work.
The Howling packs enough laughs into its lycanthropic carnage to distinguish it from other werewolf entries, with impressive visual effects adding some bite.
Offering a stunning, expansive viewing experience, Hubble 3D takes advantage of IMAX and 3-D technology like no other film.
Intriguingly strange and visually distinctive, The Hudsucker Proxy is ultimately almost -- but not quite -- as smart and absorbing as it needs to be.

movie_title: Hugh Hefner: Playboy, Activist and Rebel

critics_consensus: Hugo is an extravagant, elegant fantasy with an innocence lacking in many modern kids' movies, and one that emanates an unabashed love for the magic of cinema.
While Ang Lee's ambitious film earns marks for style and an attempt at dramatic depth, there's ultimately too much talking and not enough smashing.
Grotesque, visceral and hard to (ahem) swallow, this surgical horror doesn't quite earn its stripes because the gross-outs overwhelm and devalue everything else.
Though the acting is fine, the leads are miscast, and the story is less powerful on screen than on the page.
Observant and insightful, this indie comedy takes a different tack on the "bromance" but still makes a point without sermonizing.
Unflinching, uncompromising, vivid and vital, Steve McQueen's challenging debut is not for the faint hearted, but it's still a richly rewarding retelling of troubled times.
Perfectly cast and packed with suspense, The Hunt for Red October is an old-fashioned submarine thriller with plenty of firepower to spare.
Hustle & Flow is gritty and redemptive, with a profound sense of place and exciting music.
Paul Newman and Jackie Gleason give iconic performances in this dark, morally complex tale of redemption.
Though bolstered by a thoroughly charming performance by Bill Murray in the central role, Hyde Park on Hudson is an FDR biopic that lets down both its audience and its subject.
Hysteria has an amusing subject but its winking, vaguely sarcastic tone doesn't do the movie any favors.

movie_title: I Knew It Was You: Rediscovering John Cazale
I Am a Fugitive From a Chain Gang

critics_consensus: I Am a Sex Addict takes a penetrating look at troublesome compulsions, although its unsurprisingly self-indulgent focus may test the limits of some viewers.
I Am David smothers its heartwarming story in narrative contrivances that ultimately render suspension of disbelief - or enjoyment - all but impossible.
With warmth and affection, I Am Divine offers an engaging portrait of the complex personality behind a trailblazing cinematic figure.
I Am Legend overcomes questionable special effects and succeeds largely on the strength of Will Smith's mesmerizing performance.
It stumbles into melodrama, but I Am Love backs up its flamboyance with tremendous visual style and a marvelous central performance from Tilda Swinton.
It's positioned as the start of a franchise, but I Am Number Four's familiar plot and unconvincing performances add up to one noisy, derivative, and ultimately forgettable sci-fi thriller.
Not only does the manipulative I Am Sam oversimplify a complex issue, it drowns it in treacle.

movie_title: I Am Trying to Break Your Heart
critics_consensus: Besides being a treat for Wilco fans, I Am Trying to Break Your Heart also exposes the workings of a profit-driven music industry.

movie_title: I Can Do Bad All By Myself
critics_consensus: Though somewhat formulaic and predictable, Perry succeeds in mixing broad humor with sincere sentimentality to palatable effect.
A handsome and charming adaptation of the novel.

movie_title: I Don't Know How She Does It
critics_consensus: A limp comedy with a hopelessly outdated viewpoint on gender, featuring Sarah Jessica Parker in rote Carrie-mode.
The straightforward retelling of Kuki Gallman's life in Africa neither moves or entertains the viewer.
Loud, incoherent, and dramatically listless, I, Frankenstein is a remarkably dull fantasy adventure that fails to generate much excitement or interest in its characters.
It's nowhere near as inventive as its reverse rom-com premise might suggest, but I Give It a Year is disarmingly frank -- and often quite funny.
This boilerplate comedy lacks ingenuity or humor and features mediocre dialogue that sounds less like conversation and more like stand-up shtick.

movie_title: I Have Never Forgotten You: The Life And Legacy Of Simon Wiesenthal

critics_consensus: I Heart Huckabees certainly isn't for everyone, but audiences attuned to its quirky wavelength will find a singularly brainy screwball comedy that refuses to pander.

movie_title: I Hope They Serve Beer in Hell
critics_consensus: I Hope They Serve Beer in Hell fails in its attempts at raunchy humor, and Tucker Max comes across so unlikable and outrageous that the film's inevitable story arc feels forced.
I Killed My Mother's raw, blunt coming-of-age narrative marks an impressive debut for filmmaker Xavier Dolan.

movie_title: I Know What You Did Last Summer
critics_consensus: A by-the-numbers slasher that arrived a decade too late, the mostly tedious I Know What You Did Last Summer will likely only hook diehard fans of the genre.
Distasteful and ludicrously plotted, I Know Who Killed Me is a career nadir for all involved -- particularly Lindsay Lohan in a dual role.
There appears to be no Love lost between the fatally mismatched coupling of Julia Roberts and Nick Nolte in this screwball misfire that just isn't worth the Trouble.

movie_title: I Love You, Alice B. Toklas
I Love You, I Love You Not

critics_consensus: I Love You, Man makes the most of its simple premise due to the heartfelt and hilarious performances of Paul Rudd and Jason Segel.
This fact-based romantic comedy has its flaws, but they're mostly overcome by its consistently sweet, funny tone and one of the best performances of Jim Carrey's career.

movie_title: I Married a Monster from Outer Space
I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry
critics_consensus: Whether by way of inept comedy or tasteless stereotypes, I Now Pronounce You Chuck And Larry falters on both levels.
A potent and lithely constructed documentary about America's financial crisis, I.O.U.S.A grabs you with figures but holds you with irreverent wit.
Writer-director Mike Cahill remains an intriguingly ambitious talent, but with the uneven sci-fi drama I Origins, his reach exceeds his grasp.
Bearing only the slightest resemblance to Isaac Asimov's short stories, I, Robot is still a summer blockbuster that manages to make viewers think -- if only a little.

movie_title: I Served the King of England
critics_consensus: With charm and an eye for life's bittersweet moments, Czech New Wave master Jiri Menzel paints a picaresque story with whimsy and intellect.

movie_title: I Spit on Your Grave (Day of the Woman)
critics_consensus: I Spit on Your Grave is as aggressively exploitative as its title suggests, although as a crude rejoinder to misogyny, it packs a certain amount of undeniable power.
Well-shot exploitation that has less purpose and utility than in 1978.
Insipid and mirthless, I-Spy bares little resemblance to the TV series that inspired it.

movie_title: I Still Know What You Did Last Summer
critics_consensus: Boring, predictable, and bereft of thrills or chills, I Still Know What You Did Last Summer is exactly the kind of rehash that gives horror sequels a bad name.

movie_title: I Think I Love My Wife
critics_consensus: Chris Rock's comedic instincts are muted and the female characters are unsatisfactorily drawn in this uneven sex farce/domestic drama mashup.

Evocative direction by Jacques Tourneur collides with the low-rent production values of exploitateer Val Lewton in I Walked with a Zombie, a sultry sleeper that's simultaneously smarmy, eloquent and fascinating.

movie_title: I Was a Male War Bride
I Will Follow You Into The Dark

critics_consensus: Elliptical and deliberately paced yet steadily absorbing, I Wish presents a beguiling portrait of childhood that grounds its sweetly nostalgic glow with well-rounded characters and attention to detail.
Even though Ice Age is treading over the same grounds as Monsters, Inc. and Shrek, it has enough wit and laughs to stand on its own.
Despite its impressive animation and the hilarious antics of the saber-toothed squirrel Scrat, Ice Age 2: The Meltdown comes up short on the storytelling front.
Ice Age: Continental Drift 3D has moments of charm and witty slapstick, but it often seems content to recycle ideas from the previous films.
The Ice Harvest offers a couple of laughs, but considering the people involved, it should be a lot funnier.
This likable Disney film gets points for effort, but can't stick the landing when it comes to originality.
Director Ang Lee revisits the ennui-laden decadence of 1970s suburban America with deft humor and gripping pathos.

movie_title: Iceberg Slim: Portrait Of A Pimp

critics_consensus: Ichi The Killer is a thoroughly shocking gorefest that will surely entertain those with strong stomachs and a penchant for brutal violence.
Empathetically written, splendidly acted, and beautifully photographed, Ida finds director Pawel Pawlikowski revisiting his roots to powerful effect.
Identity is a film that will divide audiences -- the twists of its plot will either impress or exasperate you.
Identity Thief's few laughs are attributable to Melissa McCarthy and Jason Bateman, who labor mightily to create a framework for the movie's undisciplined plotline.
Idiocracy delivers the hilarity and biting satire that could only come from Mike Judge.
An uneasy mix of slapstick and gore, Idle Hands lacks the manic energy and comedic inspiration required to pull off its goofy premise.
Idlewild has some truly breathtaking moments, but borrows too heavily from other similar movies, and the disjointed script is not worthy of talents involved.
Incendiary, subversive, and darkly humorous, If.... is a landmark of British countercultural cinema.

movie_title: If a Tree Falls: A Story of the Earth Liberation Front

critics_consensus: Although ChloÃ« Grace Moretz gives it her all and the story adds an intriguing supernatural twist to its melodramatic YA framework, If I Stay is ultimately more manipulative than moving.

movie_title: If I Want To Whistle, I Whistle

critics_consensus: In the vein of The Catcher in the Rye, Igby Goes Down is scathingly witty and sharply observant.
Ikiru is a well-acted and deeply moving humanist tale about a man facing his own mortality, one of legendary director Akira Kurosawa's most intimate films.
While the web of corruption in this Italian political thriller can be hard for a non-native to follow, the visuals and the intrigue are compelling and thrilling in equal measure.

movie_title: I'll Always Know What You Did Last Summer

critics_consensus: I'll Sleep When I'm Dead's spare performances and slick style are undermined by a lack of cohesive story, yielding a neatly packaged noir with little substance beneath its polished surface.
Lackluster acting and a ridiculous plot make the over-the-top Illegal Tender an unrealistic bust.
The Illusionist is an engrossing, well-crafted story of mystery, magic and intrigue that is certain to enchant, if not hypnotize, audiences.
Quietly compassionate and rich in detail, Ilo Ilo is a strikingly mature debut from writer-director Anthony Chen.
Though this French film features good acting, it lacks the wit and charm one would expect to see.

movie_title: I'm Dancing as Fast as I Can

critics_consensus: I'm Gonna Git You Sucka puts a satirical spin on '70s nostalgia with a comedy whose somewhat scattershot laughs are often offset by pure energetic silliness.

movie_title: I'm In Love With A Church Girl

critics_consensus: I'm Not There's unique editing, visuals, and multiple talented actors portraying Bob Dylan make for a deliciously unconventional experience. Each segment brings a new and fresh take on Dylan's life.
Campy and proudly absurd, I'm So Excited! Pedro AlmodÃ³var's return to light comedy isn't quite the successful homecoming that filmgoers might wish for.

As unkempt and inscrutable as Joaquin Phoenix himself, I'm Still Here raises some interesting questions about its subject, as well as the nature of celebrity, but it fails to answer many of them convincingly.

movie_title: I'm Through with White Girls (The Inevitable Undoing of Jay Brooks)

critics_consensus: Aside from its lesbian theme, Imagine Me & You can only offer more of the same generic rom-com cliches.

movie_title: Cirque du Soleil: Journey of Man

critics_consensus: Stylish, but emotionally uninvolving.
The melding of real sets, CG work, and Tarsem's signature style produces fireworks, though the same can't be said for Immortals slack, boring storytelling.

Oliver Parker's adaptation of Oscar Wilde's classic play is breezy entertainment, helped by an impressive cast, but it also suffers from some peculiar directorial choices that ultimately dampen the film's impact.
With its low production value and uninspired direction, Impostor comes off as a mixture of The Fugitive and Blade Runner, only not as good or as involving.

movie_title: In the Name of the King: A Dungeon Siege Tale
critics_consensus: Featuring mostly wooden performances, laughable dialogue, and shoddy production values, In the Name of the King fulfills all expectations of an Uwe Boll film.
In a Better World is a sumptuous melodrama that tackles some rather difficult existential and human themes.
Led by extraordinary performances from Humphrey Bogart and Gloria Grahame, In a Lonely Place is a gripping noir of uncommon depth and maturity.
A funny, well-written screwball satire for film buffs, In a World... proves an auspicious beginning for writer, director, and star Lake Bell.
A rich and moving story about an immigrant family adjusting to life in New York.

It doesn't always find comfortable ground between broad comedy and social commentary, but lively performances -- especially from Kevin Kline and Joan Cusack -- enrich In & Out's mixture of laughs and sexual tolerance.
In Another Country offers intelligent observations throughout its trio of overlapping stories -- and demonstrates again just how much Isabelle Huppert's presence can improve a film.
In Between Days is a moving, artistic slice-of-life indie film.
Featuring witty dialogue and deft performances, In Bruges is an effective mix of dark comedy and crime thriller elements.
With a slow build to a dramatic conclusion, In Country benefits largely from its strong acting, particularly by Emily Lloyd in the lead role.
Some interesting visuals, but the movie is as confusing as a dream.
Compact and effective, In Fear offers discerning horror fans a smart and disturbing plunge into the depths of cinematic anxiety.
The witty and charming In Good Company offers laughs at the expense of corporate culture.
Honesty and solid performances make In Her Shoes a solid fit for all audiences.
A well-intentioned but melodramatic look at post-Apartheid South Africa.
With a wealth of insightful talking heads and deft musical performances, In Search of Beethoven is a thorough, thoughtful examination of the great composer's life and times.

movie_title: In Search of Memory (Auf der Suche nach dem GedÃ¤chtnis)

critics_consensus: In Search of Mozart may not be quite as exhilarating as its subject's classic compositions, but it offers an enlightening, entertaining primer on the life of a brilliant artist.
Although it benefits from a strong cast, In Secret's stars can't totally compensate for the movie's sodden pacing and overly familiar story.
This 1994 Pauly Shore vehicle stretches its star's thin shtick to the breaking point with a laugh-deficient screenplay that borrows shamelessly from Bill Murray's far superior Stripes.
Expertly crafted and performed, In the Bedroom is a quietly wrenching portrayal of grief.
Neil LaBute's pitch-black comedy is a masterful exploration of male insecurity, and it's elevated by a breakout performance by Aaron Eckhart as a businessman who likes to play psychological games.
Director/co-writer Jane Campion takes a stab at subverting the psycho-sexual thriller genre with In the Cut, but gets tangled in her own abstraction.
In the Family uses one couple's tragedy to examine the legal meaning of parenthood - and make a persuasive argument for a more inclusive approach to family law.

movie_title: In the Heat of the Night
critics_consensus: Tense, funny, and thought-provoking all at once, and lifted by strong performances from Sydney Poitier and Rod Steiger, director Norman Jewison's look at murder and racism in small-town America continues to resonate today.

movie_title: In the Land of Blood and Honey

critics_consensus: While pleasantly acted, In the Land of Women is a dramatically stilted film with underdeveloped characters.
A straightforward thriller of the highest order, In the Line of Fire benefits from Wolfgang Peterson's taut direction and charismatic performances from Clint Eastwood and John Malkovich.
In the Loop is an uncommonly funny political satire that blends Dr. Strangelove with Spinal Tap for the Iraq war era.

movie_title: In the Mirror of Maya Deren

critics_consensus: Fans may get a kick out of seeing Usher showcasing his charm on screen, but the movie itself is tone deaf and inconsequential, even by rom-com standards.
If it fails to make the most of its intriguing premise, In the Mouth of Madness remains a decent enough diversion for horror fans and John Carpenter completists.

movie_title: In the Name of the Father
critics_consensus: Impassioned and meticulously observed, In the Name of the Father mines rousing drama from a factual miscarriage of justice, aided by scorching performances and director Jim Sheridan's humanist focus.

movie_title: In the Realm of the Senses
critics_consensus: Sexual taboos are broken and boundaries crossed In the Realm of the Senses, a fearlessly provocative psychosexual tale.

movie_title: In the Shadow of the Moon
critics_consensus: Director David Sington poetically interwove 20th Century's cosmonautic history with its effect on the public's view of their country, their heroes and their future.
Though some of Paul Haggis's themes are heavy-handed, In the Valley of Elah is otherwise an engrossing murder mystery and antiwar statement, featuring a mesmerizing performance from Tommy Lee Jones.
In Time's intriguing premise and appealing cast are easily overpowered by the blunt, heavy-handed storytelling.
A solid performance from Michelle Williams isn't enough to save this well meaning, but disappointing, clichÃ© ridden drama.
It's messy, overlong, and a touch melodramatic, but those flaws pale before Incendies' impressive acting and devastating emotional impact.
Smart, innovative, and thrilling, Inception is that rare summer blockbuster that succeeds viscerally as well as intellectually.
