Love Songs is hampered by a lack of focus, but held together by Honore's deft direction and an engaging cast.
Love the Hard Way pits an intriguing ensemble against a clichÃ©-riddled storyline, and the actors lose -- along with the audience.
Amanda Seyfried and Peter Sarsgaard do their best with the material, but Lovelace lacks enough depth and conviction to truly do its fascinating subject justice.
The transition from novel to film is awkwardly executed, and Sedgwick's character, despite the attempts to make her sympathetic, merely comes across as creepy and crazy.
Interesting idea, poor execution.
Rich in mood and on-screen talent but lacking in narrative depth, Low Down tells an oft-told tale with a troubling dearth of imagination.
This familiar story of a tension-fraught love triangle wavers between brutality and steamy sex.
A relatively simple mid-life crisis story is burdened by overly cumbersome plot devices.
Lucky Break fails to do anything new with The Full Monty formula.
Trying too hard to be clever in a Pulp Fiction kind of way, this film succumbs to a convoluted plot, overly stylized characters, and dizzying set design.

Nora Ephron's attempt at dark comedy is an uneven product, both in terms of the direction and the acting. The characters are unlikable to the point where you don't care what happens to them, and Ephron condescends to the material.
Lucky Them may not quite live up to Toni Collette's bravura starring performance, but it's certainly elevated by it.
Lucky You tries to combine a romantic story with the high-stakes world of poker, but comes up with an empty hand.
Enthusiastic and silly, Lucy powers through the movie's logic gaps with cheesy thrills plus Scarlett Johansson's charm -- and mostly succeeds at it.
Ebouaney's fiery performance makes Lumumba compelling.

movie_title: Lupin III: The Castle of Cagliostro (Rupan sansei: Kariosutoro no shiro)

critics_consensus: Ang Lee's Lust, Caution is a tense, sensual and beautifully-shot espionage film.
Lymelife features sharp performances, but the story lacks the emotional depth or focus worthy of its talented cast.

movie_title: My Life in Pink (Ma Vie en Rose)
critics_consensus: Ma Vie en Rose follows a boy's exploration of his gender identity with warmth and empathy - for its young protagonist as well as the family affected by his journey.
It too often mistakes shock value for real humor, but MacGruber is better than many SNL films -- and better than it probably should be.
Roman Polanski's Macbeth is unsettling and uneven, but also undeniably compelling.
Machete is messy, violent, shallow, and tasteless -- and that's precisely the point of one of the summer's most cartoonishly enjoyable films.
While possessed with the same schlocky lunacy as its far superior predecessor, Machete Kills loses the first installment's spark in a less deftly assembled sequel.
There's a complex man at the center of Machine Gun Preacher but the movie is too shapeless and emotionally vacant to bring his story to life.
Brad Anderson's dark psychological thriller about a sleepless factory worker is elevated by Christian Bale astonishingly committed performance.
Inspired casting and a prevailing sweetness make Mad Dog and Glory an oddball treat.
This heartwarming documentary will win audiences over, as the sheer charm of precocious, enthusiastic children learning to dance resonates from the screen.
An overwrought bodice-ripper, Mad Love is more silly than dramatic.
Staging the improbable car stunts and crashes to perfection, director George Miller succeeds completely in bringing the violent, post-apocalyptic world of Mad Max to visceral life.
The Road Warrior is everything a bigger-budgeted Mad Max sequel with should be: bigger, faster, louder, but definitely not dumber.
Beyond Thunderdome deepens the Mad Max character without sacrificing the amazing vehicle choreography and stunts that made the originals memorable.
Though its story is problematic in spots and its humor is hit-or-miss for the adult crowd, Madagascar boasts impressive visuals and enough spunky charm to keep children entertained.
Dazzlingly colorful and frenetic, Madagascar 3 is silly enough for young kids, but boasts enough surprising smarts to engage parents along the way.
Madagascar: Escape 2 Africa is an improvement on the original, with more fleshed-out characters, crisper animation and more consistent humor.
Madame SatÃ£ offers an occasionally absorbing look at a pivotal figure in Brazilian culture, even if its subject deserves a more consistent biopic.
Not as good as Swingers, but it's still witty and goofy enough for some laughs.
Sharp performances by Patrick Dempsey and Michelle Monaghan can't save this forgettable, formulaic chick flick from its comic failings.
Divided between sincere melodrama and populist comedy, Madea Goes to Jail fails to provide enough laughs -- or screen time -- for its titular heroine.
Tyler Perry's Madea's Family Reunion is sincere in its positive intentions, but leaves something to be desired as a film.
As fleshy as it is funny, Bong Joon-Ho's Mother straddles family drama, horror and comedy with a deft grasp of tone and plenty of eerie visuals.
A pedictable and heavy-handed sports drama.
Thanks largely to stellar all-around performances from a talented cast, The Madness of King George is a funny, entertaining, and immensely likable adaptation of the eponymous stage production.
Mafioso begins as an amusing farce and skillfully transforms into a portentous social drama.
A typical women-in-prision film made untypical because it's based on real events.
While far from a failure, Magic in the Moonlight is too slight to stand with Woody Allen's finest work.
There might be Magic in the Water during this family-friendly adventure, but precious little of it ended up on the screen.
Magic Mike's sensitive direction, smart screenplay, and strong performances allow audiences to have their beefcake and eat it too.
Magic Trip is overall unenlightening, though there's an inherent novelty and joy in seeing the unearthed footage of Ken Kesey and his band of Merry Pranksters.
Critics say Magnolia is an ambitious, lengthy work that ultimately succeeds due to the interesting stories and excellent ensemble performances.
Magnum Force ups the ante for the Dirty Harry franchise with faster action and thrilling stuntwork.
Too blandly generic, Maid in Manhattan also suffers from a lack of chemistry between Lopez and Fiennes.
The setup for Mail Order Wife is clever, but the movie is only moderately funny, and it stumbles badly in the third act.
Ponderous and overlong, The Majestic drowns in forced sentimentality and resembles a mish-mash of other, better films.
Major Dundee is a Western-type with big war scenes, shot with bombast typical of Sam Peckinpah.
Major League may be predictable and formulaic, but buoyed by the script's light, silly humor -- not to mention the well-built sports action sequences and funny performances.

movie_title: Major League: Back to the Minors

critics_consensus: Cheap, predictable, formulaic and unimaginative generic dance film. Comes across as Showgirls for simpleton teens, but with much less flesh on show.
Mala Noche is a raw and gritty portrait of desire, doomed romance, and rejection -- and marks debuting director Gus Van Sant as a filmmaker with a gratifyingly personal touch.
Angelina Jolie's magnetic performance outshines Maleficent's dazzling special effects; unfortunately, the movie around them fails to justify all that impressive effort.
There are some laughs, but not enough to sustain the running time.
Mallrats colorfully expands the View Askewniverse, even if its snootchie has lost a few of the bootchies boasted by its beloved predecessor.
If you're into old-school scares over cheap gore, you'll be able to get over Mama's confusing script and contrived plot devices.
A broad, shrill comedy that plays like a sitcom.
This jukebox musical is full of fluffy fun but rough singing voices and a campy tone might not make you feel like "You Can Dance" the whole 90 minutes.
Action and drama elements don't mix well in this clichÃ©d actioner.

movie_title: Un condamnÃ© Ã  mort s'est Ã©chappÃ© ou Le vent souffle oÃ¹ il veut (A Man Escaped)
critics_consensus: A Man Escaped is blockbuster Bresson, a well-acted POW drama that builds with subtle, seat-gripping tension.
This story about a gigolo isn't plausible or compelling enough.
Man From Plains is a fascinating look at the former president's recent endeavors.

movie_title: The Man in the Gray Flannel Suit

critics_consensus: It may not be groundbreaking, but Man of Tai Chi represents an agreeably old-fashioned picture for martial arts fans -- and a solid debut for first-time director Keanu Reeves.
A high-concept movie that plays out like a mediocre TV sitcom.
Weakened by second-half attempts at thriller and romance, this presidential comedy also fails to hit any sharp political notes, resulting in a confused and unsatisfying mess.
Uninspired acting and preposterous plotlines defuse Man on a Ledge's mildly intriguing premise.
Man on Fire starts out well, but goes over the top in the violent second half.
James Marsh's doc about artist Phililppe Petit's artful caper brings you every ounce of suspense that can be wrung from a man on a (suspended) wire.
This compassionate portrait of a New York City street vendor is as beautiful as it is melancholy.

movie_title: The Man Who Fell to Earth
critics_consensus: Filled with stunning imagery, The Man Who Fell to Earth is a calm, meditative film that profoundly explores our culture's values and desires.

movie_title: The Man Who Knew Too Little
The Man Who Shot Liberty Valance
critics_consensus: Featuring a trio of classic leading men and a rich story captured by a director at the peak of his craft, The Man Who Shot Liberty Valance is one of the finest Westerns ever filmed.
Stylish but emotionally distant, The Man Who Wasn't There is a clever tribute to the film noir genre.

movie_title: The Man Who Would Be King
The Man with One Red Shoe
The Man with the Golden Gun
critics_consensus: A middling Bond film, The Man With the Golden Gun suffers from double entendre-laden dialogue, a noteworthy lack of gadgets, and a villain that overshadows 007.
As spastically uneven as its zany title suggests, The Man with Two Brains isn't peak Steve Martin -- but it's still often close enough to enjoy.
KaurismÃ¤ki delivers another droll comedy full of his trademark humor.
Clever and often beguiling performances by Steve Zahn and Jennifer Aniston can't revive this sweetly misguided stalker romance.
Its tranquil pace will prove jarring for the blockbuster-inclined, but Manakamana rewards patient viewers with a singularly haunting experience.
While not the classic its predecessor is, this update is well-acted and conjures a chilling resonance.
The exciting and fast-paced documentary Manda Bala shows many sides of Brazil -- from the humorous and upbeat to the violent and disturbing.
It might be too respectful to truly soar, but there's no denying Idris Elba's impressive work in Mandela: Long Walk to Freedom -- or the inspirational power of the life it depicts.
Manderlay may work better as a political statement than as a film, making its points at the expense of telling a compelling story.

movie_title: All the Boys Love Mandy Lane
critics_consensus: Mandy Lane has enough wit and craft to spark the horror fan's interest, but is not sufficiently original for mainstream audiences.
One of Woody Allen's early classics, Manhattan combines modern, bittersweet humor and timeless romanticism with unerring grace.
Shocking and bloody. Maniac is smarter than your average psychological slasher, but it's often undermined by its excessive gore.
A grim drama about emotionally damaged teens, Manic's solid cast helps to elevate the material above cliche.
An intimate and moving picture that captures the life of one of Manhattan's neighborhoods.
Mansome is a threadbare documentary with little insight into modern male maintenance, with useless celebrity interviews padding an already slim runtime.
Manufactured Landscapes leaves the work of drawing conclusions mostly to the viewer, although the imagery makes director Jennifer Baichwal's arguments well enough on its own.

movie_title: Manufacturing Consent - Noam Chomsky and the Media

critics_consensus: Brave, challenging, and brimming with rage, Manuscripts Don't Burn is a political statement as much as it is a gripping thriller.

movie_title: Many Adventures of Winnie the Pooh
critics_consensus: Perhaps the most faithful of Disney's literary adaptations, this cute, charming collection of episodes captures the spirit of A.A. Milne's classic stories.
Only the most hardened soul won't be moved by this heartwarming doc.
The material is too thin for feature-length and the jokes are socially outdated and clueless.
The scares are lacking in this J-horror flick, and the plot soon turns half-baked.
A surfeit of ideas contributes to Margaret's excessive run time, but Anna Paquin does a admirable job of guiding viewers through emotional hell.
Smart, tightly wound, and solidly acted, Margin Call turns the convoluted financial meltdown of '08 into gripping, thought-provoking drama.
Despite a great cast, the characters in Margot at the Wedding are too unlikable to enthrall viewers.
In a striking debut, Moreno carries the movie and puts a human face on the drug trade.
Marigold attempts the difficult trick of combining Bollywood movies and American rom-coms -- and ends up with an awkward blend that will satisfy fans of neither.

movie_title: Marilyn Hotchkiss Ballroom Dancing & Charm School
critics_consensus: Clumsily staged and brimming with melodrama and trite self-help cliches, this dance movie stays stuck at amateur level.

movie_title: Marina Abramovic: The Artist Is Present

critics_consensus: Overblown in every possible way, The Marine is either so bad it's good or just really, really bad.
Kevin Macdonald's exhaustive, evenhanded portrait of Bob Marley offers electrifying concert footage and fascinating insights into reggae's greatest star.
Pet owners should love it, but Marley and Me is only sporadically successful in wringing drama and laughs from its scenario.
Dull and unfunny, Marmaduke offers family filmgoers little more than another round of talking animals and scatological humor.

movie_title: Die Marquise von O... (The Marquise of O)

critics_consensus: Buoyed by Jonathan Demme's intuitive direction and Michelle Pfeiffer's irresistible charisma, Married to the Mob is a saucy mix of broad comedy and gangster drama.

movie_title: Une femme mariÃ©e: Suite de fragments d'un film tournÃ© en 1964 (A Married Woman)

critics_consensus: Tim Burton's alien invasion spoof faithfully recreates the wooden characters and schlocky story of cheesy '50s sci-fi and Ed Wood movies -- perhaps a little too faithfully for audiences.
The cast is solid and it's visually well-crafted, but Mars Needs Moms suffers from a lack of imagination and heart.
Led by a mesmerizing debut performance from Elizabeth Olsen, Martha Marcy May Marlene is a distinctive, haunting psychological drama.
Despite some charms, overt emotional manipulation and an inconsistent tone prevents Martian Child from being the heartfelt dramedy it aspires to be.
Lawrence's delivery can be funny, but the content is stale.
A real polarising movie, this Gallic torture-porn is graphic, brutal, nasty and gruesome and not to everyone's taste.
Thanks to a script that emphasizes its heroes' humanity and a wealth of superpowered set pieces, The Avengers lives up to its hype and raises the bar for Marvel at the movies.
Marvin's Room rises above the pack of dysfunctional family dramas thanks to an impeccable cast that includes Meryl Streep, Diane Keaton, and Leonardo DiCaprio.
Inspiring and fascinating, Marwencol depicts its subject with heartfelt tenderness, raising poignant questions about art and personal tragedy along the way.
A lavish modern fairy tale celebrated for its amazing special effects, catchy songs, and Julie Andrews's legendary performance in the title role.
The movie looks good and has its moments. But, overall, the movie borders on boredom.
Mary Shelley's Frankenstein is ambitious and visually striking, but the overwrought tone and lack of scares make for a tonally inconsistent experience.
A well-made coming of age drama elevated by its evocative setting, Maryam marks writer-director Ramin Serry as an emerging talent to watch.
Bold, timely, subversive, and above all funny, M*A*S*H remains a high point in Robert Altman's distinguished filmography.
Banderas returns as an aging Zorro in this surprisingly nimble, entertaining swashbuckler.
Unintelligible and self-indulgent Bob Dylan vehicle.

movie_title: Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World
critics_consensus: Russell Crowe's rough charm is put to good use in this masterful adaptation of Patrick O'Brian's novel.
An ill-concieved attempt to utilize Dana Carvey's talent for mimicry, The Master of Disguise is an irritating, witless farce weighted down by sophomoric gags.

Masters of the Universe is a slapdash adaptation of the He-Man mythos that can't overcome its cynical lack of raison d'etre, no matter how admirably Frank Langella throws himself into the role of Skeletor.
Woody Allen's sharpest film in years, Match Point is a taut, philosophical thriller about class and infidelity.
Breezy and well-acted, Matchstick Men focuses more on the characters than on the con.
Plagued by paper-thin characterizations and a hackneyed script, Material Girls fails to live up to even the minimum standards of its genre.

movie_title: The Mating Habits of the Earthbound Human

critics_consensus: Thanks to the Wachowskis' imaginative vision, The Matrix is a smartly crafted combination of spectacular action and groundbreaking special effects.
Though its heady themes are a departure from its predecessor, The Matrix Reloaded is a worthy sequel packed with popcorn-friendly thrills.
A disappointing conclusion to the Matrix trilogy as characters and ideas take a back seat to the special effects.
Matthew Barney: No Restraint makes an honest attempt to illuminate its subject's provocative work, but ultimately fails to capture its inspiration or appeal.
Maurice sensitively explores the ramifications of forbidden desire with a powerful love story brought to life by the outstanding efforts of a talented cast.
It isn't terribly deep, but it's witty and undeniably charming, and the cast is obviously having fun.
Well-acted in the execution of its provocative "what-if?" premise.
Max Keeble may be fun for kids, but bland and unoriginal for adults.
This good old-fashioned Norwegian WW2 film has impressive set pieces and never suffers for a lack of suspense.
While it boasts some stylish action, Max Payne suffers severely from an illogical plot and overdirection.
Maxed Out's presentation of startling facts and candid interviews put a human face on the issue of debt and financial insecurity.
Above average slasher flick.
McCabe & Mrs. Miller offers revisionist Western fans a landmark early addition to the genre while marking an early apogee for director Robert Altman.

movie_title: Me and You and Everyone We Know
critics_consensus: Miranda July's debut feature is a charmingly offbeat and observant film about people looking for love.
While Jim Carrey's comedic skills earn some laughs, Me, Myself and Irene sports a tired, unsatisfying plot.
At times ponderous, Me Without You is engaging due to the fine work by Williams and Friel.
Me You Them tells a warmly comical and touching story, and features a charismatically earthy performance by CasÃ©.

movie_title: Mea Maxima Culpa: Silence In The House Of God

critics_consensus: Mean Creek is an uncomfortably riveting glimpse into the casual cruelty of youth.
Funnier and more smartly written than the average teen comedy.
Despite some genuine wit, this crowd pleaser is filled with too many cliches.
Mean Streets is a powerful tale of urban sin and guilt that marks Scorsese's arrival as an important cinematic voice and features electrifying performances from Harvey Keitel and Robert De Niro.
Meatballs is a summer camp comedy with few surprises, but Bill Murray's riffing adds a spark that sets it apart from numerous subpar entries in a frequently uninspired genre.
Jason Statham and Ben Foster turn in enjoyable performances, but this superficial remake betrays them with mind-numbing violence and action thriller cliches.
The use of special effects diminishes some of Chan's appeal in this disposable picture.
Blessed with clever dialogue and poignant observations of class and race, Medicine For Melancholy is a promising debut for director Barry Jenkins.
Moving at a contemplative speed unseen in most westerns, Meek's Cutoff is an effective, intense journey of terror and survival in the untamed frontier.
Angela Bassett's considerable charms can't compensate for Meet the Browns' incessant melodrama and scattered narrative threads.
Easy gags and slack direction drag this occasionally clever alien-out-of-planet comedy down to unimaginative lows.
Glacially slow, uneventful.
Talented cast is wasted as the movie is content with recycling jokes from its predecessor, Meet the Parents.
Despite sometimes sitcom-like execution, Meet the Parents is a hilarious look at familial relationships that works mostly because the chemistry between its two leads is so effective.
Meet the Robinsons is a visually impressive children's animated film marked by a story of considerable depth.
A tired, unfunny, offensive waste of time, Meet the Spartans scrapes the bottom of the cinematic barrel.
With shoddy FX, acting and directing. This isn't so bad it's good. It's just so bad it's terrible.

It regurgitates plot points from earlier animated efforts, and isn't quite as funny as it should be, but a top-shelf voice cast and strong visuals help make Megamind a pleasant, if unspectacular, diversion.

Melancholia's dramatic tricks are more obvious than they should be, but this is otherwise a showcase for Kirsten Dunst's acting and for Lars von Trier's profound, visceral vision of depression and destruction.
Woody Allen's uneven Melinda and Melinda  fails to find neither comedy nor pathos in what seems like a rehash of his previous themes.
Christopher Nolan skillfully guides the audience through Memento's fractured narrative, seeping his film in existential dread.
Less nuanced than its source material, Memoirs of a Geisha may be a lavish production, but it still carries the simplistic air of a soap opera.
It boasts an intriguing cast and the special effects were groundbreaking, but they can't compensate for Memoirs of an Invisible Man's sadly pedestrian script.
Memories of Murder blends the familiar crime genre with social satire and comedy, capturing the all-too human desperation of its key characters.
Thanks to a smart script, spectacular set pieces, and charismatic performances from its leads, Men in Black is an entirely satisfying summer blockbuster hit.
Lacking the freshness of the first movie, MIB 2 recycles elements from its predecessor with mixed results.
It isn't exactly a persuasive argument for the continuation of the franchise, but Men in Black III is better than its predecessor and manages to exceed expectations.
De Niro and Goodings Jr. manage to turn in performances that make this by-the-numbers inspirational movie watchable.

movie_title: The Men Who Stare at Goats
critics_consensus: Though The Men Who Stare at Goats is a mostly entertaining, farcical glimpse of men at war, some may find its satire and dark humor less than edgy.
Men, Women & Children is timely, but director Jason Reitman's overbearing approach to its themes blunts the movie's impact.
Mental is a well-acted black comedy that suffers from jarring tonal shifts and a lack of comic discipline.

movie_title: Mercedes Sosa: The Voice of Latin America
William Shakespeare's The Merchant of Venice
critics_consensus: A respectable if uneven take on the Bard's The Merchant of Venice.
This overly wacky farce strains for sophistication but lacks polish and a coherent narrative.
Worthy themes and strong performances across the board make Merry Christmas, Mr. Lawrence an impactful story about bridging cultural divides.
Michael Keaton's directorial debut, The Merry Gentleman, is a slow character study aided greatly by the performances of Keaton and Kelly MacDonald.
Vincent Cassel is mesmerizing in the lead role. Even if it's less focused than its predecessor, it's more fun.
Handsome-looking but dramatically inert, Message in a Bottle maroons a formidable cast in a trite romance that lacks spark.

movie_title: The Messenger: The Story of Joan of Arc
critics_consensus: The heavy-handed narrative collapses under its own weight.
Fascinating behind-the-scenes look at how Metallica survives one of their more turbulent periods.
Imaginatively shot and edited, Metallica Through the Never is an electrifying, immersive concert film, though its fictional sequences are slightly less assured.

Though The Mexican makes a good attempt at originality, its ponderous length makes it wear out its welcome. Also, those looking forward to seeing Roberts and Pitt paired up may end up disappointed, as they are kept apart for most of the movie.

movie_title: Mia et le Migou (Mia and the Migoo)

critics_consensus: Miami Rhapsody has a handful of laughs, but wears its influences so heavily that it can't help but suffer by comparison.
Miami Vice is beautifully shot but the lead characters lack the charisma of their TV series counterparts, and the underdeveloped story is well below the standards of Michael Mann's better films.

Michael Clayton is one of the most sharply scripted films of 2007, with an engrossing premise and faultless acting. Director Tony Gilroy succeeds not only in capturing the audience's attention, but holding it until the credits roll.
As impressively ambitious as it is satisfyingly impactful, Michael Collins honors its subject's remarkable achievements with a magnetic performance from Liam Neeson in the title role.

While it may not be the definitive concert film (or the insightful backstage look) some will hope for, Michael Jackson's This Is It packs more than enough entertainment value to live up to its ambitious title.
High-brow humorists doing low-brow humor never hit their stride.
It might be a little too whimsical for its own good, but Micmacs delivers more of the inventive silliness that director Jean-Pierre Jeunet is known for.
Thoughtful, warm-hearted, and delightfully free of pretense, Mid-August Lunch offers viewers a light diversion with some surprising depth.
Middle Men benefits from a solid cast, particularly Luke Wilson, but its muddled script lets them down.
Wise, compassionate, and beautifully acted, Middle of Nowhere offers an early testament to writer-director Ava DuVernay's startling talent.

John Schlesinger's gritty, unrelentingly bleak look at the seedy underbelly of urban American life is undeniably disturbing, but Dustin Hoffman and Jon Voight's performances make it difficult to turn away.
Raw and unrelenting, Midnight Express is riveting in its realistic depiction of incarceration -- mining pathos from the simple act of enduring hardship.
It may not boast the depth of his classic films, but the sweetly sentimental Midnight in Paris is funny and charming enough to satisfy Woody Allen fans.

movie_title: Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil

critics_consensus: Enlivened by the antagonistic chemistry between Robert De Niro and Charles Grodin, Midnight Run is an uncommonly entertaining odd couple comedy.
Though Midnight's Children is beautiful to look at and poignant in spots, its script is too indulgent and Deepa Mehta's direction, though ambitious, fails to bring the story together cohesively.
It may not Woody Allen's best work, but the frothy, fun A Midsummer Night's Sex Comedy is still worth a look.
Heavy-handed and overwrought.
The Mighty Ducks has feel-good goals but only scores a penalty shot for predictability.
Angelina Jolie conveys the full emotional range of a woman in a desperate situation in A Mighty Heart, an urgent yet tactful film about a difficult subject.

movie_title: Xing xing wang (The Mighty Peking Man) (Colossus of Congo) (Goliathon)

critics_consensus: A deft hybrid of laughs, espionage, and music, The Mighty Quinn is a smart, pleasant entertainment that offers an early example of Denzel Washington's onscreen magnetism.
Though not as uproariously funny as Guest's previous movies, A Mighty Wind is also more heartfelt.
Arguably Robert Redford's most inchoate work, The Milagro Beanfield War has plenty of beautiful moments, but they don't quite add up to a worthwhile whole.
Milarepa's confusing plot structure, simplistic message, and poor production values cause it to fall flat.
Tied together by a powerhouse performance from Joan Crawford, Mildred Pierce blends noir and social drama to soapily intoxicating effect.
Anchored by Sean Penn's powerhouse performance, Milk is a triumphant account of America's first openly gay man elected to public office.

movie_title: The Milk of Sorrow (La Teta Asustada)
critics_consensus: Claudia Llosa's deliberate pace and abstract storytelling may frustrate some viewers, but there's no denying the visual pleasures soaking in The Milk of Sorrow.

Though possibly more notable for its distinctive style than an airtight story, this Coen brothers take on the classic gangster flick features sharp dialogue, impressive cinematography, and a typically quirky cast of characters.
Pleasant to a fault, Million Dollar Arm is a middle-of-the-plate pitch that coasts on Jon Hamm's considerable charm without adding any truly original curves to Disney's inspirational sports formula.

Clint Eastwood's assured direction - combined with knockout performances from Hilary Swank and Morgan Freeman - help Million Dollar Baby to transcend its clichÃ©s, and the result is deeply heartfelt and moving.
Critics say the weirdness of The Million Dollar Hotel is more grating and pretentious than interesting. Also, it takes too long to get to the conclusion.
A charming children fable even adults can enjoy.

movie_title: Milton Glaser: To Inform and Delight

critics_consensus: Plumbing the depths of tragedy without succuming to melodrama, Chang-dong Lee's Secret Sunshine is a grueling, albeit moving, piece of beautifully acted cinema.
The Last Mimzy makes efforts to be a fun children's movie, but unsuccessfully juggles too many genres and subplots -- eventually settling as an unfocused, slightly dull affair.
A retread of Ten Little Indians that lacks the source material's wit.
Thought-provoking and visceral, Steven Spielberg successfully combines high concept ideas and high octane action in this fast and febrile sci-fi thriller.
Kurt Russell's performance guides this cliche-ridden tale into the realm of inspirational, nostalgic goodness.
Miracle at St. Anna is a well-intentioned but overlong, disjointed affair that hits few of the right notes.
The Miracle of Morgan's Creek finds director Preston Sturges at his most zanily subversive -- not to mention hilarious.
Irrefutable proof that gentle sentimentalism can be the chief ingredient in a wonderful film, Miracle on 34th Street delivers a warm holiday message without resorting to treacle.
Miscast and dramatically inert, Miral is a thin chronicle of geopolitical history that offers only shallow insight into the Israeli-Palestinian conflict and characters with even less depth.

Like most of Tarsem Singh's films, Mirror Mirror is undeniably beautiful -- but its treatment of the age-old Snow White fable lacks enough depth or originality to set it apart from the countless other adaptations of the tale.
While visually dazzling, there isn't enough story to hang all the fancy effects on.
Elevated by standout performances from James Caan and Kathy Bates, this taut and frightening film is one of the best Stephen King adaptations to date.
Misery Loves Comedy starts with an idea worth exploring, but proves frustratingly unable to enlighten or amuse.

movie_title: Mishima: A Life in Four Chapters
critics_consensus: Paul Schrader's directorial masterpiece is a classy and imaginative portrait enriched by a stunning score and impressive cinematography.
Miss Bala's subject is loaded enough, but the frantic and muscular filmmaking puts this movie in a whole new league.
Though critics say Bullock is funny and charming, she can't overcome a bad script that makes the movie feel too much like a fluffy, unoriginal sitcom.
Sandra Bullock is still as appealing as ever; too bad the movie is not pageant material.
Miss Julie definitely gives Jessica Chastain and Colin Farrell room to shine, but neglects to leave them a solid enough setting to augment their efforts.

movie_title: Miss Pettigrew Lives for a Day
critics_consensus: Miss Pettigrew is a breezy period comedy carried by the strong performances of Amy Adams and Frances McDormand.
A charming biopic that maintains its sweetness even in sadder moments.
Full of special effects, Brian DePalma's update of Mission: Impossible has a lot of sweeping spectacle, but the plot is sometimes convoluted.
Your cranium may crave more substance, but your eyes will feast on the amazing action sequences.
Fast-paced, with eye-popping stunts and special effects, the latest Mission: Impossible installment delivers everything an action fan could ask for. A thrilling summer popcorn flick.
Stylish, fast-paced, and loaded with gripping set pieces, the fourth Mission: Impossible is big-budget popcorn entertainment that really works.
Beauty only goes skin deep in this shallow but visually stunning film.
Mississippi Burning draws on real-life tragedy to impart a worthy message with the measured control of an intelligent drama and the hard-hitting impact of a thriller.
Frank Darabont's impressive camerawork and politically incisive script make The Mist a truly frightening experience.
Carefully balanced between the dark and the dreamy, Mister Foe is a charged coming-of-age story with whimsy and bite.
Mixed Nuts may provoke strong allergic reactions in all but the most undemanding filmgoers -- and the most forgiving Steve Martin fans.
Despite an abundance of style and some big names, Mobsters can't escape its empty plotting, numbing violence, and Gangster Movie 101 concepts.
A sodden, overly stylized mess that's even less compelling than a TV episode.

movie_title: Modern Life (Profils paysans: la vie moderne)

critics_consensus: A slapstick skewering of industrialized America, Modern Times is as politically incisive as it is laugh-out-loud hilarious.
Nearly everyone is miscast in this disjointed and slow-moving portrait of Italian artist Amedeo Modigliani.
Dark, depraved, and unforgettably sordid, Moebius leavens its perversity with originality and wit.
Molly never really elevates above uninspired, cliche-ridden moments.

movie_title: Molokai: The Story of Father Damien
Mom and Dad Save the World

critics_consensus: Mommie Dearest certainly doesn't lack for conviction, and neither does Faye Dunaway's legendary performance as a wire-wielding monster; unfortunately, the movie is too campy and undisciplined to transcend guilty pleasure.
Cheap-looking, unfunny, and kind of sexist to boot, Moms' Night Out is a disappointment from start to finish.
Jacques Tati's most accessible film is a paean to gentle values and observing the small details of life.
Though Mona Lisa Smile espouses the value of breaking barriers, the movie itself is predictable and safe.

movie_title: Mondays in the Sun (Los Lunes al sol)
critics_consensus: Javier Bardem gives an outstanding performance in this hought-provoking (though occasionally plodding) movie about the effects of unemployment on a group of former shipyard workers.
Loud, incoherent, and aimless, Money Train reunites Snipes and Harrelson -- and proves that starring duos are far from immune to the law of diminishing returns.
Director Bennett Miller, along with Brad Pitt and Jonah Hill, take a niche subject and turn it into a sharp, funny, and touching portrait worthy of baseball lore.
The sweeping Mongol mixes romance, family drama, and enough flesh-ripping battle scenes to make sense of Ghenghis Khan's legendary stature.

movie_title: Monkey Shines: An Experiment in Fear
critics_consensus: While not one of horror legend George Romero's more evolved efforts, Monkey Shines delivers enough primal fear to satisfy more forgiving genre enthusiasts.
Though original and full of bizarre visuals, Monkeybone is too shapeless a movie, with unengaging characters and random situations that fail to build up laughs.
Monsieur Lahzar is a tender and thoughtful portrait of a man with hidden grief and also a compelling exploration of the teacher-student dynamic.
Charles Chaplin adds an undercurrent of malice to his comedic persona in Monsieur Verdoux, an unsettling satire that subverts the tramp's image to perversely amusing effect.
An insightful, energetic blend of Hollywood and Bollywood styles, Monsoon Wedding is a colorful, exuberant celebration of modern-day India, family, love, and life.
Charlize Theron gives a searing, deglamorized performance as real life serial killer Aileen Wuornos in Monster, an intense, disquieting portrait of a profoundly damaged soul.

movie_title: Monster Camp: The Story of NERO Seattle

critics_consensus: Monster House welcoms kids and adults alike into a household full of smart, monstrous fun.
A fun '80s adventure with a slightly scary twist, The Monster Squad offers tween-friendly horror with just enough of a kick.

movie_title: The Monster That Challenged the World

critics_consensus: While Jane Fonda steals the movie in her return to the screen, a tired script and flimsy performances make this borderline comedy fall flat.
It doesn't quite live up to its intriguing premise, but Monsters is a surprising blend of alien-invasion tropes, political themes, and relationship drama.
Somber and thought provoking, Monster's Ball has great performances all around.
Clever, funny, and delightful to look at, Monsters, Inc. delivers another resounding example of how Pixar elevated the bar for modern all-ages animation.
Offering Monsters, Inc. fans a return visit with beloved characters, Monsters University delivers funny and thoughtful family entertainment for viewers of any age.
Though it doesn't approach the depth of the best animated films, Monsters Vs. Aliens has enough humor and special effects to entertain moviegoers of all ages.
Although it has its charming moments, Monte Carlo is mostly silly, predictable stuff that never pushes beyond the boundaries of formula.

movie_title: Monty Python and the Holy Grail
critics_consensus: A cult classic as gut-bustingly hilarious as it is blithely ridiculous, Monty Python and the Holy Grail has lost none of its exceedingly silly charm.
One of the more cutting-edge films of the 1970s, this religious farce from the classic comedy troupe is as poignant as it is funny and satirical.

movie_title: Monty Python's The Meaning of Life
critics_consensus: Monty Python's the Meaning of Life is rude, ribald, and unafraid to take comedic risks -- which is to say it should more than satisfy fans of the titular troupe.
Mood Indigo is far from Michel Gondry's most compelling work, but it doesn't skimp on the visual whimsy and heartfelt emotion fans have come to expect.
Boosted by Sam Rockwell's intense performance, Moon is a compelling work of science-fiction, and a promising debut from director Duncan Jones.
Though the story feels rather contrived, Moonlight Mile is redeemed by the good performances of its cast.
Warm, whimsical, and poignant, the immaculately framed and beautifully acted Moonrise Kingdom presents writer/director Wes Anderson at his idiosyncratic best.
Led by energetic performances from Nicolas Cage and Cher, Moonstruck is an exuberantly funny tribute to love and one of the decade's most appealing comedies.
Though the film may not delve as deep as some would prefer, More Than a Game is an inspiring documentary featuring likable youngsters, a positive message, and some exciting in-game footage.
It's lifted by affable performances from its impeccable cast, and it's often charming -- but Morning Glory is also inconsistent and derivative.
Breathtaking scenery aside, Morning Light is geared more for the sailing enthusiasts than for the average viewers.
Despite an effective otherwordly atmosphere and appropriately cheesy visuals, Mortal Kombat suffers from its poorly constructed plot, laughable dialogue, and subpar acting.

With its shallow characters, low budget special effects, and mindless fight scenes, Mortal Kombat - Annihilation offers minimal plot development and manages to underachieve the low bar set by its predecessor.
Harrison Ford capably tackles a tough, unlikable role, producing a fascinating and strange character study.
Mostly Martha may have a predictable plot, but it still feels charming and fresh, and the food will make you hungry.
Eerie and satirical, Motel Hell has no vacancy when it comes to low-brow horror gags.
Though it occasionally veers into unnecessary melodrama, Mother and Child benefits from a stellar cast and writer-director Rodrigo Garcia's finely detailed, bravely unsentimental script.
Director Andrew Dosunmu's style takes some getting used to, but Mother of George compensates with powerful acting, a thoughtful script, and gorgeous visuals.

movie_title: Mother of Tears: The Third Mother
critics_consensus: As excessive and ketchup laden as predecessors Suspiria and Inferno, Dario Argento's Mother of Tears completes the trilogy with the same baroque grandeur and soggy 1970s sensibilities.
Despite Uma Thurman's comic skills, Motherhood's contrived set-ups and cliched jokes keep this comedy from delivering laughs -- or insights into modern parenting.
A creepy thriller that poses more questions than it answers.
A love-it-or-hate-it experience, Moulin Rouge is all style, all giddy, over-the-top spectacle. But it's also daring in its vision and wildly original.
In a setting both visually stunning and cruel, this Eastern film evokes the epic spirit of old-fashioned Westerns.
Mouse Hunt gets trapped under the weight of its excessive slapstick antics.
Though the premise may be modest on the surface, Carrere uses a man and his mustache that may or may not exist as a springboard into psychological suspense and unsettling questions.
Writer-director Alison Murray has a clear connection to the story, but Mouth to Mouth is too disjointed and thinly sketched to satisfy.
A star-studded turkey, Movie 43 is loaded with gleefully offensive and often scatological gags, but it's largely bereft of laughs.
This strange, heartfelt documentary from film critic Godfrey Cheshire is a fascinating examination of his family roots, as well as an evocative meditation on the complexities of the South.

movie_title: Mr. Blandings Builds His Dream House

critics_consensus: Bernie Mac demonstrates he can play the game even if the movie's a few innings short of a complete game.

Although this action-romance suffers from weak writing and one too many explosions, the chemistry generated by onscreen couple Pitt and Jolie is palpable enough to make this a thoroughly enjoyable summer action flick.
Mr. Bean's Holiday means well, but good intentions can't withstand the 90 minutes of monotonous slapstick and tired, obvious gags.
The setup is intriguing, but Mr. Brooks overstuffs itself with twists and subplots, becoming more preposterous as it goes along.
This update of Capra doesn't hold a candle to the original, and even on its own merits, Mr. Deeds is still indifferently acted and stale.
A feel-good story brought to life by a terrific ensemble cast, Mr. Holland's Opus plucks the heartstrings without shame -- and with undeniable skill.

movie_title: Mr. Hulot's Holiday (Les Vacances de Monsieur Hulot)
critics_consensus: Pleasant, lackadaisical, and very charming, Monsieur Hulot lays the groundwork for Jacques Tati's later, more accomplished films.
Mr. Magorium's Wonder Emporium's title is much more fun that the film itself, as the colorful visuals and talented players can't make up for a bland story.
Mr. Mom makes up for its stereotype-driven premise with a sweet script and charming work from a well-matched cast led by Michael Keaton and Teri Garr.
Mr. Nobody's narrative tangles may bedevil as much as they entertain, but its big ambitions and absorbing visuals make for an intriguing addition to director Jaco Van Dormael's filmography.
Mr. Peabody & Sherman offers a surprisingly entertaining burst of colorful all-ages fun, despite its dated source material and rather convoluted plot.
Blandly inoffensive and thoroughly predictable, Mr. Popper's Penguins could have been worse -- but it should have been better.
Billy Crystal's flawed directorial debut can't seem to decide whether it wants the viewer to love its protagonist or hate him, but it features fine work from Crystal and his co-stars.
Led by a masterful performance from Timothy Spall and brilliantly directed by Mike Leigh, Mr. Turner is a superior Hollywood biopic.

movie_title: Mr. Warmth: The Don Rickles Project

critics_consensus: Underutilizing a talented cast, Mr. Woodcock lacks the comic energy and timing to make the most of its intriguing premise.

Thanks to some top notch acting, the chemistry between its stars, and a witty, thoughtful script, Mrs. Brown delivers a nuanced and entertaining, if not entirely factual, account of a seldom explored historical relationship.
On paper, Mrs. Doubtfire might seem excessively broad or sentimental, but Robin Williams shines so brightly in the title role that the end result is difficult to resist.
Judi Dench and Bob Hoskins shine in this warm, witty period piece.
An excessively sentimental piece of propaganda, Mrs. Miniver nonetheless succeeds, due largely to Greer Garson's powerful performance.
Bittersweet and endearing, this film about aging and unexpected friendship is a lovely vehicle for Joan Plowright.

movie_title: Mrs. Parker and the Vicious Circle (Mrs. Parker and the Round Table)

critics_consensus: Lighthearted to a fault, Much Ado About Nothing's giddy energy and intimate charm make for an entertaining romantic comedy -- and a Shakespearean adaptation that's hard to resist.
Bolstered by a strong performance from Matthew McConaughey in the title role, Mud offers an engaging Southern drama that manages to stay sweet and heartwarming without being sappy.
As much legal thriller as objective documentary, this account of a farmer's battle with Zimbabwe's regime serves as a powerful and emotional attack upon President Mugabe.
Exploring themes of family duty and honor, Mulan breaks new ground as a Disney film, while still bringing vibrant animation and sprightly characters to the screen.
Smarter than its scatological premise might suggest, The Mule offers solidly explosive laughs for fans of dark comedy.

David Lynch's dreamlike and mysterious Mulholland Drive is a twisty neo-noir with an unconventional structure that features a mesmirizing performance from Naomi Watts as a woman on the dark fringes of Hollywood.
This high-concept experiment only proves that a comedy actually can have too much Michael Keaton.
Memorable moments are few and far between.
In The Mummy Returns, the special effects are impressive, but the characters seem secondary to the computer generated imagery.

movie_title: The Mummy: Tomb of the Dragon Emperor
critics_consensus: With middling CG effects and a distinct lack of fun, The Mummy: Tomb of the Dragon Emperor finds the series past its prime.
Munich can't quite achieve its lofty goals, but this thrilling, politically even-handed look at the fallout from an intractable political conflict is still well worth watching.

It may not be the finest version of Charles Dickens' tale to grace the screen, but The Muppet Christmas Carol is funny and heartwarming, and serves as a good introduction to the story for young viewers.
The Muppet Movie, the big-screen debut of Jim Henson's plush creations, is smart, lighthearted, and fun for all ages.
Though less Muppet-centric than the original trilogy, Muppet Treasure Island is an energetic, cheerful take on Robert Louis Stevenson's classic adventure, with typically solid gags.
If Muppets from Space lacks the magic and wit of its cinematic predecessors, this pleasingly silly space romp is funny and clever enough to make for better-than-average family entertainment.
While it may not reach the delirious heights of The Muppets, Muppets Most Wanted still packs in enough clever gags, catchy songs, and celebrity cameos to satisfy fans of all ages.

If it's not quite as sharp as The Muppet Movie, The Muppets Take Manhattan is still a smart, delightfully old-fashioned tale that follows the formula established by the first two movies -- a madcap adventure assisted by a huge group of human stars.
Despite a strong cast and story inspired by incredible real-life events, Murder in the First is strictly second rate.
Murder, intrigue, and a star-studded cast make this stylish production of Murder on the Orient Express one of the best Agatha Christie adaptations to see the silver screen.

movie_title: Muriel ou Le Temps d'un Retour (The Time of Return)

critics_consensus: Heartfelt and quirky, though at times broad, Muriel's Wedding mixes awkward comedy, oddball Australian characters, and a nostalgia-heavy soundtrack.
Essential for soul fans and entertaining for novices, Muscle Shoals offers a compelling, warts-and-all glimpse at one of the most fascinating stories in modern American music.
Despite quirky and original writing, the subject matter feels too removed to produce laughs.
Its languid pace may frustrate some viewers, but for patient filmgoers, Museum Hours offers a carefully observed portrait of the human condition.
Music & Lyrics is a light and pleasant romantic comedy that succeeds because of the considerable charm of its co-stars. The music segments featuring Hugh Grant are worth the price of admission.
Music from the Inside Out lets the act of making music -- and the work that goes into it -- speak for itself, offering an engaging look at the life of an orchestra member along the way.
Meryl Streep's depiction of an ordinary person doing extraordinary things transcends, inspires, and entertains.
Music Within is a well-intentioned but pedestrian production of a story that deserves better treatment.
Despite good work from its likable leads, the romantic comedy Must Love Dogs is too predictable.
Bad acting, poor CGI and clunky script mean this sci-fi thriller is lacking in all departments including the thrills.
Director Bujalski continues to give cinematic voice to awkward, literate twentysomethings with noteworthy smarts and tenderness.
A beautifully animated diversion, My Dog Tulip is as comforting and delightful as cuddling with your own canine companion.
My Amityville Horror offers an unsettlingly ambiguous personal perspective on the true story that spawned a horror franchise.
My Beautiful Laundrette is fast and all over the place because it has so much to say, and show, including a highly watchable fresh-faced Daniel Day-Lewis.

movie_title: My Best Fiend (Mein liebster Feind - Klaus Kinski)

critics_consensus: Although the plot may sound contrived, the performances of Daniel Auteuil and Dany Boon manage to turn My Best Friend into an earnest and witty romp.
Though it sometimes feels like a television sitcom, My Big Fat Greek Wedding is good-hearted, lovable, and delightfully eccentric, with a sharp script and lead performance from Nia Vardalos.
This gory, senses-assaulting slasher film is an unpretentious, effective mix of old-school horror stylings and modern 3D technology.
Though well filmed, My Blueberry Nights is a mixed bag of dedicated performers working with thin material.
T. Bill debuts as an affectionate director, keenly aware of growing pains.
Offensive, incoherent, and ineptly acted and directed.
A tough, tender tale of familial angst with careful attention to detail, My Brother the Devil is a strong debut from director Sally El Hosaini.
This war documentary offers a valuable look at Iraqi life under the U.S. occupation, and finds a compelling central subject in Dr. Riyadh.
The deft comic interplay between Joe Pesci and Marisa Tomei helps to elevate My Cousin Vinny's predictable script, and the result is a sharp, hilarious courtroom comedy.
Canny and coolly confident, My Darling Clementine is a definitive dramatization of the Wyatt Earp legend that shoots from the hip and hits its target in breezy style.

A love-it-or-hate-it stalkerazzi documentary, My Date With Drew effectively draws on America's celeb-obsessed pop culture so that viewers either unabashedly identify with it, or are filing restraining orders on Drew Barrymore's behalf.
Critics say My Dog Skip is cute, wholesome entertainment for the family. It's especially designed to appeal to your sentiment, but you might find yourself choking up just the same.

movie_title: My Father and the Man in Black
My Father's Glory (La Gloria de Mon Pere)

critics_consensus: Loud, effects-ridden comedy with no real humor.
Though well-acted, My First Mister succumbs to contrived sentimentality in its last half.
Disturbing and heart-wrenching documentary about a 53-years-old woman raising 11 children.
Director Amir Bar-Lev grapples with exposing the authenticity of four-year-old Marla's paintings at the sake of burdening her publicly shamed family to transfixing results.
No doubt most will come to My Left Foot for Daniel Day-Lewis' performance, but the movie's refusal to go downbeat will keep it in viewer minds afterwards.

movie_title: My Life as a Dog (Mitt Liv som Hund)
critics_consensus: A coming-of-age story with uncommon depth and sensitivity, My Life as a Dog is sweet, sincere, and utterly charming.
With stereotypical characters and a shopworn plot, My Life in Ruins is a charmless romantic comedy.

movie_title: Le ChÃ¢teau de Ma MÃ¨re (My Mother's Castle)
My Name Is Joe (Mein Name ist Joe)

critics_consensus: My Name Is Khan rests on powerful performances to tell an affecting story that blends timely themes and old-fashioned Bollywood melodrama.
Although My Old Lady doesn't quite live up to its stars' talents, Kevin Kline and Maggie Smith carry the film capably whenever they're together onscreen.
A tantalizing glimpse of a talented director and his stars all at the top of their respective games, Gus Van Sant's loose reworking of Henry IV is smart, sad and audacious.

movie_title: My Son, My Son, What Have Ye Done

critics_consensus: My Summer of Love is a moody, bittersweet love story featuring outstanding performances from the leads.
My Super Ex=Girlfriend is an only sporadically amusing spoof on the superhero genre that misses the mark with a nerd-turned-superwoman who embodies sexist clichÃ©s.
Michelle Williams shines in My Week with Marilyn, capturing the magnetism and vulnerability of Marilyn Monroe.
A listless interpretation of Michael Chabon's first novel, Mysteries of Pittsburgh features none of the source material's charm, but has coming-of-age film cliches in abundance.
Bold performances and sensitive, spot-on direction make watching this difficult tale of trauma and abuse a thought-provoking, resonant experience.
The lack of hockey action and authenticity left critics cold.
Absurd characters and quirky gags are brought to life by a talented cast, providing this superhero spoof with lots of laughs.
Mystery Science Theater 3000: The Movie may be thin and uneven, but it's hilarious in enough of the right spots to do the show's big-screen transition justice.
Mystic Pizza is like its namesake food: it's cheesy, topped with romance, and rises to the occasion.
Anchored by the exceptional acting of its strong cast, Mystic River is a somber drama that unfolds in layers and conveys the tragedy of its story with visceral power.

movie_title: The Myth Of The American Sleepover
critics_consensus: Somber and sweet, The Myth of the American Sleepover authentically evokes adolescence -- and all of the awkwardness and heartbreak that comes with it.
Lurid without enough evident deeper meaning to justify its prurient impulses, Bad Guy runs the gamut from confusing to simply off-putting.

At times hilarious, but other times offensive, Director Jared Hess is unable to recapture the collective charisma of his Napoleon characters, instead relying on a one-joke concept that runs out of steam. Sure to entertain the adolescents, however.

movie_title: Naked Ambition: An R Rated Look at an X Rated Industry
The Naked Gun 2 1/2: The Smell of Fear
critics_consensus: Naked Gun 2 1/2: The Smell of Fear delivers a handful of moderate laughs, but overall, its strained antics pale in comparison to its gut-busting predecessor.
An ambitious exploration of the immigrant experience with a talented cast that serves the material well.
Emma Roberts is bubbly and charming as Nancy Drew, the junior detective. But despite her best efforts, Nancy Drew still lacks excitement, surprise, and compelling secondary characters.
This powerful and horrific documentary brings the atrocities committed at Nanking to light without sugarcoating any of the brutality.
The Nanny Diaries' miscast lead and unrealistic, one-dimensional characters make this class satire far less effective than it should've been.
A bit alarming at first, Nanny McPhee has a hard edge to counter Mary Poppins-style sweetness, but it still charms us and teaches some valuable lessons.
Emma Thompson's second labor of love with the Nanny McPhee character actually improves on the first, delivering charming family fare with an excellent cast.
A charming, quirky, and often funny comedy.
The weakest film in Reggio's trilogy.
Jason Patric and Ray Liotta are electrifying in this gritty, if a little too familiar, cop drama.
Disturbing, thought-provoking, and timely, Narco Cultura sheds some crucial light on an important -- and underserved -- subject.
Comprehensive yet brisk, Nas: Time Is Illmatic offers an absorbing look at a hip-hop classic and the life of the artist who made it.
A thrill ride for fans, but those looking for a deeper experience will be choking on exhaust.
Robert Altman captures the bravado and cynicism of the American dream in Nashville, a sprawling epic bursting with vivid performances and an unforgettable soundtrack.

movie_title: National Lampoon Presents The Beach Party at the Threshold of Hell

critics_consensus: It aspires to Farrelly-level offensiveness, but the PG-13 rating and a dearth of decent gags renders Gold Diggers tame, toothless, and dull.
The talents of director John Landis and Saturday Night Live's irrepressible John Belushi conspired to create a rambunctious, subversive college comedy that continues to resonate.
While Christmas Vacation may not be the most disciplined comedy, it's got enough laughs and good cheer to make for a solid seasonal treat.
European Vacation charts a course through a succession of pretty destinations, but the journey itself lacks the laughs that made the original outing so memorable.

movie_title: Homo Erectus (National Lampoon's The Stoned Age)

critics_consensus: Blessed by a brilliantly befuddled star turn from Chevy Chase, National Lampoon's Vacation is one of the more consistent -- and thoroughly quotable -- screwball comedies of the 1980s.
A derivative gross-out comedy that's short on laughs.
The action in National Security is mindless, while the humor says nothing insightful about racial issues.
National Treasure is no treasure, but it's a fun ride for those who can forgive its highly improbable plot.
A talented cast goes to waste in the improbable National Treasure: Book of Secrets, which is eerily similar to the first film.
National Velvet makes the most of a breakout performance from Elizabeth Taylor, delivering a timeless family-friendly tearjerker that avoids straying into the sentimental.
The Nativity Story is a dull retelling of a well-worn tale with the look and feel of a high-school production.
Though heavy with sentiment, The Natural is an irresistible classic, and a sincere testament to America's national pastime.

Natural Born Killers explodes off the screen with style, but its satire is too blunt to offer any fresh insight into celebrity or crime -- pummeling the audience with depravity until the effect becomes deadening.

movie_title: Ne le Dis Ã  Personne (Tell No One)
critics_consensus: An intense, well-crafted thriller, Tell No One is equal parts heart-pounding and heart-wrenching.

movie_title: Ne Te Retourne Pas (Don't Look Back)

critics_consensus: Elegant in its simplicity and poetic in its message, Nebraska adds another stirringly resonant chapter to Alexander Payne's remarkable filmography.
This likeable, goofy football comedy has its moments, but it ultimately adheres too closely to the sports movie playbook to overcome the cliches in the script.
With stock characters and a preposterous plot, this noisily diverting video game adaptation fulfills a Need for Speed and little else.
With plenty of bawdy humor evenly spread between its well-matched stars, Neighbors earns its R rating -- and filmgoers' laughs.
The premise isn't without potential and Sandra Bullock is as likable as ever, but The Net lacks sufficient thrills -- or plausible plot points -- to recommend catching.

Driven by populist fury and elevated by strong direction, powerful acting, and an intelligent script, Network's searing satire of ratings-driven news remains sadly relevant more than four decades later.

movie_title: Never Apologize: A Personal Visit With Lindsay Anderson
critics_consensus: Essentially a stage production of Malcolm Macdowell musing over his departed friend, and brit director Lindsey Anderson. Macdowell makes for an engaging raconteur, but only for Anderson fans.
Though not without its pleasures, Never Back Down faithfully adheres to every imaginable fight movie clichÃ©.
Unoriginal and unremarkable high school satire adds little to the genre.
Pokes fun at the obsessive personalities that make up peculiar American subcultures, but misses its targets too often to be more than merely passable.
DMX's menacing charisma is put to good use in this stylish but hackneyed modern-day noir.
With Never Let Me Go, Mark Romanek has delivered a graceful adaptation that captures the spirit of the Ishiguro novel -- which will be precisely the problem for some viewers.
While the rehashed story feels rather uninspired and unnecessary, the return of both Sean Connery and a more understated Bond make Never Say Never Again a watchable retread.

movie_title: Never Sleep Again: The Elm Street Legacy

critics_consensus: Never Talk to Strangers -- and never make the mistake of believing this silly stalker mystery is the best available viewing option.

movie_title: New Police Story (San ging chaat goo si)
The New Adventures of Pippi Longstocking

critics_consensus: Generic, confusing, and trashy, New Best Friend is a laughably bad, obvious campus whodunit.
Cliched and short on charm, New In Town is a pat genre exercise that fails to bring the necessary heat to its Minnesota setting.
Shallow, sappy, and dull, New Year's Eve assembles a star-studded cast for no discernible purpose.
Arthur Kane is a fascinating subject in what ultimately proves to be a touching, bittersweet documentary.
Like many anthologies, New York, I Love You has problems of consistency, but it isn't without its moments.
Feels more like a calculated product designed to expand the Olsens' brand than an actual movie. Also, it contains ethnic stereotyping and sexual innuendo.

movie_title: Lo Squartatore di New York (The New York Ripper)

critics_consensus: Extra! Extra! Read all about Newsies instead of suffering through its underwhelming musical interludes, although Christian Bale makes for a spirited hero.
The Newton Boys uses a sharp cast and absorbing period detail to help make up for the frustrations of a story puzzlingly short on dramatic tension.
Numerous plot holes and poorly motivated characters prevent Next from being the thought-provoking sci-fi flick it could've been.
Story elements clash and acting falls short.
Rife with half-baked jokes and excessive violence, Next Day Air is an uninspired stoner comedy.
Next Friday lacks the fun of the original Friday. The movie is messy and plotless and relies on unfunny vulgar gags.

The Next Karate Kid is noteworthy for giving audiences the chance to see a pre-Oscars Hilary Swank, but other than a typically solid performance from Pat Morita, this unnecessary fourth installment in the franchise has very little to offer.
Endearing performances create characters you care about.
Russell Crowe and Elizabeth Banks give it their all, but their solid performances aren't quite enough to compensate for The Next Three Days' uneven pace and implausible plot.

movie_title: Daughter of the Nile (Ni luo he nu er)

critics_consensus: Nick and Norah's Infinite Playlist combines a pair of charming leads, the classic New York backdrop, and a sweet soundtrack.
It isn't the worst '90s action thriller, but by bungling a story pitting Johnny Depp against Christopher Walken, the rote Nick of Time ranks among the most disappointing.
Nicotina has plenty of action, but all that energy isn't enough to cover for the forgettable story between the set pieces.
Parents might call this either a spectacle-filled adventure or a shallow and vapid CG-fest, depending on whether they choose to embrace this on the same level as their kids.

movie_title: Night at the Museum 2: Battle of the Smithsonian
critics_consensus: Night at the Museum: Battle at the Smithsonian is busy enough to keep the kids interested but the slapstick goes overboard and the special effects (however well executed) throw the production into mania.

movie_title: Night at the Museum: Secret of the Tomb
critics_consensus: While not without its moments, Night at the Museum: Secret of the Tomb is a less-than-inspired sendoff for the trilogy.
Has the same problems as the worst SNL movies: one-note characters and plots unreasonably stretched to feature length runtime.
A bold, original debut, Night Catches Us personalizes a tumultuous period in American history thanks to strong performances from Anthony Mackie and Kerry Washington.
A uniquely character-driven thriller with a finely composed cast and some outstanding direction from Kelly Reichardt, Night Moves bolsters its thought-provoking themes with compelling drama.
Featuring Robert Mitchum's formidable performance as a child-hunting preacher, The Night of the Hunter is a disturbing look at good and evil.

movie_title: Die Nacht der lebenden Loser (Night of the Living Dorks)
La Notte di San Lorenzo (Night of the Shooting Stars) (The Night of San Lorenzo)
Il portiere di notte (The Night Porter)

critics_consensus: This Russian horror/fantasy film pits darkness and light against each other using snazzy CGI visuals to create an extraordinary atmosphere of a dank, gloomy city wrestling with dread.
Restless, visually sleek, and powered by a lithe star performance from Jake Gyllenhaal, Nightcrawler offers dark, thought-provoking thrills.
The Nightmare Before Christmas is a stunningly original and visually delightful work of stop-motion animation.

movie_title: Incubo sulla cittÃ  contaminata (Nightmare City) (Invasion by the Atomic Zombies)

critics_consensus: Wes Craven's intelligent premise, combined with the horrifying visual appearance of Freddy Krueger, still causes nightmares to this day.
Visually faithful but lacking the depth and subversive twists that made the original so memorable, the Nightmare on Elm Street remake lives up to its title in the worst possible way.

movie_title: Nightmares in Red, White and Blue

critics_consensus: Derivative and schmaltzy, Nicholas Sparks' Nights in Rodanthe is strongly mottled by contrivances that even the charisma of stars Diane Lane and Richard Gere can't repair.

movie_title: Nights of Cabiria (Le Notti di Cabiria)
critics_consensus: Giulietta Masina is remarkable as a chronically unfortunate wretch with an indomitable spirit in Federico Fellini's unrelentingly bleak -- yet ultimately uplifting -- odyssey through heartbreak.
Despite good intentions, Nim's Island flounders under an implausible storyline, simplistic stock characters, and distracting product placement.
It has a game, great-looking cast, led by the always worthwhile Daniel Day-Lewis, but Rob Marshall's Nine is chaotic and curiously distant.

movie_title: The Nine Lives of Fritz the Cat

critics_consensus: Nine Months finds writer-director Chris Columbus playing to his worst comedic instincts -- and relying far too heavily on the trademark tics of his miscast leading man.
With Greta Garbo proving her comedy chops in the twilight of her career, Ninotchka is a can't-miss classic.

movie_title: The Ninth Configuration (Twinkle, Twinkle, Killer Kane)

critics_consensus: Even though the film is stylish and atmospheric, critics say The Ninth Gate meanders aimlessly and is often ludicrous. And despite the advertising, there's hardly any chills.
Much like its subject's time in office, Nixon might have ended sooner -- but what remains is an engrossing, well-acted look at the rise and fall of a fascinating political figure.
No uses its history-driven storyline to offer a bit of smart, darkly funny perspective on modern democracy and human nature.

Bolstered by powerful lead performances from Javier Bardem, Josh Brolin, and Tommy Lee Jones, No Country for Old Men finds the Coen brothers spinning cinematic gold out of Cormac McCarthy's grim, darkly funny novel.

Charles Ferguson's documentary provides a good summary of the decisions that led to the mess in post-war Iraq, and offers politically interested audiences something they'd been looking for: a lowdown on the decision making.
Dull, derivative, and generally uninspired, No Good Deed wastes its stars' talents -- and the audience's time.
For No Good Reason is a solid but surface-level look at gonzo artist Ralph Steadman's artistry and eccentricities.
Bleak and darkly humorous, No Man's Land vividly illustrates the absurdity of war.
While taking full advantage of its subject's colorful baseball career, No No: A Dockumentary also imparts broader, thought-provoking messages that should resonate with viewers who aren't sports fans.

movie_title: No One Knows About Persian Cats (Les Chats Persans)
critics_consensus: Bringing a dose of humor and a fresh perspective to a very serious subject, No One Knows About Persian Cats is an exhilarating, quietly powerful tribute to the courage of Iran's underground musicians.
No Place on Earth is a haunting and well-researched -- if occasionally uneven -- account of human endurance in Nazi Germany.
This romantic comedy may look good on paper, but it's too predictable and melancholy for the genre.

movie_title: No se aceptan devoluciones (Instructions Not Included)

critics_consensus: It benefits from the presence of Natalie Portman and director Ivan Reitman's steady hand, but No Strings Attached doesn't have the courage or conviction to follow through on its ribald premise.
Stocked with talented stars but lacking any clear idea of what to do with them, No Such Thing is ultimately far too uneven to recommend.

movie_title: No Way to Treat a Lady

critics_consensus: With sweeping visuals grounded by strong performances in service of a timeless tale told on a human scale, Darren Aronofsky's Noah brings the Bible epic into the 21st century.
Noel strains for holiday uplift, but -- despite the involvement of an outstanding ensemble cast -- settles for treacly sentiment instead.
A darkly humorous, quirky coming-of-age film, enhanced by its Icelandic setting.
A fascinating, if occasionally frustrating, documentary about Klaus Nomi, a cult figure in the New Wave Underground scene during the '80s.

movie_title: Non Ma Fille, Tu N'iras Pas Danser (Making Plans for Lena)
The Living Dead at Manchester Morgue

critics_consensus: While Liam Neeson is undoubtedly an asset, Non-Stop wastes its cast -- not to mention its solid premise and tense setup -- on a poorly conceived story that hinges on a thoroughly unbelievable final act.

Coming off his Oscar-nominated performance in Dreamgirls, the talented-but-inconsistent Eddie Murphy plays three roles in Norbit, a cruel, crass, stereotype-filled comedy that's more depressing than funny.
Its four-hour length is undeniably imposing, but Norte, the End of History rewards patient viewers with an absorbing, visually expansive viewing experience.
Laden with schmaltz and largely bereft of evident narrative purpose, North represents an early major disappointment from previously sure-handed director Rob Reiner.
Gripping, suspenseful, and visually iconic, this late-period Hitchcock classic laid the groundwork for countless action thrillers to follow.
Though sometimes melodramatic and formulaic, North Country is nonetheless a rousing, powerful story of courage and humanity.
Muddled overall, but perceptive and brutally realistic, North Dallas Forty also benefits from strong performances by Nick Nolte and Charles Durning. Football fans will likely find it fascinating.
A tense and gripping spectacular piece of snow-bound historical German film-making.
Strong direction and delicate performances save Noordzee, Texas from its narrative cliches.
Visually poetic, but may be too dramatically inert for some.
Norwegian Wood is a poetic adaptation of the Haruki Murakami novel that uses rapturous visuals to draw viewers in its exploration of young love and lasting death.

movie_title: Nos enfants nous accuseront (Food Beware: The French Organic Revolution)
Nosferatu, a Symphony of Horror (Nosferatu, eine Symphonie des Grauens) (Nosferatu the Vampire)
critics_consensus: One of the silent era's most influential masterpieces, Nosferatu's eerie, gothic feel -- and a chilling performance from Max Schreck as the vampire -- set the template for the horror films that followed.

movie_title: Nosferatu: Phantom der Nacht (Nosferatu the Vampyre)
critics_consensus: Stunning visuals from Werner Herzog and an intense portrayal of the famed bloodsucker from Klaus Kinski make this remake of Nosferatu a horror classic in its own right.
Nostalgia demands patience -- and rewards the investment with a hypnotic viewing experience that finds Tarkovsky in gratifyingly uncompromising form.
NATM has some funny moments, but the movie requires the audience to have familiarity with the movies being spoofed and a tolerance for toilet and sexual humor to be truly effective.

movie_title: Not as a Stranger (Morton Thompson's Not as a Stranger)

critics_consensus: Though well-intentioned, Not Easily Broken is bogged down by melodramatic plotting and stereotypical characters.
Exuberant and bittersweet, Not Fade Away is a coming-of-age story set to a British Invasion beat that occasionally meanders but mostly charms.

movie_title: Not Quite Hollywood: The Wild, Untold Story of Ozploitation!
critics_consensus: A raucous, fast-paced celebration of the Ozploitation films that came out of Australia in the 1970s and 1980s.

movie_title: Note by Note: The Making of Steinway L1037

critics_consensus: It's hard not to admire its unabashed sentimentality, but The Notebook is too clumsily manipulative to rise above its melodramatic clichÃ©s.
In this sharp psychological thriller, Judi Dench and Cate Blanchett give fierce, memorable performances as two schoolteachers locked in a battle of wits.
Nothing Bad Can Happen uses its protagonist's punishing ordeal to pose questions about faith that are well worth considering, even if the film can't quite answer them.
A well-crafted political thriller, Nothing But the Truth features a strong cast that helps the real-life drama make an effortless transition to the big screen.
The performances are the strength of Nothing Like the Holidays, a rather ordinary holiday comedy with a latin twist.
This biopic only skims the surface of Bettie Page's life, leaving her as a cipher, and additionally fails to place her iconic status in historical context.
Charming performances provide romance aplenty.

movie_title: Nous ne vieillirons pas ensemble (We Won't Grow Old Together)

critics_consensus: The quirky Novocaine flirts with both dark comedy and noir suspense, but the result is a jarring mix of tones which never quite mesh.
Now, Voyager is a Hollywood swooner with Bette Davis and Paul Henreid in a melodrama to end all melomers.

movie_title: Now You See Him, Now You Don't

critics_consensus: Now You See Me's thinly sketched characters and scattered plot rely on sleight of hand from the director to distract audiences.
Don't expect any musical insights, but this look at John Lennon's early life benefits from its restrained, low-key approach and some fine acting from Aaron Johnson.
Quirky in the best sense of the word, Nurse Betty finds director Neil LaBute corralling a talented cast in service of a sharp, imaginative script.
While Eddie Murphy is still hilarious as the entire Klump family, the movie falls apart because of uneven pacing, a poor script, and skits that rely on being gross rather than funny.
Though well-intentioned and serious in its exploration of teen violence, O is an uneven experiment that doesn't quite succeed.
Though not as good as Coen brothers' classics such as Blood Simple, the delightfully loopy O Brother, Where Art Thou? is still a lot of fun.
Lead actress Moon So-ri's stand out performance gives this harrowing film much of its power.
Visually striking but thinly scripted, Oblivion benefits greatly from its strong production values and an excellent performance from Tom Cruise.
Though it has a mean streak, and does not cater to all tastes, Observe and Report has gut-busting laughs and a fully committed Seth Rogen in irresistible form.
Tackling a sensitive subject with maturity, honesty, and wit, Obvious Child serves as a deeply promising debut for writer-director Gillian Robespierre.
Easygoing but lazy, Ocean's Eleven blithely coasts on the well-established rapport of the Rat Pack royalty.
As fast-paced, witty, and entertaining as it is star-studded and coolly stylish, Ocean's Eleven offers a well-seasoned serving of popcorn entertainment.
Ocean's Thirteen reverts to the formula of the first installment, and the result is another slick and entertaining heist film.
While some have found the latest star-studded heist flick to be a fun, glossy star vehicle, others declare it's lazy, self-satisfied and illogical.
It flirts with voyeurism, but this deeply personal look at a working-class family in upstate New York is piercingly honest and refreshingly unsentimental.
Rich in sweet sincerity, intelligence, and good old-fashioned inspirational drama, October Sky is a coming-of-age story with a heart to match its Hollywood craftsmanship.
Despite a couple of electrifying action sequences, Octopussy is a formulaic, anachronistic Bond outing.
With an emphasis on dread over gore and an ending that leaves the door wide open for sequels, Oculus could be just the first spine-tingling chapter in a new franchise for discerning horror fans.
Anton Yelchin is the right man for the title role, but Odd Thomas suffers from a jumbled tone.
Patient and restrained, Of Gods and Men asks deep, profound questions that will linger in the audience's mind long after the movie.
Excellent performances mark this leisurely paced film.
Mike Judge lampoons the office grind with its inspired mix of sharp dialogue and witty one-liners.
Old-fashioned without sacrificing its characters to simplicity, An Officer and a Gentleman successfully walks the fine line between sweeping romance and melodrama.
