Mysterious and provocative, Room 237 is a fascinating journey into the world of obsessive cinephilles.
As formally audacious as it is narratively brilliant, Rope connects a powerful ensemble in service of a darkly satisfying crime thriller from a master of the genre.
The dramatic aspects of Rory O'Shea Was Here veer into mawkish, formulaic sentiment, which undercuts the characters' individuality.
A frightening tale of Satanism and pregnancy that is even more disturbing than it sounds thanks to convincing and committed performances by Mia Farrow and Ruth Gordon.
Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead struggles in its journey from stage to screen, but a well-chosen trio of veteran talents keep things consistently watchable.
Thoughtful drama marred by structural problems.
Timely, solidly acted, and unabashedly earnest, Rosewater serves as an impressive calling card for first-time director Jon Stewart.
Roving Mars is a decent thrill ride even when it starts feeling like a commercial plug for NASA's failing space program.
Though its sweetness borders on sappiness, Roxanne is an unabashedly romantic comedy that remains one of Steve Martin's funniest.
Vintage MGM musical stuff, characterized by Stanley Donen's fleet direction and some amazing dance performances from star Fred Astaire.
A clever premise gets plenty of comic blood and violence, but its hampered by some questionable storytelling techniques from director Quentin Dupieux.
Cleverly written and wonderfully acted, Ruby Sparks overcomes its occasional lags in pace with an abundance of charm and wit.
Rudderless asks its cast to carry an awful lot of weight for its occasionally manipulative story; fortunately, this talented bunch -- led by Billy Crudup -- is often more than up to the task.
Despite its fair share of sports movie cliches, Rudo y Cursi marks an auspicious directing debut for Carlos CuarÃ³n, and features strong performances from GarcÃ­a Bernal and Luna.

movie_title: Rudolph and Frosty: Christmas in July

critics_consensus: Though undeniably sentimental and predictable, Rudy succeeds with an uplifting spirit and determination.
The Rugrats franchise has gone from fresh to formulaic.
When the Rugrats go to Paris, the result is Nickelodeon-style fun. The plot is effectively character-driven, and features catchy songs and great celebrity voice-acting.
Charming characters; loads of fun for kids and adults.
A tiresome movie about unsympathetic college kids engaging in self-destructive behaviors.
The script is unconvincing and the courtroom action is unegaging.
Rumble Fish frustrates even as it intrigues, but director Francis Ford Coppola's strong visual style helps compensate for a certain narrative stasis.
An entertaining Jackie Chan stunt-fest in which the impressive action sequences overcome the low production value and by-the-numbers plot.
This riff on The Graduate has a solid cast, but is too lightweight to fully register.
More fun than a barrel of Jean-Paul Sartre, pic's energy riffs on an engaging love story and really human performances while offering a series of what-ifs and a blood-stirring soundtrack.
Cliche story with lack of chemistry between Richard Gere and Julia Roberts.
An implausible but entertaining legal thriller.
It has an impressive cast and an intriguing premise, but Runner Runner wastes them on a bland, haphazardly assembled thriller with very little payoff.

movie_title: Runnin' Down a Dream: Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers

critics_consensus: The Running Man is winking sci-fi satire with ridiculous clothes and workmanlike direction.
Despite a few great performances, the film lacks the sincerity and emotional edge of Burroughs' well-loved memoir.
A sleek, slick, well-oiled machine, Rush is a finely crafted sports drama with exhilarating race sequences and strong performances from Chris Hemsworth and Daniel BrÃ¼hl.
A kick-ass addition to the cop-buddy film genre.
Rush Hour 2 doesn't feel as fresh or funny as the first, and the stunts lack some of the intricacy normally seen in Chan's films.
Rush Hour 3 is a tired rehash of the earlier films, and a change of scenery can't hide a lack of new ideas.
This cult favorite is a quirky coming of age story, with fine, off-kilter performances from Jason Schwartzman and Bill Murray.

movie_title: Russell Mulcahy's Tale of the Mummy

critics_consensus: Like its predecessor L'Auberge Espagnole, Russian Dolls is charmingly breezy and light.

movie_title: The Russians Are Coming, the Russians Are Coming

critics_consensus: It's sometimes crude and tasteless, but Ruthless People wrings acid-soaked laughs out of its dark premise and gleefully misanthropic characters.
An unoriginal and only occasionally funny family road-trip movie, RV is a mediocre effort that not even the charisma of Robin Williams can save.

movie_title: S. Darko: A Donnie Darko Tale

critics_consensus: It's as scattershot as its predecessor, but V/H/S/2 rounds up enough horror filmmaking talent to deliver a satisfyingly nasty -- albeit uneven -- dose of gore.
Sabotage boasts one of Arnold Schwarzenegger's finer post-political performances, but it's wasted in a movie driven by grueling violence that punishes seemingly without purpose.
Engrossing and enraging, Sacco and Vanzetti exhumes an infamous judicial failure with a painful amount of modern relevance.

movie_title: The Saddest Music in the World
critics_consensus: Guy Maddin perfectly recreates the look and feel of a 1930s in this bizarre picture.
While hard-hitting and violently inventive, Safe ultimately proves too formulaic to set itself apart from the action thriller pack -- including some of its star's better films.
Schmaltzy, predictable, and melodramatic, Safe Haven also suffers from a ludicrous plot twist, making for a particularly ignominious Nicholas Sparks adaptation.
Safe House stars Washington and Reynolds are let down by a thin script and choppily edited action sequences.
Safety Not Guaranteed's ostensibly modest ambitions are outmatched by the movie's strong performances, beguiling charm, and heartfelt story.

movie_title: The Sailor Who Fell From Grace With the Sea

critics_consensus: The Saint is watchable thanks to Kilmer and Shue, but the muddled screenplay stretches credulity.

movie_title: Saint Misbehavin': The Wavy Gravy Movie

critics_consensus: Writer-director Hue Rhodes' debut is a poorly-paced, forgettable comedy that wastes the quirky talents of stars Steve Buscemi and Sarah Silverman.
While it draws heavily on war movie conventions, Saints and Soldiers has strong performances and a compelling central plot.
Director Tobe Hooper and a devilishly charismatic James Mason elevate this television adaptation of the Stephen King novel, injecting the vampiric tradition with fresh blood and lingering scares.
Quirky and a little reserved, Salmon Fishing in the Yemen is nonetheless a charming little romantic drama sold by some strong central performances.
A slick Tarantino-inspired movie that is not for everyone.
One of Disney's lesser-known animated films, Saludos Amigos may be slight stuff, but it's still a spirited, energetic travelogue.
Despite its somewhat disjointed narrative, Oliver Stone's Salvador is a vivid and powerful political drama that sets an early tone for the director's similarly provocative future projects.
Stylish and inventive, Salvo parcels out the thrills that genre fans seek while anchoring its story with satisfying, slow-building tension.
It's a tad heavy-handed in its message, but Samsara's overwhelmingly beautiful visuals more than compensate for any narrative flaws.
Sanctum is beautifully photographed, and it makes better use of 3-D technology than most, but that doesn't make up for its ham-handed script and lifeless cast.
It may be shamelessly derivative and overly nostalgic, but The Sandlot is nevertheless a genuinely sweet and funny coming-of-age adventure.
This suspenseful Mexican drama portrays the immigrant experience with grit and poignancy.
Technically impressive and superbly acted, Sanjuro is a funny, action-packed samurai adventure featuring outstanding cinematography and a charismatic performance from Toshiro Mifune.
Ho, ho, oh no.

movie_title: Santa Claus Is Comin' to Town
critics_consensus: Arriving with light-hearted cheeriness and the best musical numbers, Santa Claus Is Comin To Town is a magical story told by charming wood-figure animation.

movie_title: The Santa Clause 3: The Escape Clause
critics_consensus: Playing Jack Frost as an evil cross between Liza Minnelli and Liberace, Martin Short is a welcome presence, but this tired series continues drawing from its bag of bland gags and dumb slapstick.

Those unfamiliar with Alejandro Jodorowsky's style may find it overwhelming, but Santa Sangre is a provocative psychedelic journey featuring the director's signature touches of violence, vulgarity, and an oddly personal moral center.
If Saraband appears to be a minor entry in Ingmar Bergman's filmography, it's still an accomplished piece of work from one of cinema's greatest masters.

movie_title: Sarah Landon and the Paranormal Hour

critics_consensus: Silverman's brand of humor is dirty, offensive, and, judging from this film, very, very funny.
Sarah's Key is an absorbing, impeccably-acted Holocaust drama with minor plot issues.
Boasting a smart, poignant story, a classic soundtrack, and a starmaking performance from John Travolta, Saturday Night Fever ranks among the finest dramas of the 1970s.
Though visually compelling, the lamentable characters in Savage Grace make for difficult viewing.

Thanks to a tender, funny script from director Tamara Jenkins, and fine performances from Philip Seymour Hoffman and Laura Linney, this film delivers a nuanced, beautifully three-dimensional look at the struggles and comforts of family bonds.
It's undeniably messy, but Savages finds Oliver Stone returning to dark, fearlessly lurid form.
This teen romance flick feels like a predictable rehashing of other movies.
A satirical teen comedy that, unfortunately, pulls its punches.
The aggressively wholesome Saving Shiloh has honorable intentions, but this simple story of a boy and his dog is overwhelmed by its heavy-handed approach.
A charming tale of a love affair that overcomes cultural taboos.
Aggressively likable and sentimental to a fault, Saving Mr. Banks pays tribute to the Disney legacy with excellent performances and sweet, high-spirited charm.
Anchored by another winning performance from Tom Hanks, Steven Spielberg's unflinchingly realistic war film virtually redefines the genre.
Dragged down by a plot lacking any sense of logic and obnoxious, unsympathetic characters, this comedy is more crude and mean-spirited than funny.
Saw ensnares audiences with a deceptively clever plot and a myriad of memorable, nasty set pieces, but its lofty ambitions are undercut by a nihilistic streak that feels more mean than profound.
Sloppily filmed, poorly acted, and illogically plotted, Saw 3D leaves viewers trapped in the most lackluster installment of the series.
Saw III does little beyond repeating its predecessor's tropes on a gorier level.
Saw IV is more disturbing than compelling, with material already seen in the prior installments.
It won't earn the franchise many new fans, but Saw VI is a surprising step up for what has become an intricately grisly annual tradition.
Saw II is likely to please the gore-happy fans of the original, though it may be too gruesome for those not familiar with first film's premise.
If its plot were as interesting as its torture devices, or its violence less painful than its performances, perhaps Saw V might not feel like it was running on fumes.
One of the definitive Generation X movies, Say Anything is equally funny and heartfelt -- and it established John Cusack as an icon for left-of-center types everywhere.
Those that haven't tired from Farrelly brothers' brand of comedy may still find some laughs here. Otherwise, the slow pacing and unimaginative shock gags will start to wear on the viewer.
A faithful adaptation of Philip K. Dick's novel, A Scanner Darkly takes the viewer on a visual and mind-blowing journey into the author's conception of a drug-addled and politically unstable world.

Director Brian De Palma and star Al Pacino take it to the limit in this stylized, ultra-violent and eminently quotable gangster epic that walks a thin white line between moral drama and celebratory excess.
Critics say Scary Movie overloads on crudity and grossness to get its laughs.
Instead of being funny, this gross-out sequel plays like a sloppy, rushed-out product.
Though an improvement over the second Scary Movie, the laughs are still inconsistent.
Sure to inspire a few chuckles, but not enough to compensate for the recycled material from its predecessors.
Juvenile even by Scary Movie standards, this fifth installment offers stale pop culture gags that generate few laughs.
Scatter My Ashes At Bergdorf's is a fun documentary which ultimately doubles as an infomercial for the Manhattan store.

movie_title: Scenes from a Marriage (Scener ur ett Ã¤ktenskap)

critics_consensus: Schindler's List blends the abject horror of the Holocaust with Steven Spielberg's signature tender humanism to create the director's dramatic masterpiece.
School Daze is undeniably messy, but thought-provoking themes, strong performances, and Spike Lee's ingratiating energy help tie it all together.
School for Scoundrels squanders its talented cast with a formulaic, unfocused attempt at a romantic comedy that's neither romantic nor funny.
Black's exuberant, gleeful performance turns School of Rock into a hilarious, rocking good time.
Schultze Gets the Blues is a sweet and charming dark comedy.
Only the very young will get the most out of this silly trifle.
Rehashing old plot lines and characters, Scoop is a tiresome dipper and another disappointing addition to Woody Allen's repertoire.
Action adventure doesn't get much cheesier than The Scorpion King.
Scott Walker: 30 Century Man is a stylish portrait of an influential artist that will fascinate fans and neophytes alike.
Its script may not be as dazzling as its eye-popping visuals, but Scott Pilgrim vs. the World is fast, funny, and inventive.
Whether you know anything about turntablism or not, Scratch makes for fun and informative viewing.
The franchise is showing its age, but Scream 4 is undeniably an improvement over its predecessor, with just enough meta humor and clever kills.
As with the first film, Scream 2 is a gleeful takedown of scary movie conventions that manages to poke fun at terrible horror sequels without falling victim to the same fate.
Despite some surprising twists, Scream 3 sees the franchise falling back on the same old horror formulas and cliches it once hacked and slashed with postmodern abandon.
Scrooged gets by with Bill Murray and a dash of holiday spirit, although it's hampered by a markedly conflicted tone and an undercurrent of mean-spiritedness.

movie_title: The Sea Inside (Mar Adentro) (The Sea Within)
critics_consensus: Held aloft by a transfixing performance from Javier Bardem as a terminally ill man who chooses to die, The Sea Inside transcends its melodramatic story with tenderness and grace.
Moody and steadily alluring, Sea of Love benefits immeasurably from the window-fogging chemistry between Ellen Barkin and Al Pacino.
A life-affirming, if saccharine, epic treatment of a spirit-lifting figure in sports history.
Though uneven in spots, this delightful comedy will, nevertheless, put a smile on your face.
The Searchers is an epic John Wayne Western that introduces dark ambivalence to the genre that remains fashionable today.
As sensitive as the young man at its center, Searching for Bobby Fischer uses a prodigy's struggle to find personal balance as the background for a powerfully moving drama.
A fascinating portrait of a forgotten musical pioneer, Searching for Sugar Man is by turns informative and mysterious.
A wholesome but schmaltzy movie.
Featuring dazzling, disorienting cinematography from the great James Wong Howe and a strong lead performance by Rock Hudson, Seconds is a compellingly paranoid take on the legend of Faust.
A moderately funny comedy that will reward patient viewers.

movie_title: The Secret in Their Eyes (El Secreto de Sus Ojos)
critics_consensus: Unpredictable and rich with symbolism, this Argentinian murder mystery lives up to its Oscar with an engrossing plot, Juan Jose Campanella's assured direction, and mesmerizing performances from its cast.
The Secret Life of Bees has moments of charm, but is largely too maudlin and sticky-sweet.
Watching grass grow would likely be more entertaining than this dull, slight feature about a sod salesman.
Despite impressive production values, this is staid, plodding and unimpressive fantasy-fare, with poor performances struggling with an underdeveloped script.
The Secret of NIMH is a dark, well-told tale that respects its young audience enough to not tone down its subject matter.
Pretentious and trashy.
Depp is quirkily entertaining, but the movie runs out of steam by the end.
Rousing, heartwarming, and squarely traditional, Secretariat offers exactly what you'd expect from an inspirational Disney drama -- no more, and no less.
Maggie Gyllenhaal impresses in this romantic comedy with a kinky twist.

Despite utilizing a visual whirlwind of cinematic tricks, this socio-political thriller falls short of fulfilling its heavier goals but provides a powerful peek into the class issues of modern Venezuela.

movie_title: See No Evil, Hear No Evil
critics_consensus: A film whose title offers words to live by as well as a warning, See No Evil, Hear No Evil proves that even a brilliant comedy duo can team up for an unfunny dud.
See Spot Run has all the elements chidren enjoy in a movie: a lovable dog, bad things happening to stupid adults, and lots of dog poop. For adults, it's either hit-or-miss.
Give Seed of Chucky credit for embracing the increasing absurdity of the franchise -- even if the end results really aren't all that funny or entertaining.

movie_title: The Seeker: The Dark Is Rising
critics_consensus: The magic of the book is lost in translation with The Seeker, due to its clumsy plot and lack of heart.

movie_title: Seeking a Friend for the End of the World
critics_consensus: Tender, charming, and well-acted, Seeking a Friend for the End of the World is unfortunately hamstrung by jarring tonal shifts and a disappointing final act.
Self-Medicated features some nice performances, but is too sentimental and unfocused to be a truly compelling film.

Fueled by a gripping performance from David Oyelowo, Selma draws inspiration and dramatic power from the life and death of Martin Luther King, Jr. -- but doesn't ignore how far we remain from the ideals his work embodied.
Semi-Pro is an intermittently funny, half-hearted attempt at sports satire, and one of Will Ferrell's weaker cinematic efforts.
Even for filmgoers who aren't racing fans, Senna offers heart-pounding thrills -- and heartbreaking emotion.
The Sentinel starts off well enough but quickly wears thin with too many plot holes and conventional action sequences.
A compelling and oddly haunting combination of brutal and beautiful imagery.
Though the characters in this tasteful adult drama keep a stiff upper lip, the moral dilemmas are nuanced and the emotional pain feels real.
With its jarring editing, dull love story, and silly dialogue, September Dawn turns a horrific historical event into a banal movie.
This doc about the making of Vogue's biggest issue and its frosty editor-in-chief is fascinating eye candy and light-on-its-feet fun.
A brutal, slow-moving drama that unfolds among some great-looking scenery.
Seraphine is a well-crafted French film that effectively captures one woman's experience with art, religion, and mental illness, and features a brilliant performance from Yolande Moreau.
This darkly comic family drama finds ways of being viscerally graphic and intellectually stimulating at the same time.
Light and charming, Serendipity could benefit from less contrivances.
Snappy dialogue and goofy characters make this Wild Wild West soap opera in space fun and adventurous.
Serious Moonlight jumbles a comic tone with tragic circumstances and the result is confused performances from its stars.
Serpico is an engrossing, immediate depiction of 1973 New York and includes a turn by a young Pacino that's both ferocious and career changing.
A romantic comedy that's neither funny nor particularly romantic, Serving Sara is a forgettable time waster.

movie_title: Sesame Street Presents: Follow That Bird

critics_consensus: It may not boast an original plot, but Set It Off is a satisfying, socially conscious heist film thanks largely to fine performances from its leads.
Buoyed by crowd-pleasing tunes and charming performances, Seven Brides for Seven Brothers makes a successful transition from Broadway to screen that's sure to please the whole family.
Grim and morose, Seven Pounds is also undone by an illogical plot.
Seven Psychopaths delivers sly cinematic commentary while serving up a heaping helping of sharp dialogue and gleeful violence.

Arguably Akira Kurosawa's masterpiece, The Seven Samurai is an epic adventure classic with an engrossing story, memorable characters, and stunning action sequences that make it one of the most influential films ever made.
Narratively bold and visually striking, The Seventh Seal brought Ingmar Bergman to the world stage -- and remains every bit as compelling today.
A twisted and bloody spoof on office life, Severance nicely balances comedy and nasty horror.

movie_title: Severed Ways: The Norse Discovery of America

critics_consensus: Sex & Drugs & Rock & Roll pays appropriately uninhibited tribute to a pioneering artist -- and proves Andy Serkis can be every bit as compelling in a non-motion-capture role.
Sex and Death 101 aspires to be a clever sex comedy, but has little life behind the sex or the death.
Beneath the gratuitous nudity lies a complex and visually striking movie.
Sex and the City loses steam in the transition to the big screen, but will still thrill fans of the show.
Straining under a thin plot stretched to its limit by a bloated running time, Sex and the City 2 adds an unfortunate coda to the long-running HBO series.
Sex Drive has some hilarious moments and is well made for a raunchy teen film, but will appeal to few beyond that demographic.

In his feature directorial debut, Steven Soderbergh demonstrates a mastery of his craft well beyond his years, pulling together an outstanding cast and an intelligent script for a nuanced, mature film about neurosis and human sexuality.
With neither the conviction to embrace its smutty premise nor enough laughs to function as a worthwhile rom-com, the flaccid Sex Tape suffers from cinematic impotence.
Sexy Beast rises above other movies in the British gangster genre due to its performances -- particularly an electrifying one by Ben Kingsley -- and the script's attention to character development.

movie_title: Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band
critics_consensus: I thought you might like to know that the Beatles (aka the act you've known for all these years) are ill-served by this kitschy, aggressively whimsical fantasy film that's most certainly not a thrill.
A tense, thought-provoking thriller, Shadow Dancer is bolstered by sensitive direction from James Marsh and a terrific performance from Andrea Riseborough.
Shadow of the Vampire is frightening, compelling, and funny, and features an excellent performance by Willem Dafoe.
With random characters and a preposterous plot, this bizarre thriller might leave you with your mouth hanging open in disbelief.
Thanks to brilliant performances from Debra Winger and especially Anthony Hopkins, Shadowlands is a deeply moving portrait of British scholar C.S. Lewis's romance with American poet Joy Gresham.

movie_title: Shadows of Forgotten Ancestors (Tini zabutykh predkiv)

critics_consensus: This Disney retread has neither inspiration nor originality, but may please moviegoers under the age of ten.
Shakes the Clown has a handful of memorable moments, but they're scattered in a movie whose best ideas were left undeveloped on their way to the screen.
Shakespeare Behind Bars is a moving testament to the power -- and universality -- of art.
Endlessly witty, visually rapturous, and sweetly romantic, Shakespeare in Love is a delightful romantic comedy that succeeds on nearly every level.
The cast is warmly appealing, but with the loss of cultural context and addition of big-name celebrities, this American version loses the nuances of the original.

movie_title: Un Baiser s'il vous plaÃ®t (Shall We Kiss?)
critics_consensus: Shall We Kiss? combines just enough romance and laughs to make for a charming French take on Woody Allen comedies.
While surprisingly sweeter and warm-hearted than previous Farrelly outings, Shallow Hal is also less funny and more bland.
Boasting stellar performances by Michael Fassbender and Carey Mulligan, Shame is a powerful plunge into the mania of addiction affliction.
Shampoo trains a darkly comic lens on post-Nixon America, aiming at -- and often hitting -- an array of timely targets.
A silly, anachronistic mess, but the pairing of Chan and Wilson makes the movie fun.

Although the plot is really nothing to brag about, Jackie Chan and Owen Wilson work well together. The cinematography looks great, and Jackie delivers a hilarious performance. This is an old-fashioned crowd-pleaser.

movie_title: Shanghai Triad (Yao a yao yao dao waipo qiao)
critics_consensus: Well-acted and beautifully filmed, Shanghai Triad deftly depicts a young man's coming of age against the backdrop of mob violence and its punishing legacy.
The plot is utterly ridiculous, and the soccer in the movie is unlike any ever played anywhere on Earth, but watching Shaolin Soccer, you will probably find it impossible to care.
A joyless excursion into the water that doesn't even produce good gore or nudity thanks to the neutered PG-13 rating.
Derivative and full of pop culture in-jokes.
Proudly, shamelessly, and gloriously brainless, Sharknado redefines "so bad it's good" for a new generation.
The schlock factor for Sharknado 2: The Second One is not as entertaining as its predecessor's, though fans of the brand will likely enjoy it.
In addition to its breathtaking underwater photography, Sharkwater has a convincing, impassioned argument of how the plight of sharks affects everyone.
A compelling look at Stephen Glass' fall from grace.
Shaun of the Dead cleverly balances scares and witty satire, making for a bloody good zombie movie with loads of wit.
The Shawshank Redemption is an uplifting, deeply satisfying prison drama with sensitive direction and fine performances.
She Done Him Wrong, but putting Cary Grant and Mae West together is pretty much nothing but right.
She Hate Me can't decide if it wants to be a commentary on corporate greed or a sex farce.
The Sheltering Sky puts its talented stars at odds with a misguided and largely unsatisfying adaptation of potentially unfilmable source material.

Guy Ritchie's directorial style might not be quite the best fit for an update on the legendary detective, but Sherlock Holmes benefits from the elementary appeal of a strong performance by Robert Downey, Jr.

movie_title: Sherlock Holmes: A Game of Shadows
critics_consensus: Sherlock Holmes: A Game of Shadows is a good yarn thanks to its well-matched leading men but overall stumbles duplicating the well-oiled thrills of the original.

movie_title: Sherlock Holmes and the Woman in Green

critics_consensus: Maggie Gyllenhaal delivers riveting performance as a recovering drug addict in a depressing and not entirely believable movie.
Despite its charming young leads, She's All That can't overcome its predictable, inconsistently funny script.
With She's Gotta Have It, Spike Lee delivered his bracing first shot across Hollywood's bow -- and set the template for the groundbreaking act to follow.
She's Out of My League has moments of humor and insight, but it's bogged down by excessive vulgarity and cartoonishness.
Shakespeare's wit gets lost in translation with She's the Man's broad slapstick, predictable jokes, and unconvincing plotline.

movie_title: She-Wolf of London (The Curse of the Allenbys)

critics_consensus: Featuring a strong performance from Geoffrey Rush, Shine succeeds in telling a compelling, inspirational story without resorting to cheap sentimentality.
It may offer little new for fans, but Martin Scorsese's document of the Rolling Stones' electrifying live show should provide satisfaction to audiences.
Though it deviates from Stephen King's novel, Stanley Kubrick's The Shining is a chilling, often baroque journey into madness -- exemplified by an unforgettable turn from Jack Nicholson

movie_title: San suk si gin (The Shinjuku Incident)

critics_consensus: Though solidly made and acted, The Shipping News is rather heavy-handed and dull, especially given the nature of its protagonist.

movie_title: Shock to the System: A Donald Strachey Mystery

critics_consensus: With an intriguing enough premise and horror legend Wes Craven on writer-director duty, the real Shocker here is just how lame the end results turned out to be.

movie_title: Sholem Aleichem: Laughing in the Darkness

critics_consensus: As preposterous and over-the-top as Shoot 'Em Up may be, its humor and non-stop action make for a very enjoyable film.

movie_title: Shoot the Piano Player (Tirez sur le pianiste)

critics_consensus: With an implausible story and numerous plot holes, Shooter fails to distinguish itself from other mindless action-thrillers.
Deftly directed by Ernst Lubitsch from a smart, funny script by Samson Raphaelson, The Shop Around the Corner is a romantic comedy in the finest sense of the term.
Shopgirl is precariously slight, but it has some intriguing moments, and Danes is luminous.

movie_title: Short Cut to Nirvana: Kumbh Mela
critics_consensus: Short on depth but amazingly insightful, this glimpse into one of the world's largest spritual gatherings is worth viewing for the eye-opening experience alone.
Short Term 12 is an emphatic, revealing drama that pulls audiences into the perspective of neglected youths.

movie_title: Shorts: The Adventures of the Wishing Rock
critics_consensus: Shorts has imagination and energy, but most viewers beyond elementary school will likely tire of the kiddie humor and sensory overload.
Thanks to a talented cast and its uncommon depth, Nichols' debut manages to rise above its overly familiar plot.
Vile, contemptible, garish, and misogynistic -- and that might just be exactly Showgirls' point.

movie_title: Showrunners: The Art of Running a TV Show

critics_consensus: While simultaneously embracing and subverting fairy tales, the irreverent Shrek also manages to tweak Disney's nose, provide a moral message to children, and offer viewers a funny, fast-paced ride.
It may not be as fresh as the original, but topical humor and colorful secondary characters make Shrek 2 a winner in its own right.
Shrek the Third has pop culture potshots galore, but at the expense of the heart, charm, and wit that made the first two Shreks classics.
While not without its moments, Shrek Forever After too often feels like a rote rehashing of the franchise's earlier entries.

movie_title: Shriek If You Know What I Did Last Friday the 13th
Shut Up and Play the Hits
Sick: The Life and Death of Bob Flanagan, Supermasochist

critics_consensus: Driven by Michael Moore's sincere humanism, Sicko is a devastating, convincing, and very entertaining documentary about the state of America's health care.
Siddharth takes an achingly compassionate and deeply unsettling look at all-too-common circumstances in modern-day India.
A smart, clever thriller with plenty of disquieting twists, Side Effects is yet another assured effort from director Steven Soderbergh.
Charming, thoughtful, and often funny, Sideways is a decidedly mature road trip comedy full of excellent performances.
Director Ben Wheatley and writer-stars Alice Lowe and Steve Oram deliver a wicked road trip movie that successfully walks the line between dark comedy and horror.
The Signal is gruesome, funny, and has big thoughts about society, but those disparate elements fail to come together convincingly.
With Signs, Shyamalan proves once again an expert at building suspense and giving audiences the chills.
Director Jonathan Demme's smart, taut thriller teeters on the edge between psychological study and all-out horror, and benefits greatly from stellar performances by Anthony Hopkins and Jodie Foster.
Silent Hill is visually impressive, but as with many video game adaptations, it's plagued by inane dialogue, a muddled plot, and an overlong runtime.
Mediocre effort even by the standards of video game adaptations, Silent Hill: Revelation 3D features weak characters and an incomprehensible plot with a shortage of scares.
Silent House is more technically proficient and ambitious than most fright-fests, but it also suffers from a disappointing payoff.
Silent Light demands patience -- and rewards willing viewers with a compassionate and beautifully filmed look at the human condition.
Heavy-handed and often dull.
Silver Linings Playbook walks a tricky thematic tightrope, but David O. Russell's sensitive direction and some sharp work from a talented cast gives it true balance.
Boasting rich detail and well-told story, Silverado is a rare example of an '80s Hollywood Western done right.
Overly mushy; tries too hard to pull at the heart-strings.
Though its bleak themes may be off-putting for some, Simon Killer is an engrossing, effective character study of a brutal, enigmatic figure.
The satire in S1m0ne lacks bite, and the plot isn't believable enough to feel relevant.
Critics say Simpatico's lengthy plot is too unfocused; the movie becomes confusing and tedious to watch.
A riveting crime thriller full of emotional tension.
Simply Irresistible is simply not.

The Simpsons Movie contains the hearty laughs, biting satire, and honest portrayal of an American family that makes the show so popular. And it boasts slicker animation and polished writing that hearkens back to the show's glory days.
Visually groundbreaking and terrifically violent, Sin City brings the dark world of Frank Miller's graphic novel to vivid life.

movie_title: Sin noticias de Dios (Don't Tempt Me)
critics_consensus: More Hellish than it is Heavenly, AgustÃ­n DÃ­az Yanes' black comedy about the Earthly duel between two angels doesn't have enough genuine laughs to support its far-fetched premise.

movie_title: Sinbad and the Eye of the Tiger
Sinbad: Legend of the Seven Seas
critics_consensus: Competent, but not magical.
Sing Your Song takes an absorbing -- if decidedly non-critical -- look at an incredible show business career and admirable public life.
Clever, incisive, and funny, Singin' in the Rain is a masterpiece of the classical Hollywood musical.
Delightful performance from Robert Downey Jr. can't save The Singing Detective's transition from TV to the big screen.
Single White Female benefits from a pair of outstanding leads, neither of whom are well served by a storyline that wavers between thrillingly tense and utterly ridiculous.
Its plot hinges on typically implausible horror-movie behavior and recycles countless genre cliches, but Sinister delivers a surprising number of fresh, diabolical twists.
A powerful reflection on a pivotal era, from a viewpoint seldom visited, this documentary hits home, especially with its relevance to current events.
Looking for a sweet musical comedy about a witness to a crime hiding out from killers in a convent? There's nun better than Sister Act.

movie_title: Sister Act 2: Back in the Habit
The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants
critics_consensus: This adaptation of a beloved novel charms with its heartwarming tale of friendship and young adulthood; realistic portrayals of the lives of teenage girls lend the comedy-drama sincerity, and may capture hearts outside the female-centric demographic.

movie_title: The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants 2
critics_consensus: The workable chemistry among the four leads combined with the enriching message make for a winning Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants 2.
Clever yet clearly indebted to the masters of the genre, Sisters offers an early glimpse of De Palma at his stylishly crafty peak.
A tour de force for filmmaker Nina Paley, Sita Sings the Blues gives the Ramayana its animated due with a visually vibrant, dazzlingly imaginative triumph.
A generally enjoyable, if completely forgettable piece of Hollywood fluff.
Though it betrays its theatrical roots, Six Degrees of Separation largely succeeds thanks to astute direction and fine performances -- particularly from an against-type Will Smith.

movie_title: Six Sex Scenes and a Murder

critics_consensus: Significantly more mature than the teen raunch comedies that defined the era, Sixteen Candles is shot with compassion and clear respect for his characters and their hang-ups.
This offering from Arnold Schwarzenegger contains an intriguing, disturbing premise, but the film's execution is too routine and formulaic to make good use of it.
M Night Shayamalan's The Sixth Sense is a twisty ghost story with all the style of a classical Hollywood picture, but all the chills of a modern horror flick.
This affectionate, casually framed portrait of the acclaimed architect reveals him to be an engaging, likeable subject.
Though Skills Like This has little to distinguish, director Monty Miranda shows flashes of wit and talent.
Though at times melodramatic, Skins' harsh depiction of life on the reservation is an eye-opener.
Skinwalkers is an atrociously-acted project whose unoriginal and ineptly-staged action sequences remind viewers of far better werewolf and action movies.
The Skulls is full of nonsense and empty of good script and plot.

movie_title: Sky Captain and the World of Tomorrow
critics_consensus: Sky Captain and the World of Tomorrow is slim on plot and characterization, but the visuals more than make up for it.
Sam Mendes brings Bond surging back with a smart, sexy, riveting action thriller that qualifies as one of the best 007 films to date.
A middling sci-fi entry, Skyline offers proof that solid special effects alone cannot overcome a flat storyline filled with uninspired dialogue.
Slacker rests its shiftless thumb on the pulse of a generation with fresh filmmaking that captures the tenor of its time while establishing a benchmark for 1990s indie cinema.
Another teen comedy with little on its mind but moving to the next gross-out gag, Slackers strains for laughs and features grating characters.
Potty humor and juvenile antics keep this workplace comedy from being particularly funny or memorable.
Raunchy, violent, and very funny, Slap Shot is ultimately set apart by a wonderful comic performance by Paul Newman.
A bleak but original indie, The Slaughter Rule benefits from outstanding performances by Ryan Gosling and David Morse.
Sleep Dealer's depth and energy are almost enough to overcome a shaky screenplay and pedestrian acting.
This poetic and tender portrait of a Welsh village is a slow moving yet elegantly accomplished British documentary.
The strong lead performance, clever plot turns, and the unsettling ending makes Sleep Tight worth stalking.
Sleepaway Camp is a standard teen slasher elevated by occasional moments of John Waters-esque weirdness and a twisted ending.
Sleeping Beauty's provocative premise and luminous art design is hampered by a clinical, remote presentation, delivering boredom and shock in equal measure.
A game Julia Roberts gives it her all, but Sleeping with the Enemy is one stalker thriller that's unlikely to inspire many obsessions of its own.
'Tween girls will enjoy this sugar coated fluff, but others will find Sleepover a snooze.
Laugh-out-loud funny and endearingly messy, Sleepwalk with Me overcomes its tonal inconsistencies to deliver a sweetly melancholic, amiably reassuring indie crowd-pleaser.
Despite some sharp performances, Sleepwalking suffers from a grimness of tone and sluggish pacing.
Sleepy Hollow entertains with its stunning visuals and creepy atmosphere.
Sleuth is so obvious and coarse, rather than suspenseful and action-packed, that it does nothing to improve on the original version
Despite the gimmicky feel of the split narratives, the movie is watch-able due to the winning performances by the cast.
You will see what's coming, but the masterful performances, especially Thornton's, will leave you riveted.
A slimy, B-movie homage oozing with affection for low-budget horror films, Slither is creepy and funny -- if you've got the stomach for it.
Sliver is an absurd erotic thriller with technobabble and posits prime Sharon Stone as a professional book nerd.
With wooden acting and hammy, overheated dialogue, Slow Burn isn't so much a noir as it is a mediocre parody of one.
Visually dazzling and emotionally resonant, Slumdog Millionaire is a film that's both entertaining and powerful.
Warm, real, and hilarious.
Small Soldiers has plenty of visual razzle-dazzle, but the rote story proves disappointingly deficient in director Joe Dante's trademark anarchic spirit.
Woody Allen rises from his recent slump with Small Time Crooks. A simple, funny movie, Crooks proves Allen still has the touch that made his name synonymous with off-beat comedy.
Smashed resists the temptation to play up its serious subject matter for high theatrics, opting instead to let its gentle tone and Mary Elizabeth Winstead's marvelous performance carry the day.
Although many of the jokes have been done before, Anna Faris's bright performance and Gregg Araki's sharp direction make Smiley Face more than your average stoner comedy.
Smoke Signals tells a familiar story from an underrepresented point of view, proving that a fresh perspective can help subvert long-established expectations.
Not much in the head but plenty beneath the hood, Smokey and the Bandit is infectious fun with plenty of car wrecks to keep your eyes glued.
A violent mess of a movie, Smokin' Aces has some Quentin Tarantino's style but not much of his wit or humor.
Snabba Cash (Easy Money) cuts a cube of Nordic noir whose taut storytelling packs an extra dose of hard-hitting heft.
Snake Eyes has a number of ingredients that promise a trashy fun time; unfortunately, they're lost in an energetic and stylish thriller with a frustratingly hollow core.
Snakes on a Plane lives up to its title, featuring snakes on a plane. It isn't perfect, but then again, it doesn't need to be.
Warm, funny, and populated by easily relatable characters, The Snapper is a compulsively watchable slice-of-life dramedy with much to recommend.
Though perhaps a case of style over substance, Guy Ritchie's second crime caper is full of snappy dialogue, dark comedy, and interesting characters.
There isn't much to Sneakers plot and that's more than made up for with the film's breezy panache and hi-tech lingo.
Though it features one of Dwayne Johnson's more thoughtful performances, the presentation of Snitch's underlying message is muddled by lackluster storytelling and some tonal inconsistencies.
With fine acting and considerable emotional depth, Snow Angels aptly captures the highs, and especially the lows of human relationships.
Weak assembly of characters and story lines made this movie forgettable and silly.
A mediocre live-action children's movie, Snow Dogs is filled with cliched dialogue, tiresome pratfalls, and stale fish-out-of-water jokes.
Though Snow Falling on Cedars is beautiful to look at, critics say the story becomes dull and tedious to sit through.

movie_title: Snow Flower And The Secret Fan
Snow White: A Tale of Terror

critics_consensus: While it offers an appropriately dark take on the fairy tale that inspired it, Snow White and the Huntsman is undone by uneven acting, problematic pacing, and a confused script.
Snowpiercer offers an audaciously ambitious action spectacular for filmgoers numb to effects-driven blockbusters.
This HK actioner oozes with style.
Intelligent and even-handed, ...So Goes the Nation takes an impressively comprehensive look behind the scenes of the modern American election process.

movie_title: So I Married an Axe Murderer
critics_consensus: So I Married an Axe Murderer is a unique rom-com with moments of heart and hilarity -- even if they're all too scattered to cohere into a consistent whole.
A poignant documentary about terminal illness that's as moving as it is honest.
Soapdish may not be as addictive as the serialized dramas it's spoofing, but a talented cast helps make this affectionate sendup feel fresh.
A sustained blast of unbridled vitriol from writer-director Blake Edwards, S.O.B. is one of the blackest -- and most consistently funny -- Hollywood satires ever put to film.
Slow-moving, cerebral, and ambiguous, Solaris is not a movie for everyone, but it offers intriguing issues to ponder.
Built around a singularly unpleasant main character, Solitary Man needed a flawless central performance to succeed -- and Michael Douglas delivers.
Featuring hammy performances and bland characters, Solo is an all too straightforward actioner that's both predictable and instantly forgettable.
Though it features strong performances by its lead players, a lack of narrative focus prevents The Soloist from hitting its mark.
Solomon Kane's formulaic and bleak narrative is overcome by an entertaining, straightforward adherence to its genre, exciting gore, and a gratifying lead performance by James Purefoy.

movie_title: Some Days Are Better Than Others

critics_consensus: Some Kind of Wonderful is above-average '80s teen fare for people who need as much John Hughes in their lives as possible.
Some Like It Hot: A spry, quick-witted farce that never drags.
Somebody Up There Likes Me proves there's still life left in the charmingly offbeat indie dramedy, largely thanks to the efforts of its immensely likable cast.

movie_title: Someday This Pain Will Be Useful to You

critics_consensus: Its plot is sometimes hard to swallow, but some fine acting and director Ridley Scott's stylish visual flair make Someone to Watch Over Me an engaging police thriller.
Shane Meadows hits the spot with this short but sweet slice of good natured comedy, surprisingly, as it's essentially an extended black & white advert for a train station.
A poignant coming-of-age tale marked by a breakout lead performance from Abbie Cornish and a successful directorial debut from Cate Shortland.
In spite of solid performances from Kate Hudson and John Krasinski, Something Borrowed is an unpleasant misfire that lives down to its title.

movie_title: Something from Nothing: The Art of Rap

critics_consensus: Insightful, solidly acted, and smartly filmed, Something in the Air skillfully captures the idealism of youth without falling back on cheap nostalgia.
Something New tackles serious questions about race and interracial relationships with genuine appeal and an alluring romance that develops as naturally as the plot.
Small-town gossip and a battle of the sexes should really add up to more than Something to Talk About, especially with this much talent before the camera.
Boasting loads of quirky charm, a pair of likable leads, and confident direction from Jonathan Demme, Something Wild navigates its unpredictable tonal twists with room to spare.
Though it occasionally stumbles into sitcom territory, Something's Gotta Give is mostly a smart, funny romantic comedy, with sharp performances from Jack Nicholson, Diane Keaton, and Keanu Reeves.

movie_title: Sometimes a Great Notion (Never Give an Inch)

critics_consensus: It covers familiar territory for Sofia Coppola, but Somewhere remains a hypnotic, seductively pensive meditation on the nature of celebrity, anchored by charming performances from Stephen Dorff and Elle Fanning.
Sommersby stumbles as a consistently compelling mystery, but typically solid work from Jodie Foster and Richard Gere fuels an engaging romance.
Boris Karloff's final appearance as the Monster is a fitting farewell before the series descended into self-parody.
The faithful may find their spirits raised, but on purely cinematic terms, Son of God is too dull and heavy-handed to spark much fervor.
Undeniable heart and charming young leads save the film's nostalgic storyline from suffering at the hands predictability.
Overly frantic, painfully unfunny, and sorely missing the presence of Jim Carrey.
Roberto Benigni is an undeniably gifted physical comic, but the misguided Son of Pink Panther betrays his energetic efforts with a painfully unfunny script.
A heartfelt, affecting parable, The Song of Sparrows is another gem from Iranian director Majid Majidi.
Song of the Sea boasts narrative depth commensurate with its visual beauty, adding up to an animated saga overflowing with family-friendly riches.
The story may be a bit too melodramatic, but great performances abound in Songcatcher. The real reason to see the movie, however, is the hypnotic music.
It has a likable cast and loads of CGI spectacle, but for all but the least demanding viewers, The Sorcerer's Apprentice will be less than spellbinding.
A sloppy fratboy movie, Sorority Boys offers up a parade of gross-out gags and sex jokes, while insulting and ogling women.
Though it's slick and stylish, Sorority Row offers nothing new to the slasher genre and misses the mark both in its attempts at humor and thrills.
Robin Wright Penn and Abdel Kechiche's powerful performances aren't enough to keep the increasingly unbalanced Sorry, Haters from tottering completely off its axis.
Critics had a whole lot less than a truckload of good loving for this woefully misguided take on race in '80s America.
A raunchy sendup of Airplane! that never really takes off.
Featuring some incredible performances from many 70s soul legends, Soul Power is an exhilarating snap-shot of a bygone era.
There's an amazing true story at the heart of Soul Surfer -- and unfortunately, it's drowned by waves of Hollywood cheese.
Soul Survivors' stock characters and utter lack of suspense gives viewers little reason to attempt deciphering the confusing plot.
This documentary presents its opposing views in an even-handed yet emotionally engaging manner. Critics say it will provoke much thought, as well as emotions, in the audience.
Smart, affectionate, and unabashedly sincere, Sound City pairs a great soundtrack with a well-argued ode to one of rock 'n' roll's most fondly remembered bygone eras.
Unapologetically sweet and maybe even a little corny, The Sound of Music will win over all but the most cynical filmgoers with its classic songs and irresistible warmth.
Choppy logic and uneven performances are overshadowed by not-so-special effects that makes the suspension of disbelief a nearly impossible task.
Finding the human story amidst the action, director Duncan Jones and charming Jake Gyllenhaal craft a smart, satisfying sci-fi thriller.

movie_title: South of Heaven, West of Hell

critics_consensus: Its jokes are profoundly bold and rude but incredibly funny at the same time.
Southland Tales, while offering an intriguing vision of the future, remains frustratingly incoherent and unpolished.

movie_title: Southlander: Diary of a Desperate Musician

critics_consensus: While admittedly melodramatic and uneven in spots, Soylent Green ultimately succeeds with its dark, plausible vision of a dystopian future.

While the plot is overly cliched, the suberb acting by the stars (especially the tense interactions between Clint Eastwood and Tommy Lee Jones) and the spectacular special effects make this a movie worth seeing.
While it's no slam dunk, Space Jam's silly, Looney Toons-laden slapstick and vivid animation will leave younger viewers satisfied -- though accompanying adults may be more annoyed than entertained.
There's fine spoofery and amusing characters in Spaceballs, though it's a far cry from Mel Brooks' peak era.

movie_title: Spacehunter: Adventures in the Forbidden Zone

critics_consensus: Paz Vega shines, and Adam Sandler gives a performance of thoughtfulness and depth, but Spanglish is ultimately undermined by sitcommy plotting and unearned uplift.
The Spanish Prisoner delivers just what fans of writer-director David Mamet expect: a smart, solidly constructed drama that keeps viewers guessing... and entertained along the way.
While undeniably melodramatic and old-fashioned, Sparkle transcends its formulaic trappings thanks to Salim Akil's empathetic direction and strong performances from a committed cast.
A good cast and Mamet's mastery over the written language elevate an otherwise conventional thriller.
Spawn is an overbearing, over-violent film that adds little to the comic book adaptation genre.
This quirky indie comedy's low budget is readily apparent, but it's elevated by Michael Rapaport's dedicated performance.
Species shows flashes of the potential to blend exploitation and sci-fi horror in ingenious ways, but is ultimately mainly interested in flashing star Natasha Henstridge's skin.
Clumsily exploitative and sloppily assembled, Species II fails to clear the rather low bar set by its less-than-stellar predecessor.
A terrific popcorn thriller, Speed is taut, tense, and energetic, with outstanding performances from Keanu Reeves, Dennis Hopper, and Sandra Bullock.
Speed 2 falls far short of its predecessor, thanks to laughable dialogue, thin characterization, unsurprisingly familiar plot devices, and action sequences that fail to generate any excitement.
The Wachowski Brothers have overloaded Speed Racer with headache-inducing special effects, and neglected to develop a coherent storyline.
Sphere features an A-level cast working with B-grade material, with a story seen previously in superior science-fiction films.

Spice World's lack of cohesive plot will likely lose most viewers, but for fans of the titular girl group there's more than enough fun to be had in their wacky -- albeit superficial -- whirlwind of an adventure.
Not only does Spider-Man provide a good dose of web-swinging fun, it also has a heart, thanks to the combined charms of director Sam Raimi and star Tobey Maguire.
Boasting an entertaining villain and deeper emotional focus, this is a nimble sequel that improves upon the original.
Though there are more characters and plotlines, and the action sequences still dazzle, Spider-Man 3 nonetheless isn't quite as refined as the first two.

movie_title: Spiders, Part 1: The Golden Lake (Die Spinnen, 1. Teil - Der Goldene See)

critics_consensus: The Spiderwick Chronicles is an entertaining children's adventure, with heart and imagination to spare.

movie_title: Spine Tingler: The William Castle Story

critics_consensus: Both leaden and stilted, Spinning into Butter is an unsubtle drama with stagy direction and lackluster dialogue.
A visually stunning film that may be too predictable and politically correct for adults, but should serve children well.
Surreally goofy and entertaining for both children and their parents.
Despite occasional detours into surprisingly dark territory, Spread overall is an ineffectual celebration of vacuous Los Angeles high life rather than a deconstruction of it.
Spring Breakers blends stinging social commentary with bikini cheesecake and a bravura James Franco performance.
A visually stunning and contemplative piece of work.

movie_title: Springtime in a Small Town (Xiao cheng zhi chun)
critics_consensus: Director Tian Zhuangzhuang's remake of the 1948 Chinese classic may be too measured in pace for some audiences, but it's a visually sumptuous, well-acted piece.
A chaotic drug movie that has little substance behind the stylistic flash.
The outcome of the kinetic Spy Game is never in doubt, but it is fun watching Robert Redford and Brad Pitt work.
Leslie Nielsen's comic gifts are undisputed, but Spy Hard's lazy script and slapdash direction fail to take advantage of them.
A kinetic and fun movie that's sure to thrill children of all ages.

movie_title: Spy Kids 2: The Island of Lost Dreams
critics_consensus: Though the concept is no longer fresh, Spy Kids 2 is still an agreeable and energetic romp.
The movie will be found wanting if one is not taken in by the 3-D visuals.

movie_title: Spy Kids: All the Time in the World in 4D
critics_consensus: Burdened by a rote plot and unfunny scatological humor, All the Time in the World suggests that the Spy Kids franchise has run its course.
Lacking a script funny enough to cover up for Jackie Chan's fading physical gifts, The Spy Next Door fails on every conceivable level.
Though it hints at the absurdity to come in later installments, The Spy Who Loved Me's sleek style, menacing villains, and sly wit make it the best of the Roger Moore era.

movie_title: Square Grouper: The Godfathers of Ganja

critics_consensus: This is a piercingly honest, acidly witty look at divorce and its impact on a family.
St. Elmo's Fire is almost peak Brat Pack: it's got the cast, the fashion, and the music, but the characters are too frequently unlikable.
Both naughtier and campier than Ronald Searle's original post war series, this St. Trinian's leans on high jinks instead of performances or witty dialogue.

movie_title: St Trinian's II: The Legend of Fritton's Gold

critics_consensus: St. Vincent offers the considerable pleasure of seeing Bill Murray back in funny form, but drifts into dangerously sentimental territory along the way.
Uneven but enjoyable, Stage Beauty uses historical events as the springboard for a well-acted romance with a charming Shakespearean spin.
There might be a good movie to be made from mashing up the slasher and musical genres; unfortunately, Stage Fright isn't quite it.

Though the genre is well worn at this point, director Jim Mickle focuses on strong characterization and eerie atmosphere to craft an effective apocalyptic vampire chiller that also manages to pack a mean punch.
Stalag 17 survives the jump from stage to screen with flying colors, thanks to Billy Wilder's typically sterling direction and a darkly funny script.
There's no arguing with its impressive production values, but Stalingrad should have devoted more attention to the screenplay and spent less on special effects-enhanced spectacle.
Stand By Me is a wise, nostalgic movie with a weird streak that captures both Stephen King's voice and the trials of growing up.

movie_title: Stand Clear Of The Closing Doors
critics_consensus: Unassuming yet irrevocably absorbing, Stand Clear of the Closing Doors uses a refreshing perspective to explore universal themes.
Stand Up Guys largely wastes its talented cast in a resolutely mediocre comedy hampered by messy direction and a perfunctory script.
Well researched and finely crafted, Standard Operating Procedure is another gem from master documentarian Errol Morris.

movie_title: Standing in the Shadows of Motown
critics_consensus: A toe-tapping tribute to the band that gave Motown its sound.

movie_title: Stanley Kubrick: A Life in Pictures

critics_consensus: Star Trek reignites a classic franchise with action, humor, a strong story, and brilliant visuals, and will please traditional Trekkies and new fans alike.
While fans of the series will surely appreciate it, First Contact is exciting, engaging, and visually appealing enough to entertain Star Trek novices.
Generations stands as a mediocre changing of the guard for crews of the Enterprise, with a dull plot that sometimes seems like an expanded episode of the television series.

movie_title: Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan
critics_consensus: Considered by many fans to be the best of the Star Trek movies, Khan features a strong plot, increased tension, and a sharp supporting performance from Ricardo Montalban.

movie_title: Star Trek III - The Search for Spock
critics_consensus: Though it may be short on dazzling special effects, The Search for Spock is still a strong Star Trek installment, thanks to affecting performances by its iconic cast.
Although not terrible, the sluggishly paced Insurrection plays like an extended episode of the TV series.
Visually spectacular and suitably action packed, Star Trek Into Darkness is a rock-solid installment in the venerable sci-fi franchise, even if it's not as fresh as its predecessor.

movie_title: Star Trek IV - The Voyage Home
critics_consensus: Star Trek IV: The Voyage Home is perhaps the lightest and most purely enjoyable entry of the long-running series, emphasizing the eccentricities of the Enterprise's crew.
Nemesis has an interesting premise and some good action scenes, but the whole affair feels a bit tired.
Featuring a patchwork script and a dialogue-heavy storyline whose biggest villain is a cloud, Star Trek: The Motion Picture is a less-than-auspicious debut for the franchise.

movie_title: Star Trek V - The Final Frontier
critics_consensus: Filled with dull action sequences and an underdeveloped storyline, this fifth Trek movie is probably the worst of the series.

movie_title: Star Trek VI - The Undiscovered Country
critics_consensus: The Undiscovered Country is a strong cinematic send-off for the original Trek crew, featuring some remarkable visuals and an intriguing, character-driven mystery plot.

movie_title: Star Wars: Episode IV - A New Hope
critics_consensus: A legendarily expansive and ambitious start to the sci-fi saga, George Lucas opened our eyes to the possibilities of blockbuster filmmaking and things have never been the same.

movie_title: Star Wars: Episode I - The Phantom Menace
critics_consensus: Burdened by exposition and populated with stock characters, The Phantom Menace gets the Star Wars prequels off to a bumpy -- albeit visually dazzling -- start.

movie_title: Star Wars: Episode II - Attack of the Clones
critics_consensus: Star Wars Episode II: Attack of the Clones benefits from an increased emphasis on thrilling action, although they're once again undercut by ponderous plot points and underdeveloped characters.

movie_title: Star Wars: Episode III - Revenge of the Sith
critics_consensus: With Episode III: Revenge of the Sith, George Lucas brings his second Star Wars trilogy to a suitably thrilling and often poignant -- if still a bit uneven -- conclusion.

movie_title: Star Wars: Episode VI - Return of the Jedi
critics_consensus: Though failing to reach the cinematic heights of its predecessors, Return of the Jedi remains an entertaining sci-fi adventure and a fitting end to the classic trilogy.
A faithful interpretation that captures the spirit of whimsy, action, and off-kilter humor of Neil Gaiman, Stardust juggles multiple genres and tones to create a fantastical experience.
What initially begins as sci-fi transforms into a surprisingly sweet, offbeat drama, courtesy of John Carpenter's careful direction.
Smart, hard-hitting, and queasily realistic, Starred Up is an instant classic of U.K. prison cinema.
Starry Eyes pokes Hollywood's seedy underbelly to produce a refreshingly original horror story led by a breakout performance from Alex Essoe.
A fun movie...if you can accept the excessive gore and wooden acting.

movie_title: Starship Troopers 2: Hero of the Federation

critics_consensus: It's uneven and occasionally somewhat aimless, but Starsky & Hutch benefits from Stiller and Wilson's chemistry and a surprisingly warm-hearted script.

Starter For 10 is a spirited coming-of-age tale that remains charming and witty even as it veers into darker teritory. The unique setting of a quiz show makes the film wittier than your average romantic comedy.
Starting Out in the Evening features sharp dialogue and moving performances from the talented Frank Langella and Lili Taylor.
Startup.com is more than just a look at the rise and fall of the new economy. At its center is a friendship being tested to the limit, and that's what makes it worth viewing.
State and Main offers plenty of wit and laughs in its lampoons of the movie industry.
The movie bores despite a splendid performance by Michael Caine.
An inept drama that rings false.
A sweet and quirky film about a dwarf, a refreshment stand operator, and a reclusive artist connecting with one another.
A muddled brain-teaser, Stay has a solid cast and innovative visuals but little beneath the surface.
This sequel to Saturday Night Fever is shockingly embarrassing and unnecessary, trading the original's dramatic depth for a series of uninspired dance sequences.
Steal a Pencil For Me is a unique Holocaust story that pays tribute to the strength of the human spirit in the face of enormous hardship.
D'Onofrio's performance fails to do justice to Hoffman, and the depiction of the 60s also rings false.
There are laughs Stealing Harvard, but they are few and far between. Tom Green's antics grow old fast.
The story isn't the greatest, but there's an abundance of sci-fi eye candy to compensate.
A blue-collar drama with an uncommonly strong sense of its characters and setting, Steel City suggests a bright future for debuting writer-director Brian Jun.
Steel Magnolias has jokes and characters to spare, which makes it more dangerous (and effective) when it goes for the full melodrama by the end.
Steep is a mixed bag of breathtaking mountain footage and yawn-inducing banter.

movie_title: La sindrome di Stendhal (The Stendhal Syndrome)

critics_consensus: A perfect companion piece to The Endless Summer.
This trite teen romance has too little plot and not enough dancing.
There's a kinetic appeal to the handsome cast and their smooth moves, but everything else about Step Up 2 the Streets is been there, danced that.
It may not contain believable acting or a memorable plot, but Step Up 3-D delivers solid choreography and stunning visuals.
With slick choreography all too often interrupted by feeble attempts at plot, Step Up: All In would be more fun with all of its dialogue edited out.
Step Up Revolution treads familiar territory by surrounding its lively and kinetic dance sequences with a predictably generic story.
In exchanging the chilling satire of the original into mindless camp, this remake has itself become Stepford-ized.
Solid work from Julia Roberts and Susan Sarandon isn't enough to save Stepmom from a story whose manipulations dilute the effectiveness of a potentially affecting drama.
Poignant documentary that's hard to forget.
Director Jessica Bendinger is unable to transfer her winning Bring It On formula to the world of gymnastics, despite Missy Peregrym's strong lead performance.
The story is unconvincing and the acting is weak.
Still Crazy can't completely escape the shadow left by the classic rock mockumentaries of the past, but it earns a commendable number of laughs in its own right.
James Cromwell and GeneviÃ¨ve Bujold are outstanding in this tender, affecting, insightful drama about the bonds and sacrifices of marriage.
Kevin Bacon's acting is so genuine that it's creepy and director David Keopp knows how to create true suspense.

Its script doesn't quite carry the dramatic heft of his earlier work, but Park Chan-wook's Stoker showcases his eye for sumptuous imagery and his affection for dark, atmospheric narratives populated by mysterious characters.
A real-life whodunit with colorful characters, especially art detective Harold Smith, this documentary is a fascinating peek into the world of art collecting.
Stolen Summer feels like a sugary after-school special stretched out to feature length.
While Stomp the Yard contains impressive musical and dance numbers, it loses its momentum during the intervening soap opera-style subplots.

Stone boasts a cast that includes Robert De Niro, Edward Norton, and Milla Jovovich, and it features strong dialogue, but it's ultimately undone by its heavy-handed symbolism and overabundant plot twists.
Poorly cast and sloppily assembled, Stoned turns one of rock 'n' roll's most darkly fascinating mysteries into a cinematic tragedy all its own.
The Stoning of Soraya M. nearly transcends its deficiencies through the sheer strength of its subject material, but ultimately drowns out its message with an inappropriately heavy-handed approach.
Stop-Loss is sincere and complex, and features strong performances, even if it tries to cover too much ground.
Jonathan Demme's Stop Making Sense captures the energetic, unpredictable live act of peak Talking Heads with color and visual wit.

movie_title: Stop! Or My Mom Will Shoot
critics_consensus: Thoroughly witless and thuddingly unfunny, Stop! Or My Mom Will Shoot gives its mismatched stars very little to work with - and as a result, they really don't work.
In Stories We Tell, Sarah Polley plays with the documentary format to explore the nature of memory and storytelling, crafting a thoughtful, compelling narrative that unfolds like a mystery.

movie_title: Story of a Love Affair (Cronaca di un amore)

critics_consensus: A lack of chemistry between Bruce Willis and Michelle Pfeiffer fatally undermines the dull and predictable Story of Us.

movie_title: The Story of Vernon and Irene Castle

critics_consensus: Todd Solondz's Storytelling boasts an audacious narrative structure, but fails to deliver on the mechanics of its namesake, yielding a creative exercise that is more interested in satisfying the author's interests than the audience's investment.
Slow-paced but heart-warming.
Straight Jacket succeeds in its moments of lighthearted comedy, but ultimately collapses under the weight of its serious -- and clumsily imparted -- messages.

movie_title: Stranded: I Have Come from a Plane That Crashed on the Mountains
critics_consensus: Stranded is a thoroughly uplifting account of the well-known tragedy, with touching testimony from remaining survivors.

movie_title: The Strange Affair of Uncle Harry (Guilty of Murder?)

critics_consensus: Though lowbrow in intent and outcome, Strange Brew effectively mines laughs from its unique premise and likeable stars.

movie_title: The Strange Love of Martha Ivers
Strange Powers: Stephin Merritt And The Magnetic Fields

critics_consensus: Strange Wilderness is a laugh-free comedy that's both aimless and overly crass.
A disappointing misfire for director Sidney Lumet, A Stranger Among Us tries to tell a murder mystery and a fish-out-of-water love story, doing a disservice to both.
Sexy, smart, and darkly humorous, Stranger by the Lake offers rewarding viewing for adult filmgoers in search of thought-provoking drama.

A fun, whimsical tale about an office drone trying to save his life from his narrator, Stranger Than Fiction features a subdued performances from Will Ferrell that contributes mightily to its quirky, mind-bending affect.
This remake streamlines the plot but ultimately makes a fatal mistake: It celebrates violence.

movie_title: Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun-Li
critics_consensus: The combination of a shallow plot and miscast performers renders Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun Li a perfectly forgettable video game adaptation.
Street Kings contains formulaic violence but no shred of intelligence.
Streets of Fire may sometimes buckle under the strain of its ambitious fusion of disparate genres, but Walter Hill's bravura style gives this motorcycle musical fuel to burn.
Weighed down by a rote story and passionless performances, Striking Distance represents one of the lesser '90s genre outings from action hero Bruce Willis.
A raucous military comedy that features Bill Murray and his merry cohorts approaching the peak of their talents.
Striptease can't decide whether it is a lurid thriller or a sexy satire - which becomes a moot point as it proves disastrously incapable of pulling either off.
Critics say Stuart Little is charming with kids and adults for its humor and visual effects.
Stuart Little 2 is a sweet, visually impressive sequel that provides wholesome entertainment for kids.
Steeped in gallows humor, Stuck is a taut, tense examination of a tragic accident.
It struggles to enliven its uneven script, but Stuck in Love boasts enough winning performances from its solid veteran cast to offer an appealing diversion for rom-com enthusiasts.
An unusually sweet and charming comedy by the Farrelly brothers. Fans may miss the distinct lack of bodily fluids though.
The Stunt Man is a preposterously entertaining thriller with a clever narrative and Oscar-worthy (nomination, at least!) Peter O'Toole performance.
Funny, stylish, and ringing with adolescent truth, Submarine marks Richard Ayoade as a talent to watch.
It's technically impressive and loaded with eye-catching images, but without characters or a plot to support them, all of Sucker Punch's visual thrills are for naught.
Sudden Impact delivers all the firepower -- and the most enduring catchphrase -- fans associate with the Dirty Harry franchise, but it's far from the best film in the series.

Though this cheerleader comedy has an intriguing premise, it's too empty-headed and saddled with too many lame jokes to live up to it. Also, some critics say the movie is irresponsible in its depiction of teens and guns.
Inventive and off-kilter, the newest feast from J-Horror director Takashi Miike is super-sensory, self-referential and somewhat excessive.
A slick and well-made thriller that takes on new weight due to the current political climate.
Family drama mixes with virtual online action in the breezy and entertaining Summer Wars.
A cliched and predictable sports comedy that's mostly devoid of excitement or laughs, Summer Catch is strictly bush-league.
Olivier Assayas' contemplative family drama handles lofty ideas about art and culture with elegance and lightness.
It boasts beautiful scenery, but in every other respect, Summer in February is a painfully bland period drama.
Spike Lee offers intense visuals but his storytelling feels crowded and overambitious.
With A Summer's Tale, Eric Rohmer continues his "Tales of the Four Seasons" in typically Rohmeresque fashion -- and for cineastes, that's excellent news indeed.
It doesn't offer much in the way of uplift, but Sunlight Jr.'s grim storyline is offset by Laurie Collyer's empathetic screenplay and strong performances from Naomi Watts and Matt Dillon.

movie_title: Sunrise: A Song of Two Humans
critics_consensus: Boasting masterful cinematography to match its well-acted, wonderfully romantic storyline, Sunrise is perhaps the final -- and arguably definitive -- statement of the silent era.
Arguably the greatest movie about Hollywood, Billy Wilder's masterpiece Sunset Boulevard is a tremendously entertaining combination of noir, black comedy, and character study.

Danny Boyle continues his descent into mind-twisting sci-fi madness, taking us along for the ride. Sunshine fulfills the dual requisite necessary to become classic sci-fi: dazzling visuals with intelligent action.
Despite a sometimes overly familiar plot, Sunshine Cleaning benefits from the lively performances of its two stars.
Wonderfully acted, but the story and pacing can use a little work.
Super's intriguing premise and talented cast are drowned in a blood-red sea of graphic violence, jarring tonal shifts, and thinly written characters.
It may evoke memories of classic summer blockbusters a little too eagerly for some, but Super 8 has thrills, visual dazzle, and emotional depth to spare.
A startling lack of taste pervades Superbabies, a sequel offering further proof that bad jokes still aren't funny when coming from the mouths of babes.
Entertaining doc about the adverse effects of eating fast food.
A more-miss -than-hit affair, Super Troopers will most likely appeal to those looking for something silly.

Deftly balancing vulgarity and sincerity while placing its protagonists in excessive situations, Superbad is an authentic take on friendship and the overarching awkwardness of the high school experience.
Blending hand-to-hand combat with breathtaking stunts and slapstick comedy, Supercop reminds us why Jackie Chan is one of the world's great entertainers.
While it showcases some cool stunts, Supercross feels like an infomercial for its titular sport, with undeveloped characters and a shopworn plot.
The effects are cheesy and Supergirl's wide-eyed, cheery heroine simply isn't interesting to watch for an hour and a half.
The humor occasionally stumbles into slapstick territory, and the special effects are dated, but Superman II meets, if not exceeds, the standard set by its predecessor.
When not overusing sight gags, slapstick, and Richard Pryor, Superman III resorts to plot points rehashed from the previous Superman flicks.

movie_title: Superman IV: The Quest for Peace
critics_consensus: The Superman series bottoms out here: the action is boring, the special effects look cheaper, and none of the actors appear interested in where the plot's going.
Man of Steel's exhilarating action and spectacle can't fully overcome its detours into generic blockbuster territory.
Bryan Singer's reverent and visually decadent adaptation gives the Man of Steel welcome emotional complexity. The result: a satisfying stick-to-your-ribs adaptation.
Superman deftly blends humor and gravitas, taking advantage of the perfectly cast Christopher Reeve to craft a loving, nostalgic tribute to an American pop culture icon.

movie_title: Supermensch: The Legend of Shep Gordon
critics_consensus: Its unabashedly positive tone may strike some viewers as disingenuous, but even if Supermensch doesn't tell the whole story, it's an undeniably entertaining one.

Surf's Up is a laid back, visually stunning animated movie that brings a fresh twist to some familiar conventions. Its witty mockumentary format is fun and inventive, and the CGI is breathtakingly realistic.
An intriguing account of a unique family.
This dark psycho-thriller from Jennifer Lynch, is violent, sharp and baffling, but not to everyone's taste.
Survival of the Dead offers glimmers of Romero's savage wit, but not nearly enough to make up for his unusually uninspired directing and a lack of new ideas
Surviving Christmas is unpleasant characters attacking each other for 90 minutes before delivering a typical, hollow anti-consumerist message
Other than Ben Kingsley, there's not much to like in this preposterous thriller.
Suspended Animation offers some gory good fun for genre fans, even if the end results don't quite transcend their cheerfully shallow roots.
Unabashedly campy -- often to its detriment -- Swamp Thing is not without its charms, among them Adrienne Barbeau as the damsel in distress.
A competent, but routine police thriller.

movie_title: Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street
critics_consensus: Full of pith and Grand Guignol grossness, this macabre musical is perfectly helmed and highly entertaining. Tim Burton masterfully stages the musical in a way that will make you think he has done this many times before.
Director Atom Egoyan examines tragedy and its aftermath with intelligence and empathy.
Reese Witherspoon is charming enough, but the road to Alabama is well-traveled.
Finding the right balance between subtle and sentimental, Sweet Land moves beyond other similarly-themed dramas with evocative cinematography that plays an equal role to the talented cast.
A bleak, but heartbreaking coming-of-age tale that resonates with truth.
Sweet Smell of Success boasts a top-notch cast, sharp direction, atmospheric cinematography, and an appropriately jazzy score, making it one of the best noir crime thrillers ever made.
A collection of hit-or-miss gags tied together by a thin plot.

movie_title: Swept Away (Travolti da un Insolito Destino nell'Azzurro Mare d'Agosto)

critics_consensus: It aims for pulpy noir thrills, but Swerve never lives up to the twisty promise of its title.
A Fatal Attraction rip-off, Swimfan is a predictable, mediocre thriller.
